{"title_page": "Orange Is the New Black", "text_new": "{{short description|American comedy-drama television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Orange Is the New Black\n| image                    = Orange is the new Black.png\n| genre                    = [[Comedy-drama]]\n| creator                  = [[Jenji Kohan]]\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Orange Is the New Black: My Year in a Women's Prison]]''|[[Piper Kerman]]}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Holly the homo]]\n* [[Kacee Gibbs the raging Homo]]\n* [[Taylor Schilling]]\n* [[Laura Prepon]]\n* [[Michael Harney]]\n* [[Michelle Hurst]]\n* [[Kate Mulgrew]]\n* [[Jason Biggs]]\n* [[Uzo Aduba]]\n* [[Danielle Brooks]]\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]]\n* [[Taryn Manning]]\n* [[Selenis Leyva]]\n* [[Adrienne C. Moore]]\n* [[Dascha Polanco]]\n* [[Nick Sandow]]\n* [[Yael Stone]]\n* [[Samira Wiley]]\n* [[Jackie Cruz]]\n* [[Lea DeLaria]]\n* [[Elizabeth Rodriguez]]\n* [[Jessica Pimentel]]\n* [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]]\n* Matt Peters\n* [[Dale Soules]]\n* [[Alysia Reiner]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Regina Spektor]]\n| opentheme                = \"[[You've Got Time]]\"\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Scott Doherty\n* Brandon Jay\n* [[Gwendolyn Sanford]]\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 7\n| num_episodes             = 91\n| list_episodes            = List of Orange Is the New Black episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jenji Kohan\n* [[Liz Friedman]] (pilot)\n* [[Sara Hess]]\n* Tara Herrmann\n* Lisa Vinnecour\n* Neri Kyle Tannenbaum\n* Mark A. Burley\n}}\n| producer                 = Neri Kyle Tannenbaum\n| location                 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 51\u201393 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* Tilted Productions\n* [[Lionsgate Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = {{Plainlist|\n* Lionsgate Television\n* [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n}}\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[1080p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n* [[4K resolution|4K]]\n}}\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital Plus]] 5.1 with [[Descriptive Video Service]] track\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2013|7|11}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2019|7|26}}\n| website                  = http://www.netflix.com/orangeisthenewblack\n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n}}\n\n'''''Orange Is the New Black''''' (sometimes abbreviated to '''''OITNB''''') is an American [[comedy-drama]] [[web television]] series created by [[Jenji Kohan]] for [[Netflix]].<ref name=Dunne>{{cite news |last=Dunne |first=Susan |title=Danbury Women's Prison Setting For Netflix Original Series |url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-07-03/entertainment/hc-orange-is-the-new-black-0707-20130703_1_kerman-drug-operation-prison-staff |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |newspaper=The Hartford Courant |date=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"duocast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/09/duo-cast-in-netflixs-orange-is-the-new-black-don-stark-upped-on-vhs-bounce/ |title=Duo Cast in Netflix's 'Orange Is The New Black', Don Stark Upped on VH's 'Bounce' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=September 17, 2012 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> The series is based on [[Piper Kerman]]'s memoir, ''[[Orange Is the New Black: My Year in a Women's Prison]]'' (2010), about her experiences at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Danbury|FCI Danbury]], a minimum-security [[federal prison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/08/06/piper-kerman-orange-is-the-new-black-interview_n_3714601.html |title=Piper Kerman, 'Orange Is The New Black' Author: What's Real, What's Not About Netflix Show |date=August 6, 2013 |website=HuffPost Canada |access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref> Produced by Tilted Productions in association with [[Lionsgate Television]], ''Orange Is the New Black'' premiered on Netflix on July 11, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-orange-new-black-premiere-date-jenji-kohan-448610 |title=Netflix Sets Premiere Date for Jenji Kohan's 'Orange Is the New Black' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=April 30, 2013 |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> In February 2016, the series was renewed for a fifth, sixth, and seventh season.<ref name=\"rating\" /> On October 17, 2018, it was confirmed that the seventh season, which was released on July 26, 2019, would be its last.<ref name=\"end\" /><ref name=\"S7ReleaseDate\" />\n\n''Orange Is the New Black'' has become Netflix's most-watched original series.<ref name=\"rating\" /><ref name=\"rating2\" /> It was widely acclaimed throughout its run, and has received many accolades. For its first season, the series garnered 12 [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]], winning three. A new Emmy rule in 2015 forced the series to change categories from comedy to drama.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/16/8976181/emmys-nominations-comedy-drama |title=7 Emmys rules and quirks that explain the 2015 nominations |first=Emily |last=VanDerWerff |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> For its second season, the series received four Emmy nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], and [[Uzo Aduba]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]]. ''Orange Is the New Black'' is the first series to score Emmy nominations in both comedy and drama categories.<ref name=\"Birnbaum\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jenji-kohan-orange-is-the-new-black-showrunner-1201555759/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Boss Jenji Kohan on Running the Show Her Way |website=Variety |first=Debra |last=Birnbaum |date=August 4, 2015 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> The series has also received six [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations, six [[Writers Guild of America Award]] nominations, a [[Producers Guild of America Award]], an [[American Film Institute]] award, and a [[Peabody Award]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{Main|List of Orange Is the New Black episodes}}\n{{:List of Orange Is the New Black episodes}}\n{{expand section|with=Main storyline(s) of seasons 1\u20134|date=August 2018}}\n\nThe series begins revolving around [[Piper Chapman]] ([[Taylor Schilling]]), a woman in her thirties living in New York City who is sentenced to 15 months in Litchfield Penitentiary, a [[Prison#Security|minimum-security]] women's [[federal prison]] in [[upstate New York]]. Chapman was convicted of transporting a suitcase full of drug money for her girlfriend [[Alex Vause]] ([[Laura Prepon]]), an international [[Illegal drug trade|drug smuggler]]. The offense had occurred 10 years before the start of the series and in that time Chapman had moved on to a quiet, law-abiding life among New York's [[upper middle class]]. Her sudden and unexpected indictment disrupts her relationships with her fianc\u00e9, family and friends. In prison, Chapman is reunited with Vause (who named Chapman in her trial, resulting in Chapman's arrest), and they re-examine their relationship. Simultaneously, Chapman, along with the other inmates, attempt to grapple with prison's numerous, inherent struggles. Episodes often feature [[flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]] of significant events from various inmates' and prison guards' pasts. These flashbacks typically depict how an inmate came to be in prison or develop a character's backstory. The prison is initially operated by the \"Federal Department of Corrections\" (a fictional version of the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]), and was in a later season acquired by the Management & Correction Corporation (MCC), a private prison company.\n\nThe fifth season shows the prisoners revolting against the guards, wardens and the system after MCC's failed handling of an inmate's death at the hands of a guard in the fourth season. The inmate death had followed a peaceful protest and subsequent instigation of an inmate fight by another guard. Fueled by the conditions the inmates are forced to tolerate, as well as grudges against the prison guards, a three-day riot ensues. During the riot, some inmates attempt to negotiate better living conditions and seek justice for the death of the inmate, while others pursue their own interests and entertainment, and a few seek no involvement. At the emergence of the riot, the guard who incited the fight in the prior season is critically wounded by an inmate who took the gun the guard illegally brought into the prison. At the end of the season, [[SWAT]] raids the prison to end the riot and remove all inmates from the facility. During this raid, a correctional officer is fatally wounded by a corrupt \"strike team\", which then conspires to blame the guard's death on inmates who hid in an underground bunker and had taken the guard hostage. All inmates are transported to other prisons.\n\nThe consequences of the riot are shown in the sixth season. A number of the inmates, including Chapman and Vause, are transported to Litchfield Maximum Security. Most of these inmates are interrogated, and several of them charged and sentenced for their involvement in the riot. In max, new inmates are introduced, alliances are made, and a gang-like war emerges between two prison blocks, spearheaded by a longstanding feud between two sisters and a grudge harbored by them toward a former maximum-security inmate who returned as a consequence of the riot (she had been moved to the minimum security prison). Inmates who arrived from the minimum security prison are either caught up or willingly participate in the war between prison blocks. The season portrays further corruption and guard brutality.\n\nThe seventh season provides an ending to various inmate's stories. Chapman and Vause continue their on/off again relationship. The season shows how some prisoners are able to move beyond their time in prison while others are captured by the system and through their own flaws and/or systemic problems in the structure of US society and its \u201cjustice\u201d system are unable to progress. In addition to the established setting of Litchfield Max, a significant portion of the season takes place in a newly created [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] detention centre for detained presumed illegal immigrants, showing their struggles and lack of access to outside help in large part because of complete or extreme disregard of the law. \n\nThroughout the series, it is shown how various forms of corruption, funding cuts by the corporate owner to increase profit by millions, [[private prison|privatization of prison]], overcrowding, guard brutality and racial discrimination (among other issues), affect the prisoners' safety, health and well-being; the correctional officers\u2019 lives; and the prison's basic inability to fulfill its fundamental legal responsibilities and ethical obligations as a corrections institution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Terry|first=April|date=July 2016|title=Surveying Issues That Arise in Women's Prisons: A Content Critique of Orange Is the New Black: OITNB: Women's Prisons|journal=Sociology Compass|volume=10|issue=7|pages=553\u2013566|doi=10.1111/soc4.12388}}</ref> One of the show's key conflicts involves the minimum-security prison's Director of Human Activities (aka the warden, under privatization nomenclature), Joe Caputo, whose efforts and aims as a [[Prison warden|warden]] constantly conflict with the corporate interests of MCC, which acquired the facility when it was about to be shut down. This theme is continued when a new forward-thinking & caring warden is hired at the maximum security prison, and unlike Caputo actually institutes educational programs and positive changes. She is fired for these actions and her attitude toward the corporate corruption, although her short-lived changes have profound positive results.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Orange Is the New Black characters}}\n\n===Main cast===\n<!-- Main cast is determined by opening credits billing, not popularity or episode count -->\n{{div col}}\n* [[Taylor Schilling]] as [[Piper Chapman]]\n* [[Laura Prepon]] as [[Alex Vause]], inmate  {{Small|(seasons 1, 3\u20137; recurring season 2)}}\n* [[Michael Harney]] as Sam Healy, correctional officer {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134; guest season 6 and 7)}}{{efn|Michael J. Harney was credited as main cast for season 5 but did not make an appearance.}}\n* [[Michelle Hurst]] as Miss Claudette Pelage, inmate {{Small|(season 1)}}\n* [[Kate Mulgrew]] as Galina \"Red\" Reznikov, inmate\n* [[Jason Biggs]] as Larry Bloom, Piper's fianc\u00e9 {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 5; recurring season 7)}}\n* [[Uzo Aduba]] as [[Crazy Eyes (character)|Suzanne \"Crazy Eyes\" Warren]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Danielle Brooks]] as Tasha \"Taystee\" Jefferson, inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]] as [[Nicky Nichols]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Taryn Manning]] as [[Tiffany Doggett|Tiffany \"Pennsatucky\" Doggett]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Selenis Leyva]] as Gloria Mendoza, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Adrienne C. Moore]] as Cindy \"Black Cindy\" Hayes, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Dascha Polanco]] as Dayanara \"Daya\" Diaz, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Nick Sandow]] as Joe Caputo, Captain of the Guard, later warden {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Yael Stone]] as [[Lorna Morello]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Samira Wiley]] as [[Poussey Washington]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134; recurring seasons 1\u20132; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* [[Jackie Cruz]] as Marisol \"Flaca\" Gonzales, inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Lea DeLaria]] as Carrie \"Big Boo\" Black, inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; recurring seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Elizabeth Rodriguez]] as Aleida Diaz, former inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Jessica Pimentel]] as Maria Ruiz, inmate {{Small|(seasons 5\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]] as Blanca Flores, inmate {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20135)}}\n* Matt Peters as Joel Luschek, correctional officer {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20135)}}\n* [[Dale Soules]] as Frieda Berlin, inmate {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 2\u20135)}}\n* [[Alysia Reiner]] as Natalie \"Fig\" Figueroa, warden {{Small|(season 7; recurring 1\u20133, 5\u20136; guest season 4)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Recurring cast===\n{{Main|List of recurring Orange Is the New Black characters}}\n\n====Inmates====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Laverne Cox]] as Sophia Burset {{Small|(seasons 1\u20136, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Diane Guerrero]] as Maritza Ramos {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* [[Annie Golden]] as Norma Romano {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Vicky Jeudy]] as Janae Watson {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Julie Lake]] as Angie Rice {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Emma Myles]] as Leanne Taylor {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Abigail Savage]] as Gina Murphy {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Constance Shulman]] as Yoga Jones {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lori Tan Chinn]] as Mei Chang {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Tamara Torres as Emily \"Weeping Woman\" Germann {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lin Tucci]] as Anita DeMarco {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Beth Fowler]] as Sister Jane Ingalls {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Barbara Rosenblat]] as [[Miss Rosa|Rosa \"Miss Rosa\" Cisneros]] {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 3)}}\n* [[Madeline Brewer]] as Tricia Miller {{Small|(season 1)}}\n* [[Kimiko Glenn]] as Brook Soso {{Small|(seasons 2\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lori Petty]] as Lolly Whitehill {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134, 6\u20137; guest season 2)}}\n* Yvette Freeman as Irma Lerman {{Small|(season 2; guest season 3)}}\n* [[Lorraine Toussaint]] as Yvonne \"Vee\" Parker {{Small|(season 2)}}\n* [[Blair Brown]] as Judy King {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Emily Althaus as Maureen Kukudio {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* [[Ruby Rose]] as Stella Carlin {{Small|(season 3; guest season 4)}}\n* Daniella De Jesus as Irene \"Zirconia\" Cabrera {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Shannon Esper as Alana Dwight {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Rosal Colon as Carmen \"Ouija\" Aziza {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* Francesca Curran as Helen \"Skinhead Helen\" Van Maele {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* [[Kelly Karbacz]] as Kasey Sankey {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Amanda Stephen as Alison Abdullah {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Asia Kate Dillon]] as Brandy Epps {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Miriam Morales as Ramona \"Pidge\" Contreras {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* [[Jolene Purdy]] as Stephanie Hapakuka {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Shirley Roeca as Juanita Vasquez {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137, guest season 5)}}\n* Rebecca Knox as Tina Swope {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Sipiwe Moyo as Adeola Chinede {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Besanya Santiago as Raquel \"Creech\" Munoz {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Finnerty Steeves as Beth Hoefler {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Christina Toth as Annalisa Damiva {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Amanda Fuller]] as Madison \"Badison\" Murphy {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Vicci Martinez]] as Dominga \"Daddy\" Duarte {{Small|(seasons 6, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Mackenzie Phillips]] as Barbara \"Barb\" Denning {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Henny Russell as Carol Denning {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Ismenia Mendes as Tali Grapes {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Staff====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Catherine Curtin]] as Wanda Bell {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* Joel Marsh Garland as Scott O'Neill {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* Brendan Burke as Wade Donaldson {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Pablo Schreiber]] as George \"Pornstache\" Mendez {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* Lolita Foster as Eliqua Maxwell {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* Germar Terrell Gardner as Charles Ford {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Matt McGorry]] as John Bennett {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Lauren Lapkus]] as Susan Fischer {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 7)}}\n* Kaipo Schwab as Igme Dimaguiba {{Small|(season 1; guest seasons 2\u20134)}}\n* James McMenamin as Charlie \"Donuts\" Coates {{Small|(seasons 3\u20136)}}\n* [[Alan Aisenberg]] as Baxter \"Gerber\" Bayley {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* Jimmy Gary Jr. as Felix Rikerson {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* [[Mike Birbiglia]] as Danny Pearson {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134)}}\n* [[Marsha Stephanie Blake]] as Berdie Rogers {{Small|(season 3)}}\n* [[Beth Dover]] as Linda Ferguson {{Small| (seasons 4\u20137; guest season 3)}}\n* Nick Dillenburg as Ryder Blake {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Mike Houston as Lee Dixon {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* [[Emily Tarver]] as Artesian McCullough {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* [[Brad William Henke]] as Desi Piscatella {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* Evan Arthur Hall as B. Stratman {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* John Palladino as Josh {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Michael Torpey as Thomas \"Humps\" Humphrey {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Hunter Emery as Rick Hopper {{Small|(seasons 5\u20137)}}\n* Shawna Hamic as Virginia \"Ginger\" Copeland {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Susan Heyward]] as Tamika Ward {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Josh Segarra]] as Danilo Stefanovic {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Greg Vrotsos as Greg Hellman {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Nicholas Webber as J. Alvarez {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Branden Wellington as Jarod Young {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Adam Lindo as Carlos \"Clitvack\" Litvack {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Others====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Michael Chernus]] as Cal Chapman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134, 7; guest season 6)}}\n* [[Tanya Wright]] as Crystal Burset {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134; guest season 6)}}\n* Berto Colon as Cesar Velazquez {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133, 7; guest season 5)}}\n* [[Deborah Rush]] as Carol Chapman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* [[Tracee Chimo]] as Neri Feldman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133, 7)}}\n* [[Maria Dizzia]] as Polly Harper {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 7)}}\n* Ian Paola as Yadriel {{Small|(seasons 2\u20135; guest season 7)}}\n* [[John Magaro]] as Vince Muccio {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135, 7)}}\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]] as Delia Mendez-Powell {{Small|(season 3; guest season 5)}}\n* Miguel Izaguirre as Dario \"Diablo\" Z\u00fa\u00f1iga {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; guest seasons 1, 4\u20135)}}\n* [[Michael J. Burg]] as Detective Mark Bellamy {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Bill Hoag as Bill Chapman {{Small|(season 7; guest seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Karina Arroyave]] as Karla C\u00f3rdova {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* Melinna Bobadilla as Santos Chaj {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* [[Marie-Lou Nahhas]] as Shani Abboud {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* [[Alicia Witt]] as Zelda {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Cast of Orange Is The New Black at Paley Fest.jpg|thumb|right|The series cast at The Paley Center For Media's PaleyFest 2014 event honoring the show]]\n\nShow creator [[Jenji Kohan]] read [[Piper Kerman]]'s memoir after a friend sent it to her. She then set up a meeting with Kerman to pitch her on a TV adaptation, which she notes she \"screwed up\" as she spent most of the time asking Kerman about her experiences she described in the book rather than selling her on the show. This appealed to Kerman as it let her know that she was a fan and she signed off on the adaptation.<ref name=\"Collidermay\">{{cite web |last1=Radish |first1=Christina |title=Creator Jenji Kohan Talks ORANGE IS THE NEW BLACK, Her Research Into Prison Life, and Graphic Sex Scenes |url=https://collider.com/jenji-kohan-orange-is-the-new-black-interview/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref> Kohan would later go on to describe the main character, [[Piper Chapman]], as a \"trojan horse\" for the series, allowing it to focus on characters whose demographics would not normally be represented on TV.<ref>{{cite web |title='Orange' Creator Jenji Kohan: 'Piper Was My Trojan Horse' |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/08/13/211639989/orange-creator-jenji-kohan-piper-was-my-trojan-horse |publisher=NPR |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, it was revealed that Netflix was in negotiations with Lionsgate for a 13-episode TV adaptation of Kerman's memoirs with Kohan as creator.<ref name=\"based\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/07/netflix-eyeing-second-original-series-comedy-from-weeds-creator-jenji-kohan/ |title=Netflix Eyeing Second Original Series \u2013 Comedy From ''Weeds'' Creator Jenji Kohan |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> In November 2011, negotiations were finalized and the series had been [[Green-light|greenlit]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/11/netflix-lionsgate-tv-closing-deal-for-jenji-kohans-orange-is-the-new-black-comedy/ |title=Netflix, Lionsgate TV Closing Deal For Jenji Kohan's 'Orange Is The New Black' Comedy |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 11, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> Kohan had initially wanted to cast [[Katie Holmes]] in the role of Piper Chapman, and met with the actress to discuss it, but Holmes had other commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/08/06/katie-holmes-almost-starred-in-orange-is-the-new-black/|title=Katie Holmes almost starred in 'Orange is the New Black'|website=[[New York Post]]|date=August 6, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Casting announcements began in August 2012 with [[Taylor Schilling]], the first to be cast, as Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/08/taylor-schilling-to-star-in-jenji-kohans-netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title=Taylor Schilling To Star in Jenji Kohan's Netflix Series ''Orange Is The New Black'' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=August 30, 2012 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=August 30, 2012}}</ref> followed by [[Jason Biggs]] as Piper's fianc\u00e9 Larry Bloom.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jason-biggs-netflix-orange-new-black-jenji-kohan-weeds-369610 |title=Jason Biggs to Co-Star in Netflix's 'Orange Is the New Black' (Exclusive) |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=September 12, 2012 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Laura Prepon]] and [[Yael Stone]] were next to join the series, as [[Alex Vause]] and [[Lorna Morello]], respectively.<ref name=\"duocast\" /> [[Abigail Savage]], who plays Gina, and [[Alysia Reiner]], who plays Fig, had auditioned for role of Alex Vause.<ref name=\"Collidermay\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/07/orange-is-the-new-black-fig-interview.html |title=Orange Is the New Black's Fig Explains the 'Beer Can' Scene |website=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |first=E. Alex |last=Jung |date=July 9, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Prepon initially auditioned for Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/16/big-boo-orange-is-the-new-black_n_3768682.html |title=Big Boo Wasn't Originally Supposed To Be A Part Of 'Orange Is The New Black' (VIDEO) |website=HuffPost |date=August 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> however Kohan felt she would not worry about her [in prison], noting a \"toughness and a presence to her that wasn't right for the character.\" Kohan instead gave her the role of Alex.<ref name=\"Collidermay\" /> Stone had originally auditioned for the role of [[Nicky Nichols]], but she was not considered \"tough enough\" for the character;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jul/06/yael-stone-on-orange-is-the-new-black-i-wasnt-sapphic-enough-to-play-nicky |title=Yael Stone on Orange is the New Black: 'I wasn't Sapphic enough to play Nicky' |website=[[The Guardian]] |first=Steve |last=Down |date=July 5, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> she was asked to audition for Lorna Morello instead.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> Likability was important for Morello, whom casting director Jen Euston deemed \"a very helpful, nice, sweet Italian girl.\"<ref name=\"Orley\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyorley/how-the-orange-is-the-new-black-cast-came-to-be |title=How The \"Orange Is The New Black\" Cast Came To Be |website=BuzzFeed |first=Emily |last=Orley |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Natasha Lyonne]] was to audition for Alex, but was asked to read for the character Nicky Nichols; \"[Kohan knew] she could do Nicky with her eyes closed. She was perfect,\" said Euston.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> [[Laverne Cox]], a black [[transgender]] woman, was cast as Sophia Burset, a transgender character. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' touted ''Orange Is the New Black'' as possibly the first women-in-prison narrative to cast a transgender woman for this type of role.<ref name=\"Anderson full\">{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Diane |url=http://www.advocate.com/print-issue/current-issue/2013/07/10/why-you-should-watch-orange-new-black?page=full |title=Why You Should Watch 'Orange Is the New Black' |website=The Advocate |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> [[Uzo Aduba]] read for the part of Janae Watson but was offered the character [[Suzanne Warren|Suzanne \"Crazy Eyes\" Warren]].<ref name=\"Orley\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/orange-is-the-new-blacks-uzo-aduba-how-would-make-someone-think-id-be-right-for-crazy-eyes/news-story/7b8dda54c824f6a17d9fed7c73c917a0 |title=Orange Is The New Black's Uzo Aduba: 'How would make someone think I'd be right for Crazy Eyes?' |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |first=Holly |last=Byrnes |date=December 18, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Taryn Manning was offered the role of Tiffany \"Pennsatucky\" Doggett.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> ''[[This American Life]]'' host [[Ira Glass]] was offered a role as a [[Public broadcasting#Radio|public radio]] [[radio host|host]], but he declined. The role instead went to [[Robert Stanton (actor)|Robert Stanton]], who plays the fictional host Maury Kind.<ref>{{cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/ira-glass-politely-declined-role-orange-new-black-110491 |title=Ira Glass 'Politely Declined' Role on 'Orange Is the New Black' |publisher=The Wrap |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Orange is the New Black'' is set in a fictional minimum-security prison in [[Litchfield, New York]], which is a real town in upstate New York, but it does not have a federal penitentiary.<ref name=WIBX>{{cite web |title=Is the 'Orange is New Black' Prison Real? Yes, and it is Located Near Utica |url=http://wibx950.com/orange-is-new-black-prison-is-located-near-utica/ |publisher=WIBX 950 AM |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref> The series began filming in the former Rockland Children's Psychiatric Center in [[Rockland County, New York]], on March 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288|title=Netflix series 'Orange is the New Black' filming in Rockland|last=Serico|first=Chris|date=March 7, 2013|website=Newsday|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014171403/http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288|archivedate=October 14, 2013|accessdate=March 28, 2013}}</ref> The building, part of the what was then the [[Rockland State Hospital]] campus, was completed in 1970 and closed by 2010. The [[title sequence]] features photos of real former female prisoners including Kerman herself, she is the one that blinks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pate |first1=Caroline |title='Orange is the New Black' Title Sequence Uses Actual Former Prisoners |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/3924-orange-is-the-new-black-title-sequence-uses-actual-former-prisoners |website=Bustle |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2013, prior to the series' premiere, Netflix renewed the show for a second season consisting of 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite press |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/06/27/netflix-renews-original-series-orange-is-the-new-black-for-second-season-534123/20130627netflix01/ |title=Netflix Renews Original Series \"Orange Is the New Black\" for Second Season |publisher=Netflix |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the second season, Uzo Aduba, Taryn Manning, Danielle Brooks, and Natasha Lyonne were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2013/08/uzo-aduba-upped-to-regular-on-orange-is-the-new-black-steven-culp-in-revolution-560320/ |title=Uzo Aduba Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black', Steven Culp In 'Revolution' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 8, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Laura Prepon did not return as a series regular for a second season because of scheduling conflicts, but returned for season 3 as a regular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/season-3-laura-prepon-back-829732/ |title=Orange Is the New Black Season 3: Laura Prepon Back as Series Regular! |website=[[Wetpaint]] |first=Rebecca |last=Martin |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> On May 5, 2014, the series was renewed for a third season, as revealed by actress Laura Prepon.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/05/05/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-3rd-season |title='Orange is the New Black' renewed for 3rd season |website=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=May 5, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the third season, several actors were promoted to series regulars, including Selenis Leyva, Adrienne C. Moore, Dascha Polanco, Nick Sandow, Yael Stone, and Samira Wiley.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hypable.com/orange-is-the-new-black-season-3-series-regulars-list/ |title='Orange is the New Black' season 3 promotes Dascha Polanco to series regular |publisher=Hypable |first=Andrew |last=Simms |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Both Jason Biggs and Pablo Schreiber were confirmed as not returning for the third season, but Schreiber appeared in the 10th episode of the third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-jason-biggs-larry-leaving-season-3-1201437968/ |title='Orange Is the New Black': Jason Biggs Not Returning to Season 3 |website=Variety |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |date=February 20, 2015 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/23/pornstache-will-not-be-in-season-3-of-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title='Pornstache' out ahead of 'Orange' season 3 |website=New York Post |first=Gregory E. |last=Miller |date=July 23, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/pablo_schreiber_pornstache_has_ointnb_season_3_surprise_fans-2015-06 |title=Pablo Schreiber's Pornstache has an 'OITNB' Season 3 surprise in store for fans |publisher=Zap2it |first=Sarah |last=Huggins |date=June 13, 2015 |accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> The series was renewed for a fourth season on April 15, 2015, prior to its third-season release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/04/15/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-season-4-by-netflix/389524/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Renewed for Season 4 by Netflix |website=TV by the Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=April 15, 2015 |accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/orange-new-black-kimmy-schmidt-grace-frankie-premiere-dates-netflix |title=Netflix sets premiere dates for ''OITNB'', ''Kimmy Schmidt'', and more |website=Entertainment Weekly |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |date=January 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> For the fourth season, Jackie Cruz and Lea DeLaria were promoted to series regulars; with Elizabeth Rodriguez also being promoted by the season's sixth episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/lea-delaria-orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-regular-1201417764/ |title=Lea DeLaria Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> On February 5, 2016, the series was renewed for a fifth, sixth and seventh season.<ref name=\"rating\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-3-seasons-netflix-1201698227/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Renewed For 3 Seasons By Netflix |website=Variety |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=February 5, 2016 |accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> In season six, [[Dale Soules]], [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]], and Matt Peters were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-dale-soules-series-regular-frieda-1202104866/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Ups Dale Soules To Series Regular |first=Denise |last=Petski |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=May 31, 2017 |accessdate=October 11, 2018}}</ref> On October 17, 2018, Netflix announced that the seventh season would be the series' last and would be released on July 26, 2019.<ref name=\"end\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/orange-is-the-new-black-end-season-7.html|title=Orange Is the New Black's Prison Sentence Will End With Season 7  |first=Dee |last=Lockett |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=October 17, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"S7ReleaseDate\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/orange-is-the-new-black-final-season-premiere-date-photos-video-1202618932/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Gets Final-Season Premiere Date & Photos \u2013 Watch The Video Announcement |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 22, 2019 |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#475C61;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 1)|1]]\n| 95% (55 reviews)\n| 79 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#D6D3CE;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 2)|2]]\n| 96% (52 reviews)\n| 89 (31 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#84C0F0;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 3)|3]]\n| 95% (63 reviews)\n| 83 (24 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#C3B091;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 4)|4]]\n| 94% (51 reviews)\n| 86 (19 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#FF803D;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 5)|5]]\n| 71% (49 reviews)\n| 67 (20 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#ACACAC;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 6)|6]]\n| 83% (36 reviews)\n| 69 (14 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#191919;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 7)|7]]\n| 97% (34 reviews)\n| 81 (12 reviews)\n|}\n\n[[File:The cast and crew of 'Orange is the New Black' 2014.jpg|280px|left|thumb|Members of the cast and crew with their [[Peabody Award]], May 2014]]\n''Orange Is the New Black'' was widely acclaimed throughout its run. It has been particularly praised for humanizing prisoners<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/how-orange-is-the-new-black-humanizes-inmates/2013/07/26/d1559bac-f3e5-11e2-9434-60440856fadf_story.html |title=How 'Orange Is the New Black' humanizes inmates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Seth |last=Abramson |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/28263-has-orange-is-the-new-black-changed-the-way-we-think-of-prisoners-former-inmates-say |title=Has 'Orange is the New Black' Changed the Way We Think of Prisoners? Former Inmates Say No, But There's Progress Ahead |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |first=Rachel |last=Simon |date=June 17, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> and for its depiction of race, sexuality, gender and body types.<ref name=\"Great Orange grantland\">{{cite web |url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/the-great-orange-is-the-new-black-is-suddenly-the-best-netflix-binge-watch-series-yet/ |title=The Great Orange Is the New Black Is Suddenly the Best Netflix Series Yet |website=[[Grantland]] |first=Andy |last=Greenwald |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYPost ignites\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/06/04/orange-is-the-new-black-ignites-a-tv-revolution-for-women/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' ignites a TV revolution for women |website=[[New York Post]] |first=Robert |last=Rorke |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Caged\">{{cite news |first=Mac |last=McClelland |url=http://contentviewer.adobe.com/s/Rolling%20Stone%20Magazine/57ff9f4987144d9c87ed088b3f6faba5/RS1237/0350.R1237_FEA_Orange.html |title=Caged Heat |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=1237 |date=June 18, 2015 |accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"What Red Did\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/orange-new-black-prison-sex-women-paleyfest-netflix/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Cast Dishes on Prison Sex, Women Calling the Shots, and What Red Did |website=[[TheWrap]] |first=L.A. |last=Ross |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"TVG Cox Breaks\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/orange-new-black-laverne-cox-1068255/ |title=Trans Actress Laverne Cox Breaks New Ground with Orange Is the New Black |first=Sadie |last=Gennis |website=[[TV Guide]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DDot changed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/orange-new-black-fandom-feminism/ |title=How \"Orange Is the New Black\" changed the way we talk about TV |website=[[The Daily Dot]] |first=Audra |last=Schroeder |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Time New Way\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/07/25/dead-tree-alert-orange-is-the-new-black-is-the-new-way-of-talking-about-tv/ |title=Dead Tree Alert: Orange Is the New Black Is the New Way of Talking About TV |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=James |last=Poniewozik |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first season received positive reviews from critics. Review aggregator [[Metacritic]] gave it a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 79/100 based on reviews from 32 critics, indicating favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-1/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Orange Is the New Black Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], season one has a 95% approval rating based on 55 reviews, with an average rating of 8.28/10. The site's critical consensus is \"''Orange Is the New Black'' is a sharp mix of [[black humor]] and dramatic heft, with interesting characters and an intriguing flashback structure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s01 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 1 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2013 |accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHank Stuever, television critic for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', gave ''Orange Is the New Black'' a perfect score. In his review of the series, he stated: \"In Jenji Kohan's magnificent and thoroughly engrossing new series, ''Orange Is the New Black'', prison is still the pits. But it is also filled with the entire range of human emotion and stories, all of which are brought vividly to life in a world where a stick of gum could ignite either a romance or a death threat.\"<ref name=\"Hank\">{{cite web |last=Steuver |first=Hank |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/netflixs-orange-is-the-new-black-brilliance-behind-bars/2013/07/11/d52f911e-e9aa-11e2-8f22-de4bd2a2bd39_story.html |title=Netflix's ''Orange Is the New Black'': Brilliance behind bars |website=The Washington Post |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> Maureen Ryan, of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', wrote: \"''Orange'' is one of the best new programs of the year, and the six episodes I've seen have left me hungry to see more.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/orange-is-the-new-black_b_3574249.html |title='Orange Is The New Black' Review: Subversive Netflix Prison Drama Proves Addictive |website=The Huffington Post |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013 |last=Ryan |first=Maureen}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim. Rotten Tomatoes gave a rating of 96%, with an average rating of 9.2/10 based on 52 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"With a talented ensemble cast bringing life to a fresh round of serial drama, ''Orange Is the New Black's'' sophomore season lives up to its predecessor's standard for female-led television excellence.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s02 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 2 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2014 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref> Metacritic gave the second season a score of 89/100 based on 31 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-2/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Orange Is the New Black Season 2 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2014 |accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> David Wiegland of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the season a positive review, calling the first six episodes \"not only as great as the first season, but arguably better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Orange-Is-the-New-Black-review-Me-vs-we-5526099.php |title='Orange Is the New Black' review: Me vs. we |website=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegland |date=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received critical acclaim. On Metacritic, it has a score of 83/100 based on 24 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-3 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 3 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2015 |accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 95% rating with an average score of 8.08/10 based on 63 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"Thanks to its blend of potent comedy and rich character work, ''Orange is the New Black'' remains a bittersweet pleasure in its third season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s03 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 3 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2015 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received critical acclaim. On Metacritic, it has a score of 86/100 based on 19 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-4 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 4 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2016 |accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 94% rating with an average score of 8.46/10 based on 51 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Orange is the New Black'' is back and better than ever, with a powerful fourth season full of compelling performances by the ensemble cast.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s04 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 4 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2016 |accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> James Poniewozik of ''The New York Times'' reviewed the fourth season as \"Do you measure the quality of a TV season as a beginning-to-end average or by how well it ends? By the first yardstick, Season 4 is ambitious but uneven; by the latter, it's the series' best.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/24/arts/television/season-4-of-orange-is-the-new-black-its-about-time.html |title=Orange Is The New Black: It's About Time |website=The New York Times |first=James |last=Poniewozik |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth season received \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=MC>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-5 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 5 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2017 |accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> On Metacritic, it has a score of 67/100 based on 20 reviews.<ref name=MC /> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 71% rating with an average score of 7.29/10 based on 49 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Orange Is the New Black''{{'}}s fifth season offers up more of the sharp writing and dizzying tonal juggling acts that fans expect \u2013 albeit somewhat less successfully.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s05 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 5 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2017 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe sixth season received positive reviews from critics, with many critics noting its improvement over the previous season. On Metacritic, it has a score of 69/100 based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-6|title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 6 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2018 |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has an 83% rating with an average score of 7.3/10 based on 36 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"Brutality and humor continue to mesh effectively in a season of ''Orange Is the New Black'' that stands as a marked improvement from its predecessor, even if some arcs are more inspired than others.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s06 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 6 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2018 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe seventh season has a score of 81/100 on Metacritic based on 12 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-7 |title=Orange is the New Black: Season 7 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |year=2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 97% rating with an average score of 7.69/10 based on 34 reviews. The site's consensus reads: \"Carried by its exceptional ensemble, ''Orange Is the New Black''{{'}}s  final season gets straight to the point, tackling hard-hitting issues with the same dramatic depth and gallows humor that made the show so ground-breaking to begin with\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s07 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 7 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2019 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Orange Is the New Black'' was ranked 58th on ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |date=September 13, 2019 |accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Orange Is the New Black}}\n\n''Orange Is the New Black'' has received many accolades since its debut. The series has garnered 16 [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]] nominations and four wins. For its first season, it received 12 Emmy Award nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]], winning three.<ref name=\"Emmy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/orange-new-black |title=Orange Is The New Black |publisher=Television Academy |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> [[Taylor Schilling]] received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Television Series \u2013 Drama]].<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hfpa.org/browse/?param=/film/26477 |title=Orange is the New Black |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the [[American Film Institute]] selected the series as one of the Top 10 Television Programs of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFIAwards13.aspx |title=AFI Awards 2013 |publisher=American Film Institute |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA new Emmy rule in 2015, classifying half-hour shows as comedies and hour-long shows as dramas, forced the series to change categories from comedy to drama for its second season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/16/8976181/emmys-nominations-comedy-drama |title=7 Emmys Rules and Quirks that Explain the 2015 Nominations |first=Emily |last=VanDerWerff |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> That year, the series received four Emmy nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], and Aduba won her second Emmy Award, for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref name=\"Emmy\" /> ''Orange Is the New Black'' became the first series to receive Emmy nominations in both comedy and drama categories.<ref name=\"Birnbaum\" /> For its second season, the series also received three Golden Globe Award nominations: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for Schilling, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] for Aduba. At the [[21st Screen Actors Guild Awards]], the series won [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] and Aduba won [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sag-award-winners-2015-screen-actors-guild-awards-winner-list-1201414657/ |title=SAG Award Winners 2015: Full List |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 25, 2015 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor its third season, ''Orange Is the New Black'' won Screen Actors Guild Awards for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series and Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series (Aduba).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016-sag-winners-complete-list-856945/item/outstanding-performance-by-a-female-846040 |title=SAG Awards: The Complete Winners List |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 30, 2016 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> It received a Golden Globe Award nomination for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy.<ref name=\"GG\" /> The series has also received, among other accolades, six [[Writers Guild of America Award]] nominations,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners |title=Previous Nominees & Winners |publisher=[[Writers Guild of America]] |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> five [[Satellite Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2013/ |title=2013 Satellite Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2015/ |title=2015 Satellite Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> four [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]s,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/critics-choice-television-awards-2014-712986 |title=Critics' Choice Television Awards 2014: Complete Winners List |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=June 19, 2014 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/critics-choice-television-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201509015/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards Winners: Full List |website=Variety |date=May 31, 2015 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref> a [[GLAAD Media Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glaad.org/blog/george-takei-orange-new-black-concussion-among-glaadawards-recipients-new-york-city |title=George Takei, \"Orange is the New Black,\" \"Concussion\" among #GLAADAwards recipients in New York City |publisher=[[GLAAD]] |date=May 3, 2014 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref> an [[American Cinema Editors Awards 2016|American Cinema Editors Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/2016-ace-eddie-award-nominations-851748 |title='Star Wars' Among Nominees for ACE Eddie Awards for Film Editing |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 4, 2016 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> a [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Episodic Comedy|Producers Guild of America Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pga-awards-orange-is-new-766654 |title=PGA Awards: 'Orange Is the New Black' Wins Outstanding Producer of Episodic Television, Comedy |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> and a [[Peabody Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix |title=Orange is the New Black (Netflix) |publisher=Peabody Awards |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\n{{quote box|width=270px|align=left| quote=Netflix is famously tight-fisted when it comes to offering up viewership data about its original series. But execs with the streaming giant have repeatedly confirmed that ''OITNB'' is its most-watched original series. That has been backed up by the efforts of outside measurement companies to track viewing in the Netflix eco-system.|source=\u2014''Variety''<ref name=\"rating\" />}}\n\nThe series began airing on broadcast television in [[New Zealand]], on [[TVNZ 2|TV2]], on August 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/orange-is-the-new-black/index-group-5523557 |title=Orange Is The New Black |website=TVNZ |accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> It premiered in [[Australia]] on October 9, 2013, on [[Showcase (Australian TV channel)|Showcase]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/09/airdate-orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Airdate: Orange is the New Black |website=TV Tonight |date=September 9, 2013 |first=David |last=Knox |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> The second season began on Showcase on July 16, 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxtel.com.au/got/whats-on/foxtel-insider/foxtel/most-anticipated-returning-shows.html |title=Most anticipated returning shows in 2014 |website=Foxtel |date=January 14, 2014 |accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref> and the third season premiered on June 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxtel.com.au/got/whats-on/foxtel-insider/showcase/orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Orange is the New Black S3: same time as the US |website=Foxtel |date=June 4, 2015 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> The first season began airing on broadcast television in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] on [[Sony Channel (UK and Ireland)|Sony Channel]] from April 19, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/orange-is-new-black-uk-linear-rights-go-sony-channel-988468 |title=Sony Channel U.K. Takes 'Orange Is the New Black' |last=Szalai |first=Georg |date=March 24, 2017 |website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> It has been shown in [[Ireland]] on [[TG4]] since January 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tg4.ie/en/programmes/orange-is-the-new-black/|title=Orange Is The New Black|website=tg4.ie}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, it was reported that a [[Cybercrime|cybercriminal]] had stolen the first ten episodes of season 5, in a security breach of a post-production company. Netflix failed to respond to ransom demands, and the cybercriminal [[internet leak|leaked]] the episodes online. Netflix confirmed the security breach and an ongoing investigation by federal law enforcement.<ref name=\"S5 Leaked\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hacker-threatens-release-new-episodes-orange-is-new-black-998670 |title=Hacker Releases New Episodes of 'Orange Is the New Black |website=The Hollywood Reporter |agency=Associated Press |date=April 28, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/29/business/media/netflix-hack-orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Hacker Leaks Episodes From Netflix Show and Threatens Other Networks |work =The New York Times |last1=Perlroth |first1=Nicole |last2=Haag |first2=Matthew |date=April 29, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Multichannel News]]'' reported that demand for the series significantly increased over the seven-day period following the leak of the episodes. It was also said that the leak would likely cause a decrease in demand for the fifth season when Netflix released it in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.multichannel.com/blog/bauminator/demand-orange-new-black-spiked-following-hack/412744 |title=Demand for 'Orange Is the New Black' Spiked Following Hack |website=[[Multichannel News]] |date=May 10, 2017 |first=Jeff |last=Baumgartner |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n''Orange Is the New Black'' generated more viewers and hours viewed in its first week than the other top Netflix original series ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]'' and ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]''.<ref name=\"Grantland\">{{cite web |url=http://grantland.com/features/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix-season-two/ |title=Brilliant 'Orange' |website=[[Grantland]] |first=Andy |last=Greenwald |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20130723/netflixs-no-name-show-beating-house-of-cards-and-arrested-development/ |title=Netflix's No-Name Show Beating \"House of Cards\" and \"Arrested Development\" |website=[[All Things Digital]] |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |last=Kafka |first=Peter}}</ref> In October 2013, Netflix stated that the show is a \"tremendous success\" for the streaming platform. \"It will end the year as our most watched original series ever and, as with each of our other previously launched originals, enjoys an audience comparable with successful shows on cable and broadcast TV.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/10/21/netflix-orange-is-the-new-black-most-watched/ |title=Netflix: 'Orange Is The New Black' Is Our Most-Watched Original, But Our TV Exclusives Are Even Bigger |website=[[TechCrunch]] |first=Anthony |last=Ha |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2013/10/21/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix-most-watched/#YHlOr3Wcb8qw |title='Orange Is the New Black' Is Netflix's Most-Watched Original Series |website=[[Mashable]] |first=Brian Anthony |last=Hernandez |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> As reported in February 2016, ''Orange Is the New Black'' remained Netflix's most-watched original series.<ref name=\"rating\" /><ref name=\"rating2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/netflix-renews-orange-is-the-new-black-for-three-more-series-a6855626.html |title=Netflix renews Orange is the New Black for three more series |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Jess |last=Denham |date=February 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/feb/05/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-new-season-netflix |title=Orange is the New Black renewed for three additional seasons |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Nigel M |last=Smith |date=February 5, 2016 |accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' study of the 50 TV shows with the most [[List of Facebook features#Likes and Reactions|Facebook Likes]] found that ''Orange Is the New Black'' is one of the shows most watched in [[urban area]]s, and despite its \"minority-rich ensemble cast\", the series \"appeals more to a white audience\".<ref name=\"katz20161227\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/12/26/upshot/duck-dynasty-vs-modern-family-television-maps.html |title='Duck Dynasty' vs. 'Modern Family': 50 Maps of the U.S. Cultural Divide |last=Katz |first=Josh |date=December 27, 2016 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Incarceration of women in the United States]]\n* [[List of dramatic television series with LGBT characters]]\n* [[List of LGBT characters in television and radio]]\n* [[Prison\u2013industrial complex]]\n* ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news| url=http://thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2014-06-09/piper-kerman-her-story-inspired-netflix-series-orange-new-black| title= Piper Kerman On Her Story That Inspired The Netflix Series ''Orange Is The New Black''|date=June 2014|work=[[The Diane Rehm Show]]}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Orange Is the New Black}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Netflix title|70242311}}\n*{{IMDb title|2372162|Orange Is the New Black}}\n\n{{Orange Is the New Black}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Orange Is the New Black|Awards for ''Orange Is the New Black'']]\n|list =\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Comedy Series}}\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Comedy Series}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Episodic Comedy}}\n{{Satellite Award for Best Cast \u2013 Television Series}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Musical or Comedy Television Series}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAwards EnsembleTVComedy 2010\u20132019}}\n{{TCA Award for Outstanding New Program}}\n{{VH1 Trailblazer Honors}}\n}}\n{{Netflix original ended series}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Television|United States|LGBT|Comedy}}\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American black television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s prison television series]]\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related web series]]\n[[Category:American black television series]]\n[[Category:American prison television series]]\n[[Category:Bisexuality-related television series]]\n[[Category:Crime drama web series]]\n[[Category:Federal American minimum security prisons in fiction]]\n[[Category:Feminist television]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American television]]\n[[Category:Imprisonment and detention of women in the United States]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Nonlinear narrative television series]]\n[[Category:Orange Is the New Black]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Peabody Award-winning television programs]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award-winning television series]]\n[[Category:Prison web series]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television series about illegal drug trade]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on books]]\n[[Category:Television series by Lionsgate Television]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Jenji Kohan]]\n[[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Transgender-related television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American comedy-drama television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Orange Is the New Black\n| image                    = Orange is the new Black.png\n| genre                    = [[Comedy-drama]]\n| creator                  = [[Jenji Kohan]]\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|''[[Orange Is the New Black: My Year in a Women's Prison]]''|[[Piper Kerman]]}}\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kacee Gibbs the raging Homo]]\n* [[Taylor Schilling]]\n* [[Laura Prepon]]\n* [[Michael Harney]]\n* [[Michelle Hurst]]\n* [[Kate Mulgrew]]\n* [[Jason Biggs]]\n* [[Uzo Aduba]]\n* [[Danielle Brooks]]\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]]\n* [[Taryn Manning]]\n* [[Selenis Leyva]]\n* [[Adrienne C. Moore]]\n* [[Dascha Polanco]]\n* [[Nick Sandow]]\n* [[Yael Stone]]\n* [[Samira Wiley]]\n* [[Jackie Cruz]]\n* [[Lea DeLaria]]\n* [[Elizabeth Rodriguez]]\n* [[Jessica Pimentel]]\n* [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]]\n* Matt Peters\n* [[Dale Soules]]\n* [[Alysia Reiner]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Regina Spektor]]\n| opentheme                = \"[[You've Got Time]]\"\n| endtheme                 = \n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Scott Doherty\n* Brandon Jay\n* [[Gwendolyn Sanford]]\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 7\n| num_episodes             = 91\n| list_episodes            = List of Orange Is the New Black episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Jenji Kohan\n* [[Liz Friedman]] (pilot)\n* [[Sara Hess]]\n* Tara Herrmann\n* Lisa Vinnecour\n* Neri Kyle Tannenbaum\n* Mark A. Burley\n}}\n| producer                 = Neri Kyle Tannenbaum\n| location                 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 51\u201393 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* Tilted Productions\n* [[Lionsgate Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = {{Plainlist|\n* Lionsgate Television\n* [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n}}\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[1080p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n* [[4K resolution|4K]]\n}}\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital Plus]] 5.1 with [[Descriptive Video Service]] track\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2013|7|11}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|2019|7|26}}\n| website                  = http://www.netflix.com/orangeisthenewblack\n| channel                  = [[Netflix]]\n}}\n\n'''''Orange Is the New Black''''' (sometimes abbreviated to '''''OITNB''''') is an American [[comedy-drama]] [[web television]] series created by [[Jenji Kohan]] for [[Netflix]].<ref name=Dunne>{{cite news |last=Dunne |first=Susan |title=Danbury Women's Prison Setting For Netflix Original Series |url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-07-03/entertainment/hc-orange-is-the-new-black-0707-20130703_1_kerman-drug-operation-prison-staff |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |newspaper=The Hartford Courant |date=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"duocast\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/09/duo-cast-in-netflixs-orange-is-the-new-black-don-stark-upped-on-vhs-bounce/ |title=Duo Cast in Netflix's 'Orange Is The New Black', Don Stark Upped on VH's 'Bounce' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=September 17, 2012 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=September 17, 2012}}</ref> The series is based on [[Piper Kerman]]'s memoir, ''[[Orange Is the New Black: My Year in a Women's Prison]]'' (2010), about her experiences at [[Federal Correctional Institution, Danbury|FCI Danbury]], a minimum-security [[federal prison]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2013/08/06/piper-kerman-orange-is-the-new-black-interview_n_3714601.html |title=Piper Kerman, 'Orange Is The New Black' Author: What's Real, What's Not About Netflix Show |date=August 6, 2013 |website=HuffPost Canada |access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref> Produced by Tilted Productions in association with [[Lionsgate Television]], ''Orange Is the New Black'' premiered on Netflix on July 11, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-orange-new-black-premiere-date-jenji-kohan-448610 |title=Netflix Sets Premiere Date for Jenji Kohan's 'Orange Is the New Black' |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=April 30, 2013 |accessdate=April 30, 2013}}</ref> In February 2016, the series was renewed for a fifth, sixth, and seventh season.<ref name=\"rating\" /> On October 17, 2018, it was confirmed that the seventh season, which was released on July 26, 2019, would be its last.<ref name=\"end\" /><ref name=\"S7ReleaseDate\" />\n\n''Orange Is the New Black'' has become Netflix's most-watched original series.<ref name=\"rating\" /><ref name=\"rating2\" /> It was widely acclaimed throughout its run, and has received many accolades. For its first season, the series garnered 12 [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]], winning three. A new Emmy rule in 2015 forced the series to change categories from comedy to drama.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/16/8976181/emmys-nominations-comedy-drama |title=7 Emmys rules and quirks that explain the 2015 nominations |first=Emily |last=VanDerWerff |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref> For its second season, the series received four Emmy nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], and [[Uzo Aduba]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]]. ''Orange Is the New Black'' is the first series to score Emmy nominations in both comedy and drama categories.<ref name=\"Birnbaum\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jenji-kohan-orange-is-the-new-black-showrunner-1201555759/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Boss Jenji Kohan on Running the Show Her Way |website=Variety |first=Debra |last=Birnbaum |date=August 4, 2015 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> The series has also received six [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations, six [[Writers Guild of America Award]] nominations, a [[Producers Guild of America Award]], an [[American Film Institute]] award, and a [[Peabody Award]].\n\n==Plot==\n{{Main|List of Orange Is the New Black episodes}}\n{{:List of Orange Is the New Black episodes}}\n{{expand section|with=Main storyline(s) of seasons 1\u20134|date=August 2018}}\n\nThe series begins revolving around [[Piper Chapman]] ([[Taylor Schilling]]), a woman in her thirties living in New York City who is sentenced to 15 months in Litchfield Penitentiary, a [[Prison#Security|minimum-security]] women's [[federal prison]] in [[upstate New York]]. Chapman was convicted of transporting a suitcase full of drug money for her girlfriend [[Alex Vause]] ([[Laura Prepon]]), an international [[Illegal drug trade|drug smuggler]]. The offense had occurred 10 years before the start of the series and in that time Chapman had moved on to a quiet, law-abiding life among New York's [[upper middle class]]. Her sudden and unexpected indictment disrupts her relationships with her fianc\u00e9, family and friends. In prison, Chapman is reunited with Vause (who named Chapman in her trial, resulting in Chapman's arrest), and they re-examine their relationship. Simultaneously, Chapman, along with the other inmates, attempt to grapple with prison's numerous, inherent struggles. Episodes often feature [[flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]] of significant events from various inmates' and prison guards' pasts. These flashbacks typically depict how an inmate came to be in prison or develop a character's backstory. The prison is initially operated by the \"Federal Department of Corrections\" (a fictional version of the [[Federal Bureau of Prisons]]), and was in a later season acquired by the Management & Correction Corporation (MCC), a private prison company.\n\nThe fifth season shows the prisoners revolting against the guards, wardens and the system after MCC's failed handling of an inmate's death at the hands of a guard in the fourth season. The inmate death had followed a peaceful protest and subsequent instigation of an inmate fight by another guard. Fueled by the conditions the inmates are forced to tolerate, as well as grudges against the prison guards, a three-day riot ensues. During the riot, some inmates attempt to negotiate better living conditions and seek justice for the death of the inmate, while others pursue their own interests and entertainment, and a few seek no involvement. At the emergence of the riot, the guard who incited the fight in the prior season is critically wounded by an inmate who took the gun the guard illegally brought into the prison. At the end of the season, [[SWAT]] raids the prison to end the riot and remove all inmates from the facility. During this raid, a correctional officer is fatally wounded by a corrupt \"strike team\", which then conspires to blame the guard's death on inmates who hid in an underground bunker and had taken the guard hostage. All inmates are transported to other prisons.\n\nThe consequences of the riot are shown in the sixth season. A number of the inmates, including Chapman and Vause, are transported to Litchfield Maximum Security. Most of these inmates are interrogated, and several of them charged and sentenced for their involvement in the riot. In max, new inmates are introduced, alliances are made, and a gang-like war emerges between two prison blocks, spearheaded by a longstanding feud between two sisters and a grudge harbored by them toward a former maximum-security inmate who returned as a consequence of the riot (she had been moved to the minimum security prison). Inmates who arrived from the minimum security prison are either caught up or willingly participate in the war between prison blocks. The season portrays further corruption and guard brutality.\n\nThe seventh season provides an ending to various inmate's stories. Chapman and Vause continue their on/off again relationship. The season shows how some prisoners are able to move beyond their time in prison while others are captured by the system and through their own flaws and/or systemic problems in the structure of US society and its \u201cjustice\u201d system are unable to progress. In addition to the established setting of Litchfield Max, a significant portion of the season takes place in a newly created [[U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement|ICE]] detention centre for detained presumed illegal immigrants, showing their struggles and lack of access to outside help in large part because of complete or extreme disregard of the law. \n\nThroughout the series, it is shown how various forms of corruption, funding cuts by the corporate owner to increase profit by millions, [[private prison|privatization of prison]], overcrowding, guard brutality and racial discrimination (among other issues), affect the prisoners' safety, health and well-being; the correctional officers\u2019 lives; and the prison's basic inability to fulfill its fundamental legal responsibilities and ethical obligations as a corrections institution.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Terry|first=April|date=July 2016|title=Surveying Issues That Arise in Women's Prisons: A Content Critique of Orange Is the New Black: OITNB: Women's Prisons|journal=Sociology Compass|volume=10|issue=7|pages=553\u2013566|doi=10.1111/soc4.12388}}</ref> One of the show's key conflicts involves the minimum-security prison's Director of Human Activities (aka the warden, under privatization nomenclature), Joe Caputo, whose efforts and aims as a [[Prison warden|warden]] constantly conflict with the corporate interests of MCC, which acquired the facility when it was about to be shut down. This theme is continued when a new forward-thinking & caring warden is hired at the maximum security prison, and unlike Caputo actually institutes educational programs and positive changes. She is fired for these actions and her attitude toward the corporate corruption, although her short-lived changes have profound positive results.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{Main|List of Orange Is the New Black characters}}\n\n===Main cast===\n<!-- Main cast is determined by opening credits billing, not popularity or episode count -->\n{{div col}}\n* [[Taylor Schilling]] as [[Piper Chapman]]\n* [[Laura Prepon]] as [[Alex Vause]], inmate  {{Small|(seasons 1, 3\u20137; recurring season 2)}}\n* [[Michael Harney]] as Sam Healy, correctional officer {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134; guest season 6 and 7)}}{{efn|Michael J. Harney was credited as main cast for season 5 but did not make an appearance.}}\n* [[Michelle Hurst]] as Miss Claudette Pelage, inmate {{Small|(season 1)}}\n* [[Kate Mulgrew]] as Galina \"Red\" Reznikov, inmate\n* [[Jason Biggs]] as Larry Bloom, Piper's fianc\u00e9 {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 5; recurring season 7)}}\n* [[Uzo Aduba]] as [[Crazy Eyes (character)|Suzanne \"Crazy Eyes\" Warren]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Danielle Brooks]] as Tasha \"Taystee\" Jefferson, inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Natasha Lyonne]] as [[Nicky Nichols]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Taryn Manning]] as [[Tiffany Doggett|Tiffany \"Pennsatucky\" Doggett]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 2\u20137; recurring season 1)}}\n* [[Selenis Leyva]] as Gloria Mendoza, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Adrienne C. Moore]] as Cindy \"Black Cindy\" Hayes, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Dascha Polanco]] as Dayanara \"Daya\" Diaz, inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Nick Sandow]] as Joe Caputo, Captain of the Guard, later warden {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Yael Stone]] as [[Lorna Morello]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20132)}}\n* [[Samira Wiley]] as [[Poussey Washington]], inmate {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134; recurring seasons 1\u20132; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* [[Jackie Cruz]] as Marisol \"Flaca\" Gonzales, inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Lea DeLaria]] as Carrie \"Big Boo\" Black, inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; recurring seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Elizabeth Rodriguez]] as Aleida Diaz, former inmate {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Jessica Pimentel]] as Maria Ruiz, inmate {{Small|(seasons 5\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]] as Blanca Flores, inmate {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20135)}}\n* Matt Peters as Joel Luschek, correctional officer {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 1\u20135)}}\n* [[Dale Soules]] as Frieda Berlin, inmate {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; recurring seasons 2\u20135)}}\n* [[Alysia Reiner]] as Natalie \"Fig\" Figueroa, warden {{Small|(season 7; recurring 1\u20133, 5\u20136; guest season 4)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Recurring cast===\n{{Main|List of recurring Orange Is the New Black characters}}\n\n====Inmates====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Laverne Cox]] as Sophia Burset {{Small|(seasons 1\u20136, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Diane Guerrero]] as Maritza Ramos {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* [[Annie Golden]] as Norma Romano {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Vicky Jeudy]] as Janae Watson {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Julie Lake]] as Angie Rice {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Emma Myles]] as Leanne Taylor {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Abigail Savage]] as Gina Murphy {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Constance Shulman]] as Yoga Jones {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lori Tan Chinn]] as Mei Chang {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Tamara Torres as Emily \"Weeping Woman\" Germann {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lin Tucci]] as Anita DeMarco {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Beth Fowler]] as Sister Jane Ingalls {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Barbara Rosenblat]] as [[Miss Rosa|Rosa \"Miss Rosa\" Cisneros]] {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 3)}}\n* [[Madeline Brewer]] as Tricia Miller {{Small|(season 1)}}\n* [[Kimiko Glenn]] as Brook Soso {{Small|(seasons 2\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Lori Petty]] as Lolly Whitehill {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134, 6\u20137; guest season 2)}}\n* Yvette Freeman as Irma Lerman {{Small|(season 2; guest season 3)}}\n* [[Lorraine Toussaint]] as Yvonne \"Vee\" Parker {{Small|(season 2)}}\n* [[Blair Brown]] as Judy King {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Emily Althaus as Maureen Kukudio {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* [[Ruby Rose]] as Stella Carlin {{Small|(season 3; guest season 4)}}\n* Daniella De Jesus as Irene \"Zirconia\" Cabrera {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Shannon Esper as Alana Dwight {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Rosal Colon as Carmen \"Ouija\" Aziza {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* Francesca Curran as Helen \"Skinhead Helen\" Van Maele {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* [[Kelly Karbacz]] as Kasey Sankey {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* Amanda Stephen as Alison Abdullah {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Asia Kate Dillon]] as Brandy Epps {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Miriam Morales as Ramona \"Pidge\" Contreras {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* [[Jolene Purdy]] as Stephanie Hapakuka {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Shirley Roeca as Juanita Vasquez {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137, guest season 5)}}\n* Rebecca Knox as Tina Swope {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Sipiwe Moyo as Adeola Chinede {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Besanya Santiago as Raquel \"Creech\" Munoz {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Finnerty Steeves as Beth Hoefler {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Christina Toth as Annalisa Damiva {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Amanda Fuller]] as Madison \"Badison\" Murphy {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Vicci Martinez]] as Dominga \"Daddy\" Duarte {{Small|(seasons 6, guest season 7)}}\n* [[Mackenzie Phillips]] as Barbara \"Barb\" Denning {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Henny Russell as Carol Denning {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Ismenia Mendes as Tali Grapes {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Staff====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Catherine Curtin]] as Wanda Bell {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* Joel Marsh Garland as Scott O'Neill {{Small|(seasons 1\u20135, 7)}}\n* Brendan Burke as Wade Donaldson {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134)}}\n* [[Pablo Schreiber]] as George \"Pornstache\" Mendez {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* Lolita Foster as Eliqua Maxwell {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* Germar Terrell Gardner as Charles Ford {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Matt McGorry]] as John Bennett {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Lauren Lapkus]] as Susan Fischer {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 7)}}\n* Kaipo Schwab as Igme Dimaguiba {{Small|(season 1; guest seasons 2\u20134)}}\n* James McMenamin as Charlie \"Donuts\" Coates {{Small|(seasons 3\u20136)}}\n* [[Alan Aisenberg]] as Baxter \"Gerber\" Bayley {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* Jimmy Gary Jr. as Felix Rikerson {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135)}}\n* [[Mike Birbiglia]] as Danny Pearson {{Small|(seasons 3\u20134)}}\n* [[Marsha Stephanie Blake]] as Berdie Rogers {{Small|(season 3)}}\n* [[Beth Dover]] as Linda Ferguson {{Small| (seasons 4\u20137; guest season 3)}}\n* Nick Dillenburg as Ryder Blake {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* Mike Houston as Lee Dixon {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* [[Emily Tarver]] as Artesian McCullough {{Small|(seasons 4\u20137)}}\n* [[Brad William Henke]] as Desi Piscatella {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135; guest season 6)}}\n* Evan Arthur Hall as B. Stratman {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* John Palladino as Josh {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Michael Torpey as Thomas \"Humps\" Humphrey {{Small|(seasons 4\u20135)}}\n* Hunter Emery as Rick Hopper {{Small|(seasons 5\u20137)}}\n* Shawna Hamic as Virginia \"Ginger\" Copeland {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Susan Heyward]] as Tamika Ward {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* [[Josh Segarra]] as Danilo Stefanovic {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Greg Vrotsos as Greg Hellman {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Nicholas Webber as J. Alvarez {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Branden Wellington as Jarod Young {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137)}}\n* Adam Lindo as Carlos \"Clitvack\" Litvack {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n====Others====\n{{div col}}\n* [[Michael Chernus]] as Cal Chapman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134, 7; guest season 6)}}\n* [[Tanya Wright]] as Crystal Burset {{Small|(seasons 1\u20134; guest season 6)}}\n* Berto Colon as Cesar Velazquez {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133, 7; guest season 5)}}\n* [[Deborah Rush]] as Carol Chapman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133; guest seasons 5, 7)}}\n* [[Tracee Chimo]] as Neri Feldman {{Small|(seasons 1\u20133, 7)}}\n* [[Maria Dizzia]] as Polly Harper {{Small|(seasons 1\u20132; guest season 7)}}\n* Ian Paola as Yadriel {{Small|(seasons 2\u20135; guest season 7)}}\n* [[John Magaro]] as Vince Muccio {{Small|(seasons 3\u20135, 7)}}\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]] as Delia Mendez-Powell {{Small|(season 3; guest season 5)}}\n* Miguel Izaguirre as Dario \"Diablo\" Z\u00fa\u00f1iga {{Small|(seasons 6\u20137; guest seasons 1, 4\u20135)}}\n* [[Michael J. Burg]] as Detective Mark Bellamy {{Small|(season 6)}}\n* Bill Hoag as Bill Chapman {{Small|(season 7; guest seasons 1\u20133)}}\n* [[Karina Arroyave]] as Karla C\u00f3rdova {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* Melinna Bobadilla as Santos Chaj {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* [[Marie-Lou Nahhas]] as Shani Abboud {{Small|(season 7)}}\n* [[Alicia Witt]] as Zelda {{Small|(season 7)}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Cast of Orange Is The New Black at Paley Fest.jpg|thumb|right|The series cast at The Paley Center For Media's PaleyFest 2014 event honoring the show]]\n\nShow creator [[Jenji Kohan]] read [[Piper Kerman]]'s memoir after a friend sent it to her. She then set up a meeting with Kerman to pitch her on a TV adaptation, which she notes she \"screwed up\" as she spent most of the time asking Kerman about her experiences she described in the book rather than selling her on the show. This appealed to Kerman as it let her know that she was a fan and she signed off on the adaptation.<ref name=\"Collidermay\">{{cite web |last1=Radish |first1=Christina |title=Creator Jenji Kohan Talks ORANGE IS THE NEW BLACK, Her Research Into Prison Life, and Graphic Sex Scenes |url=https://collider.com/jenji-kohan-orange-is-the-new-black-interview/ |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=July 7, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref> Kohan would later go on to describe the main character, [[Piper Chapman]], as a \"trojan horse\" for the series, allowing it to focus on characters whose demographics would not normally be represented on TV.<ref>{{cite web |title='Orange' Creator Jenji Kohan: 'Piper Was My Trojan Horse' |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/08/13/211639989/orange-creator-jenji-kohan-piper-was-my-trojan-horse |publisher=NPR |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, it was revealed that Netflix was in negotiations with Lionsgate for a 13-episode TV adaptation of Kerman's memoirs with Kohan as creator.<ref name=\"based\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/07/netflix-eyeing-second-original-series-comedy-from-weeds-creator-jenji-kohan/ |title=Netflix Eyeing Second Original Series \u2013 Comedy From ''Weeds'' Creator Jenji Kohan |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=July 22, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> In November 2011, negotiations were finalized and the series had been [[Green-light|greenlit]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/11/netflix-lionsgate-tv-closing-deal-for-jenji-kohans-orange-is-the-new-black-comedy/ |title=Netflix, Lionsgate TV Closing Deal For Jenji Kohan's 'Orange Is The New Black' Comedy |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 11, 2011 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref> Kohan had initially wanted to cast [[Katie Holmes]] in the role of Piper Chapman, and met with the actress to discuss it, but Holmes had other commitments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/08/06/katie-holmes-almost-starred-in-orange-is-the-new-black/|title=Katie Holmes almost starred in 'Orange is the New Black'|website=[[New York Post]]|date=August 6, 2014|accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Casting announcements began in August 2012 with [[Taylor Schilling]], the first to be cast, as Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2012/08/taylor-schilling-to-star-in-jenji-kohans-netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title=Taylor Schilling To Star in Jenji Kohan's Netflix Series ''Orange Is The New Black'' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=August 30, 2012 |website=Deadline Hollywood |accessdate=August 30, 2012}}</ref> followed by [[Jason Biggs]] as Piper's fianc\u00e9 Larry Bloom.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jason-biggs-netflix-orange-new-black-jenji-kohan-weeds-369610 |title=Jason Biggs to Co-Star in Netflix's 'Orange Is the New Black' (Exclusive) |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=September 12, 2012 |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Laura Prepon]] and [[Yael Stone]] were next to join the series, as [[Alex Vause]] and [[Lorna Morello]], respectively.<ref name=\"duocast\" /> [[Abigail Savage]], who plays Gina, and [[Alysia Reiner]], who plays Fig, had auditioned for role of Alex Vause.<ref name=\"Collidermay\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/07/orange-is-the-new-black-fig-interview.html |title=Orange Is the New Black's Fig Explains the 'Beer Can' Scene |website=[[Vulture (blog)|Vulture]] |first=E. Alex |last=Jung |date=July 9, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Prepon initially auditioned for Piper Chapman,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/08/16/big-boo-orange-is-the-new-black_n_3768682.html |title=Big Boo Wasn't Originally Supposed To Be A Part Of 'Orange Is The New Black' (VIDEO) |website=HuffPost |date=August 16, 2017 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> however Kohan felt she would not worry about her [in prison], noting a \"toughness and a presence to her that wasn't right for the character.\" Kohan instead gave her the role of Alex.<ref name=\"Collidermay\" /> Stone had originally auditioned for the role of [[Nicky Nichols]], but she was not considered \"tough enough\" for the character;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jul/06/yael-stone-on-orange-is-the-new-black-i-wasnt-sapphic-enough-to-play-nicky |title=Yael Stone on Orange is the New Black: 'I wasn't Sapphic enough to play Nicky' |website=[[The Guardian]] |first=Steve |last=Down |date=July 5, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> she was asked to audition for Lorna Morello instead.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> Likability was important for Morello, whom casting director Jen Euston deemed \"a very helpful, nice, sweet Italian girl.\"<ref name=\"Orley\">{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/emilyorley/how-the-orange-is-the-new-black-cast-came-to-be |title=How The \"Orange Is The New Black\" Cast Came To Be |website=BuzzFeed |first=Emily |last=Orley |date=August 13, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> [[Natasha Lyonne]] was to audition for Alex, but was asked to read for the character Nicky Nichols; \"[Kohan knew] she could do Nicky with her eyes closed. She was perfect,\" said Euston.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> [[Laverne Cox]], a black [[transgender]] woman, was cast as Sophia Burset, a transgender character. ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'' touted ''Orange Is the New Black'' as possibly the first women-in-prison narrative to cast a transgender woman for this type of role.<ref name=\"Anderson full\">{{cite web |last=Anderson |first=Diane |url=http://www.advocate.com/print-issue/current-issue/2013/07/10/why-you-should-watch-orange-new-black?page=full |title=Why You Should Watch 'Orange Is the New Black' |website=The Advocate |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> [[Uzo Aduba]] read for the part of Janae Watson but was offered the character [[Suzanne Warren|Suzanne \"Crazy Eyes\" Warren]].<ref name=\"Orley\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/orange-is-the-new-blacks-uzo-aduba-how-would-make-someone-think-id-be-right-for-crazy-eyes/news-story/7b8dda54c824f6a17d9fed7c73c917a0 |title=Orange Is The New Black's Uzo Aduba: 'How would make someone think I'd be right for Crazy Eyes?' |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |first=Holly |last=Byrnes |date=December 18, 2015 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> Taryn Manning was offered the role of Tiffany \"Pennsatucky\" Doggett.<ref name=\"Orley\" /> ''[[This American Life]]'' host [[Ira Glass]] was offered a role as a [[Public broadcasting#Radio|public radio]] [[radio host|host]], but he declined. The role instead went to [[Robert Stanton (actor)|Robert Stanton]], who plays the fictional host Maury Kind.<ref>{{cite web |last=Molloy |first=Tim |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tv/article/ira-glass-politely-declined-role-orange-new-black-110491 |title=Ira Glass 'Politely Declined' Role on 'Orange Is the New Black' |publisher=The Wrap |date=August 13, 2013 |accessdate=August 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Orange is the New Black'' is set in a fictional minimum-security prison in [[Litchfield, New York]], which is a real town in upstate New York, but it does not have a federal penitentiary.<ref name=WIBX>{{cite web |title=Is the 'Orange is New Black' Prison Real? Yes, and it is Located Near Utica |url=http://wibx950.com/orange-is-new-black-prison-is-located-near-utica/ |publisher=WIBX 950 AM |accessdate=May 23, 2014 |date=January 6, 2014}}</ref> The series began filming in the former Rockland Children's Psychiatric Center in [[Rockland County, New York]], on March 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288|title=Netflix series 'Orange is the New Black' filming in Rockland|last=Serico|first=Chris|date=March 7, 2013|website=Newsday|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014171403/http://brooklyn.news12.com/news/hudson-buzz-1.3774483/netflix-series-orange-is-the-new-black-filming-in-rockland-1.4761288|archivedate=October 14, 2013|accessdate=March 28, 2013}}</ref> The building, part of the what was then the [[Rockland State Hospital]] campus, was completed in 1970 and closed by 2010. The [[title sequence]] features photos of real former female prisoners including Kerman herself, she is the one that blinks.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pate |first1=Caroline |title='Orange is the New Black' Title Sequence Uses Actual Former Prisoners |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/3924-orange-is-the-new-black-title-sequence-uses-actual-former-prisoners |website=Bustle |date=August 21, 2013 |accessdate=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2013, prior to the series' premiere, Netflix renewed the show for a second season consisting of 13 episodes.<ref>{{cite press |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2013/06/27/netflix-renews-original-series-orange-is-the-new-black-for-second-season-534123/20130627netflix01/ |title=Netflix Renews Original Series \"Orange Is the New Black\" for Second Season |publisher=Netflix |date=June 27, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the second season, Uzo Aduba, Taryn Manning, Danielle Brooks, and Natasha Lyonne were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2013/08/uzo-aduba-upped-to-regular-on-orange-is-the-new-black-steven-culp-in-revolution-560320/ |title=Uzo Aduba Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black', Steven Culp In 'Revolution' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 8, 2013 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Laura Prepon did not return as a series regular for a second season because of scheduling conflicts, but returned for season 3 as a regular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wetpaint.com/season-3-laura-prepon-back-829732/ |title=Orange Is the New Black Season 3: Laura Prepon Back as Series Regular! |website=[[Wetpaint]] |first=Rebecca |last=Martin |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 9, 2017}}</ref> On May 5, 2014, the series was renewed for a third season, as revealed by actress Laura Prepon.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2014/05/05/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-3rd-season |title='Orange is the New Black' renewed for 3rd season |website=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=May 5, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> For the third season, several actors were promoted to series regulars, including Selenis Leyva, Adrienne C. Moore, Dascha Polanco, Nick Sandow, Yael Stone, and Samira Wiley.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hypable.com/orange-is-the-new-black-season-3-series-regulars-list/ |title='Orange is the New Black' season 3 promotes Dascha Polanco to series regular |publisher=Hypable |first=Andrew |last=Simms |date=June 12, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> Both Jason Biggs and Pablo Schreiber were confirmed as not returning for the third season, but Schreiber appeared in the 10th episode of the third season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-jason-biggs-larry-leaving-season-3-1201437968/ |title='Orange Is the New Black': Jason Biggs Not Returning to Season 3 |website=Variety |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |date=February 20, 2015 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/23/pornstache-will-not-be-in-season-3-of-orange-is-the-new-black/ |title='Pornstache' out ahead of 'Orange' season 3 |website=New York Post |first=Gregory E. |last=Miller |date=July 23, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zap2it.com/blogs/pablo_schreiber_pornstache_has_ointnb_season_3_surprise_fans-2015-06 |title=Pablo Schreiber's Pornstache has an 'OITNB' Season 3 surprise in store for fans |publisher=Zap2it |first=Sarah |last=Huggins |date=June 13, 2015 |accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> The series was renewed for a fourth season on April 15, 2015, prior to its third-season release.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2015/04/15/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-for-season-4-by-netflix/389524/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Renewed for Season 4 by Netflix |website=TV by the Numbers |last=Bibel |first=Sara |date=April 15, 2015 |accessdate=April 15, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/17/orange-new-black-kimmy-schmidt-grace-frankie-premiere-dates-netflix |title=Netflix sets premiere dates for ''OITNB'', ''Kimmy Schmidt'', and more |website=Entertainment Weekly |last=Abrams |first=Natalie |date=January 17, 2016 |accessdate=January 17, 2016}}</ref> For the fourth season, Jackie Cruz and Lea DeLaria were promoted to series regulars; with Elizabeth Rodriguez also being promoted by the season's sixth episode.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/lea-delaria-orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-regular-1201417764/ |title=Lea DeLaria Upped To Regular On 'Orange Is The New Black' |website=Deadline Hollywood |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> On February 5, 2016, the series was renewed for a fifth, sixth and seventh season.<ref name=\"rating\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-3-seasons-netflix-1201698227/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Renewed For 3 Seasons By Netflix |website=Variety |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=February 5, 2016 |accessdate=February 5, 2016}}</ref> In season six, [[Dale Soules]], [[Laura G\u00f3mez (actress)|Laura G\u00f3mez]], and Matt Peters were promoted to series regulars.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/orange-is-the-new-black-promoted-dale-soules-series-regular-frieda-1202104866/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Ups Dale Soules To Series Regular |first=Denise |last=Petski |work=Deadline Hollywood |date=May 31, 2017 |accessdate=October 11, 2018}}</ref> On October 17, 2018, Netflix announced that the seventh season would be the series' last and would be released on July 26, 2019.<ref name=\"end\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/10/orange-is-the-new-black-end-season-7.html|title=Orange Is the New Black's Prison Sentence Will End With Season 7  |first=Dee |last=Lockett |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture]] |date=October 17, 2018 |accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"S7ReleaseDate\">{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/orange-is-the-new-black-final-season-premiere-date-photos-video-1202618932/ |title='Orange Is The New Black' Gets Final-Season Premiere Date & Photos \u2013 Watch The Video Announcement |publisher=Deadline Hollywood |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 22, 2019 |accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical response===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#475C61;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 1)|1]]\n| 95% (55 reviews)\n| 79 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#D6D3CE;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 2)|2]]\n| 96% (52 reviews)\n| 89 (31 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#84C0F0;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 3)|3]]\n| 95% (63 reviews)\n| 83 (24 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#C3B091;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 4)|4]]\n| 94% (51 reviews)\n| 86 (19 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#FF803D;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 5)|5]]\n| 71% (49 reviews)\n| 67 (20 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#ACACAC;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 6)|6]]\n| 83% (36 reviews)\n| 69 (14 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#191919;\"|\n| [[Orange Is the New Black (season 7)|7]]\n| 97% (34 reviews)\n| 81 (12 reviews)\n|}\n\n[[File:The cast and crew of 'Orange is the New Black' 2014.jpg|280px|left|thumb|Members of the cast and crew with their [[Peabody Award]], May 2014]]\n''Orange Is the New Black'' was widely acclaimed throughout its run. It has been particularly praised for humanizing prisoners<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/how-orange-is-the-new-black-humanizes-inmates/2013/07/26/d1559bac-f3e5-11e2-9434-60440856fadf_story.html |title=How 'Orange Is the New Black' humanizes inmates |website=[[The Washington Post]] |first=Seth |last=Abramson |date=July 26, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/28263-has-orange-is-the-new-black-changed-the-way-we-think-of-prisoners-former-inmates-say |title=Has 'Orange is the New Black' Changed the Way We Think of Prisoners? Former Inmates Say No, But There's Progress Ahead |website=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |first=Rachel |last=Simon |date=June 17, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref> and for its depiction of race, sexuality, gender and body types.<ref name=\"Great Orange grantland\">{{cite web |url=http://grantland.com/hollywood-prospectus/the-great-orange-is-the-new-black-is-suddenly-the-best-netflix-binge-watch-series-yet/ |title=The Great Orange Is the New Black Is Suddenly the Best Netflix Series Yet |website=[[Grantland]] |first=Andy |last=Greenwald |date=July 15, 2013 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYPost ignites\">{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2014/06/04/orange-is-the-new-black-ignites-a-tv-revolution-for-women/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' ignites a TV revolution for women |website=[[New York Post]] |first=Robert |last=Rorke |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Caged\">{{cite news |first=Mac |last=McClelland |url=http://contentviewer.adobe.com/s/Rolling%20Stone%20Magazine/57ff9f4987144d9c87ed088b3f6faba5/RS1237/0350.R1237_FEA_Orange.html |title=Caged Heat |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |issue=1237 |date=June 18, 2015 |accessdate=January 5, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"What Red Did\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/orange-new-black-prison-sex-women-paleyfest-netflix/ |title='Orange Is the New Black' Cast Dishes on Prison Sex, Women Calling the Shots, and What Red Did |website=[[TheWrap]] |first=L.A. |last=Ross |date=March 15, 2014 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"TVG Cox Breaks\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/orange-new-black-laverne-cox-1068255/ |title=Trans Actress Laverne Cox Breaks New Ground with Orange Is the New Black |first=Sadie |last=Gennis |website=[[TV Guide]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DDot changed\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailydot.com/fandom/orange-new-black-fandom-feminism/ |title=How \"Orange Is the New Black\" changed the way we talk about TV |website=[[The Daily Dot]] |first=Audra |last=Schroeder |date=August 5, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Time New Way\">{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2013/07/25/dead-tree-alert-orange-is-the-new-black-is-the-new-way-of-talking-about-tv/ |title=Dead Tree Alert: Orange Is the New Black Is the New Way of Talking About TV |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=James |last=Poniewozik |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first season received positive reviews from critics. Review aggregator [[Metacritic]] gave it a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 79/100 based on reviews from 32 critics, indicating favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-1/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Orange Is the New Black Season 1 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2013 |accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], season one has a 95% approval rating based on 55 reviews, with an average rating of 8.28/10. The site's critical consensus is \"''Orange Is the New Black'' is a sharp mix of [[black humor]] and dramatic heft, with interesting characters and an intriguing flashback structure.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s01 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 1 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2013 |accessdate=January 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHank Stuever, television critic for ''[[The Washington Post]]'', gave ''Orange Is the New Black'' a perfect score. In his review of the series, he stated: \"In Jenji Kohan's magnificent and thoroughly engrossing new series, ''Orange Is the New Black'', prison is still the pits. But it is also filled with the entire range of human emotion and stories, all of which are brought vividly to life in a world where a stick of gum could ignite either a romance or a death threat.\"<ref name=\"Hank\">{{cite web |last=Steuver |first=Hank |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/netflixs-orange-is-the-new-black-brilliance-behind-bars/2013/07/11/d52f911e-e9aa-11e2-8f22-de4bd2a2bd39_story.html |title=Netflix's ''Orange Is the New Black'': Brilliance behind bars |website=The Washington Post |date=July 11, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013}}</ref> Maureen Ryan, of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', wrote: \"''Orange'' is one of the best new programs of the year, and the six episodes I've seen have left me hungry to see more.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/orange-is-the-new-black_b_3574249.html |title='Orange Is The New Black' Review: Subversive Netflix Prison Drama Proves Addictive |website=The Huffington Post |date=July 10, 2013 |accessdate=August 8, 2013 |last=Ryan |first=Maureen}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim. Rotten Tomatoes gave a rating of 96%, with an average rating of 9.2/10 based on 52 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"With a talented ensemble cast bringing life to a fresh round of serial drama, ''Orange Is the New Black's'' sophomore season lives up to its predecessor's standard for female-led television excellence.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s02 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 2 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2014 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref> Metacritic gave the second season a score of 89/100 based on 31 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-2/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for Orange Is the New Black Season 2 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2014 |accessdate=August 16, 2014}}</ref> David Wiegland of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the season a positive review, calling the first six episodes \"not only as great as the first season, but arguably better.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Orange-Is-the-New-Black-review-Me-vs-we-5526099.php |title='Orange Is the New Black' review: Me vs. we |website=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegland |date=June 3, 2014 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received critical acclaim. On Metacritic, it has a score of 83/100 based on 24 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-3 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 3 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2015 |accessdate=June 16, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 95% rating with an average score of 8.08/10 based on 63 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"Thanks to its blend of potent comedy and rich character work, ''Orange is the New Black'' remains a bittersweet pleasure in its third season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s03 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 3 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2015 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received critical acclaim. On Metacritic, it has a score of 86/100 based on 19 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-4 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 4 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2016 |accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 94% rating with an average score of 8.46/10 based on 51 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Orange is the New Black'' is back and better than ever, with a powerful fourth season full of compelling performances by the ensemble cast.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s04 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 4 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2016 |accessdate=July 25, 2016}}</ref> James Poniewozik of ''The New York Times'' reviewed the fourth season as \"Do you measure the quality of a TV season as a beginning-to-end average or by how well it ends? By the first yardstick, Season 4 is ambitious but uneven; by the latter, it's the series' best.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/24/arts/television/season-4-of-orange-is-the-new-black-its-about-time.html |title=Orange Is The New Black: It's About Time |website=The New York Times |first=James |last=Poniewozik |date=June 22, 2016 |accessdate=September 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe fifth season received \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref name=MC>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-5 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 5 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2017 |accessdate=June 10, 2017}}</ref> On Metacritic, it has a score of 67/100 based on 20 reviews.<ref name=MC /> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 71% rating with an average score of 7.29/10 based on 49 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"''Orange Is the New Black''{{'}}s fifth season offers up more of the sharp writing and dizzying tonal juggling acts that fans expect \u2013 albeit somewhat less successfully.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s05 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 5 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2017 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe sixth season received positive reviews from critics, with many critics noting its improvement over the previous season. On Metacritic, it has a score of 69/100 based on 14 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-6|title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 6 |publisher=Metacritic |year=2018 |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has an 83% rating with an average score of 7.3/10 based on 36 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads: \"Brutality and humor continue to mesh effectively in a season of ''Orange Is the New Black'' that stands as a marked improvement from its predecessor, even if some arcs are more inspired than others.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s06 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 6 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2018 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe seventh season has a score of 81/100 on Metacritic based on 12 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/season-7 |title=Orange is the New Black: Season 7 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |year=2019 |accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 97% rating with an average score of 7.69/10 based on 34 reviews. The site's consensus reads: \"Carried by its exceptional ensemble, ''Orange Is the New Black''{{'}}s  final season gets straight to the point, tackling hard-hitting issues with the same dramatic depth and gallows humor that made the show so ground-breaking to begin with\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/orange-is-the-new-black/s07 |title=Orange Is the New Black: Season 7 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |year=2019 |accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, ''Orange Is the New Black'' was ranked 58th on ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s list of the 100 best TV shows of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web |title=The 100 best TV shows of the 21st century |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/16/100-best-tv-shows-of-the-21st-century |website=The Guardian |date=September 13, 2019 |accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Orange Is the New Black}}\n\n''Orange Is the New Black'' has received many accolades since its debut. The series has garnered 16 [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]] nominations and four wins. For its first season, it received 12 Emmy Award nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Outstanding Comedy Series]], [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series]], and [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series|Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series]], winning three.<ref name=\"Emmy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.emmys.com/shows/orange-new-black |title=Orange Is The New Black |publisher=Television Academy |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> [[Taylor Schilling]] received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Actress in a Television Series \u2013 Drama]].<ref name=\"GG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hfpa.org/browse/?param=/film/26477 |title=Orange is the New Black |publisher=[[Hollywood Foreign Press Association]] |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> In 2013, the [[American Film Institute]] selected the series as one of the Top 10 Television Programs of the Year.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afi.com/afiawards/AFIAwards13.aspx |title=AFI Awards 2013 |publisher=American Film Institute |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nA new Emmy rule in 2015, classifying half-hour shows as comedies and hour-long shows as dramas, forced the series to change categories from comedy to drama for its second season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/16/8976181/emmys-nominations-comedy-drama |title=7 Emmys Rules and Quirks that Explain the 2015 Nominations |first=Emily |last=VanDerWerff |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> That year, the series received four Emmy nominations, including [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Drama Series|Outstanding Drama Series]], and Aduba won her second Emmy Award, for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Supporting Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref name=\"Emmy\" /> ''Orange Is the New Black'' became the first series to receive Emmy nominations in both comedy and drama categories.<ref name=\"Birnbaum\" /> For its second season, the series also received three Golden Globe Award nominations: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actress \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for Schilling, and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film]] for Aduba. At the [[21st Screen Actors Guild Awards]], the series won [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series]] and Aduba won [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sag-award-winners-2015-screen-actors-guild-awards-winner-list-1201414657/ |title=SAG Award Winners 2015: Full List |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=January 25, 2015 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor its third season, ''Orange Is the New Black'' won Screen Actors Guild Awards for Outstanding Performance by an Ensemble in a Comedy Series and Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Comedy Series (Aduba).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2016-sag-winners-complete-list-856945/item/outstanding-performance-by-a-female-846040 |title=SAG Awards: The Complete Winners List |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 30, 2016 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> It received a Golden Globe Award nomination for Best Television Series \u2013 Musical or Comedy.<ref name=\"GG\" /> The series has also received, among other accolades, six [[Writers Guild of America Award]] nominations,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners |title=Previous Nominees & Winners |publisher=[[Writers Guild of America]] |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> five [[Satellite Awards]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2013/ |title=2013 Satellite Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2015/ |title=2015 Satellite Awards |publisher=[[International Press Academy]] |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> four [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]s,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/critics-choice-television-awards-2014-712986 |title=Critics' Choice Television Awards 2014: Complete Winners List |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=June 19, 2014 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/critics-choice-television-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201509015/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards Winners: Full List |website=Variety |date=May 31, 2015 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref> a [[GLAAD Media Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glaad.org/blog/george-takei-orange-new-black-concussion-among-glaadawards-recipients-new-york-city |title=George Takei, \"Orange is the New Black,\" \"Concussion\" among #GLAADAwards recipients in New York City |publisher=[[GLAAD]] |date=May 3, 2014 |accessdate=April 15, 2016}}</ref> an [[American Cinema Editors Awards 2016|American Cinema Editors Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/2016-ace-eddie-award-nominations-851748 |title='Star Wars' Among Nominees for ACE Eddie Awards for Film Editing |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 4, 2016 |accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> a [[Producers Guild of America Award for Best Episodic Comedy|Producers Guild of America Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pga-awards-orange-is-new-766654 |title=PGA Awards: 'Orange Is the New Black' Wins Outstanding Producer of Episodic Television, Comedy |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 24, 2015 |accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> and a [[Peabody Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.peabodyawards.com/award-profile/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix |title=Orange is the New Black (Netflix) |publisher=Peabody Awards |accessdate=April 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\n{{quote box|width=270px|align=left| quote=Netflix is famously tight-fisted when it comes to offering up viewership data about its original series. But execs with the streaming giant have repeatedly confirmed that ''OITNB'' is its most-watched original series. That has been backed up by the efforts of outside measurement companies to track viewing in the Netflix eco-system.|source=\u2014''Variety''<ref name=\"rating\" />}}\n\nThe series began airing on broadcast television in [[New Zealand]], on [[TVNZ 2|TV2]], on August 19, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/orange-is-the-new-black/index-group-5523557 |title=Orange Is The New Black |website=TVNZ |accessdate=August 22, 2013}}</ref> It premiered in [[Australia]] on October 9, 2013, on [[Showcase (Australian TV channel)|Showcase]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/09/airdate-orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Airdate: Orange is the New Black |website=TV Tonight |date=September 9, 2013 |first=David |last=Knox |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref> The second season began on Showcase on July 16, 2014,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxtel.com.au/got/whats-on/foxtel-insider/foxtel/most-anticipated-returning-shows.html |title=Most anticipated returning shows in 2014 |website=Foxtel |date=January 14, 2014 |accessdate=July 26, 2014}}</ref> and the third season premiered on June 11, 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxtel.com.au/got/whats-on/foxtel-insider/showcase/orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Orange is the New Black S3: same time as the US |website=Foxtel |date=June 4, 2015 |accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref> The first season began airing on broadcast television in the [[United Kingdom|UK]] on [[Sony Channel (UK and Ireland)|Sony Channel]] from April 19, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/orange-is-new-black-uk-linear-rights-go-sony-channel-988468 |title=Sony Channel U.K. Takes 'Orange Is the New Black' |last=Szalai |first=Georg |date=March 24, 2017 |website=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=March 24, 2017}}</ref> It has been shown in [[Ireland]] on [[TG4]] since January 15, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tg4.ie/en/programmes/orange-is-the-new-black/|title=Orange Is The New Black|website=tg4.ie}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, it was reported that a [[Cybercrime|cybercriminal]] had stolen the first ten episodes of season 5, in a security breach of a post-production company. Netflix failed to respond to ransom demands, and the cybercriminal [[internet leak|leaked]] the episodes online. Netflix confirmed the security breach and an ongoing investigation by federal law enforcement.<ref name=\"S5 Leaked\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hacker-threatens-release-new-episodes-orange-is-new-black-998670 |title=Hacker Releases New Episodes of 'Orange Is the New Black |website=The Hollywood Reporter |agency=Associated Press |date=April 28, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/29/business/media/netflix-hack-orange-is-the-new-black.html |title=Hacker Leaks Episodes From Netflix Show and Threatens Other Networks |work =The New York Times |last1=Perlroth |first1=Nicole |last2=Haag |first2=Matthew |date=April 29, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Multichannel News]]'' reported that demand for the series significantly increased over the seven-day period following the leak of the episodes. It was also said that the leak would likely cause a decrease in demand for the fifth season when Netflix released it in June 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.multichannel.com/blog/bauminator/demand-orange-new-black-spiked-following-hack/412744 |title=Demand for 'Orange Is the New Black' Spiked Following Hack |website=[[Multichannel News]] |date=May 10, 2017 |first=Jeff |last=Baumgartner |accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Ratings===\n''Orange Is the New Black'' generated more viewers and hours viewed in its first week than the other top Netflix original series ''[[House of Cards (U.S. TV series)|House of Cards]]'' and ''[[Arrested Development (TV series)|Arrested Development]]''.<ref name=\"Grantland\">{{cite web |url=http://grantland.com/features/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix-season-two/ |title=Brilliant 'Orange' |website=[[Grantland]] |first=Andy |last=Greenwald |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://allthingsd.com/20130723/netflixs-no-name-show-beating-house-of-cards-and-arrested-development/ |title=Netflix's No-Name Show Beating \"House of Cards\" and \"Arrested Development\" |website=[[All Things Digital]] |date=July 23, 2013 |accessdate=December 10, 2013 |last=Kafka |first=Peter}}</ref> In October 2013, Netflix stated that the show is a \"tremendous success\" for the streaming platform. \"It will end the year as our most watched original series ever and, as with each of our other previously launched originals, enjoys an audience comparable with successful shows on cable and broadcast TV.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/10/21/netflix-orange-is-the-new-black-most-watched/ |title=Netflix: 'Orange Is The New Black' Is Our Most-Watched Original, But Our TV Exclusives Are Even Bigger |website=[[TechCrunch]] |first=Anthony |last=Ha |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=February 12, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mashable.com/2013/10/21/orange-is-the-new-black-netflix-most-watched/#YHlOr3Wcb8qw |title='Orange Is the New Black' Is Netflix's Most-Watched Original Series |website=[[Mashable]] |first=Brian Anthony |last=Hernandez |date=October 21, 2013 |accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> As reported in February 2016, ''Orange Is the New Black'' remained Netflix's most-watched original series.<ref name=\"rating\" /><ref name=\"rating2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/netflix-renews-orange-is-the-new-black-for-three-more-series-a6855626.html |title=Netflix renews Orange is the New Black for three more series |work=[[The Independent]] |first=Jess |last=Denham |date=February 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/feb/05/orange-is-the-new-black-renewed-new-season-netflix |title=Orange is the New Black renewed for three additional seasons |work=[[The Guardian]] |first=Nigel M |last=Smith |date=February 5, 2016 |accessdate=April 19, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, a ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' study of the 50 TV shows with the most [[List of Facebook features#Likes and Reactions|Facebook Likes]] found that ''Orange Is the New Black'' is one of the shows most watched in [[urban area]]s, and despite its \"minority-rich ensemble cast\", the series \"appeals more to a white audience\".<ref name=\"katz20161227\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/12/26/upshot/duck-dynasty-vs-modern-family-television-maps.html |title='Duck Dynasty' vs. 'Modern Family': 50 Maps of the U.S. Cultural Divide |last=Katz |first=Josh |date=December 27, 2016 |accessdate=December 28, 2016 |work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Incarceration of women in the United States]]\n* [[List of dramatic television series with LGBT characters]]\n* [[List of LGBT characters in television and radio]]\n* [[Prison\u2013industrial complex]]\n* ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]''\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news| url=http://thedianerehmshow.org/shows/2014-06-09/piper-kerman-her-story-inspired-netflix-series-orange-new-black| title= Piper Kerman On Her Story That Inspired The Netflix Series ''Orange Is The New Black''|date=June 2014|work=[[The Diane Rehm Show]]}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Orange Is the New Black}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Netflix title|70242311}}\n*{{IMDb title|2372162|Orange Is the New Black}}\n\n{{Orange Is the New Black}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Orange Is the New Black|Awards for ''Orange Is the New Black'']]\n|list =\n{{Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Comedy Series}}\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Comedy Series}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for