levision shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Transgender-related television programs]]\n", "name_user": "2a00:23c8:7004:5a01:9c54:2260:5fbd:8eaa", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(i fixed a typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_Is_the_New_Black"}
{"title_page": "Politics of Aberdeen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\nThe '''Politics of [[Aberdeen]]''', [[Scotland]] have changed significantly in recent years. In 1996, under the [[Local Government etc. (Scotland) Act 1994]], [[Grampian|Grampian Regional Council]] and Aberdeen District Council were dissolved, creating the new unitary [[Aberdeen City Council]] to represent the city's [[Council areas of Scotland|council area]].\n\n==Aberdeen City Council==\n[[Aberdeen City Council]] represents the Aberdeen City [[Council areas of Scotland|council area]] of [[Scotland]].\n\nThe council area was created in 1996, under the [[Local Government etc. (Scotland) Act 1994]]. However, a sense of Aberdeen as a [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]], with its own city council, can be traced back to 1900, when the [[Counties of Scotland|city of county]] of Aberdeen was created.\n \nIn 1975, under the [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973]], the county of city was combined with [[Bucksburn]], [[Dyce]], Newhills, Old Machar, [[Peterculter]] and the Stoneywood areas of the [[county of Aberdeen]] and, the [[Nigg, Aberdeen|Nigg]] area of the [[county of Kincardine]], (including [[Cove Bay]]) to form the Aberdeen district of the [[Grampian]] [[Regions and districts of Scotland|region]]. This district became the now existing [[unitary council area]] in 1996.\n\nOn 9 May 1995, by resolution under section 23 of the [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973]], The City of Aberdeen Council changed the name of the local government area of \"City of Aberdeen\" to \"Aberdeen City\".\n\n==Composition==\nBetween 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat]] and [[Scottish Conservative and Unionist Party|Conservative]] coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council. Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] stronghold.<ref>{{cite news|first=Scott|last=David|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1443312002|title=Labour is set to lose council strongholds in elections|work=The Scotsman|date=2002-12-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060109233442/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1443312002|archivedate=9 January 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following the [[2007 Aberdeen City Council election|May 2007 election]], contested for the first time using a system of [[proportional representation]], the [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]] and the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) formed a coalition to run the council, holding 27 of the 43 seats (following an SNP by-election gain from the Conservatives on 16 August 2007, the Liberal Democrat/SNP coalition held 28 of the 43 seats). At the [[2012 Aberdeen City Council election|May 2012 election]], Labour entered into a coalition with the Conservatives and the [[Independent (politics)|independents]] to run the council, with 23 out of the 43 seats.\n\nAberdeen City Council comprises forty-three councillors, who represent the city's thirteen [[ward (politics)|wards]], and is chaired by the [[List of Provosts and Lord Provosts of Aberdeen|Lord Provost]].\n\n==New wards from May 2007==\nBefore May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards, but since then, all seats were contested by the [[first-past-the-post]] electoral system. On 5 May 2007, it was the first [[2007 Aberdeen City Council election|election]] to use the [[single transferable vote]] system of election and multi-member [[ward (politics)|ward]]s, each ward electing three or four councillors. The [[Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland]] completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the [[council areas of Scotland]] and for [[Aberdeen]] it was concluded that there would be 13 multi-member wards with a total of 43 councillors. This system was introduced as a result of the [[Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004]], and was designed to produce a form of [[proportional representation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electoralcommission.gov.uk/your-area/scotelections2007.cfm|title=Scottish elections 2007|publisher=The Electoral Commission|accessdate=2007-02-08 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070127122545/http://www.electoralcommission.gov.uk/your-area/scotelections2007.cfm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-01-27}}</ref>\n\nThe composition of wards changed to:\n\n'''3 councillors:'''\n*(11) Airyhall/[[Broomhill, Aberdeen|Broomhill]]/[[Garthdee]]\n*(8) George Street/Harbour\n*(5) [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]/Stockethill\n*(13) [[Kincorth]]/Loirston\n*(3) [[Kingswells]]/Sheddocksley\n*(9) Lower Deeside\n*(7) [[Midstocket]]/[[Rosemount, Aberdeen|Rosemount]]\n*(4) Northfield\n*(6) [[Tillydrone]]/Seaton/[[Old Aberdeen]]\n\n'''4 councillors:'''\n*(2) [[Bridge of Don]]\n*(1) [[Dyce]]/[[Bucksburn]]/[[Danestone]]\n*(10) [[Hazlehead, Aberdeen|Hazlehead]]/Ashley/[[Queen's Cross|Queens Cross]]\n*(12) [[Torry]]/[[Ferryhill, Aberdeen|Ferryhill]]\n\n'''Name changes'''\n*(3) Kingswells/Sheddocksley to [[Kingswells]]/Sheddocksley/[[Summerhill, Aberdeen|Summerhill]]\n*(4) Northfield to Northfield/[[Mastrick]] North\n*(5) Hilton/Stockethill to [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]/[[Woodside, Aberdeen|Woodside]]/Stockethill\n*(13) Kincorth/Loirston to [[Kincorth]]/[[Nigg, Aberdeen|Nigg]]/[[Cove Bay|Cove]]\n\n==Composition (2012\u20132017)==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"180\"|'''Ward'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Councillors'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"5\"|\n|-\n|Dyce/Bucksburn/Danestone\n|Barney Crockett\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Graeme Lawrence\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Neil MacGregor\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gill Samarai\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Bridge of Don\n|Muriel Jaffrey\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|John Reynolds\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|Sandy Stuart\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Willie Young\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Kingswells/Sheddocksley/Summerhill\n|David Cameron\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Steve Delaney\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Len Ironside\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Northfield/Mastrick North\n|Scott Carle\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jackie Dunbar\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gordon Graham\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Hilton/Woodside/Stockethill\n|George Adam\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Kirsty Blackmann (\"n\u00e9e\" West)\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Lesley Dunbar\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Tillydrone/Seaton/Old Aberdeen\n|Ross Grant\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Ramsey Milne\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jim Noble\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Midstocket/Rosemount\n|Bill Cormie\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Fraser Forsyth\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|Jenny Laing\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|George Street/Harbour\n|Andrew May\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jean Morrison\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Nathan Morrison\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Lower Deeside\n|Mary Boulton\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|M. Tauqeer Malik\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Aileen Malone\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Hazlehead/Ashley/Queens Cross\n|John Corall\n|SNP\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Martin Greig\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jennifer Stewart\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Ross Thomson \n|Conservative\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Airyhall/Broomhill/Garthdee\n|Angela Taylor\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gordon Townson\n|SNP\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Ian Yuill\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Torry/Ferryhill\n|Yvonne Allan\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Graham Dickson\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Alan Donnelly\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|Jim Kiddle\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Kincorth/Nigg/Cove\n|Neil Cooney\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Andrew Finlayson\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|[[Callum McCaig]]\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|}\n\n==Changes since 2012 Election==\n*In January 2014, Torry/Ferryhill Cllr Alan Donnelly was expelled from the Conservative Party group and sits as an Independent.\n*In May 2014, Midstocket/Rosemount Cllr Jenny Laing replaced Dyce/Bucksburn/Danestone Cllr Barney Crockett as Leader of the Council.\n*In May 2014, Midstocket/Rosemount Cllr Fraser Forsyth resigned from the Conservative Party group and sits as an Independent.\n\n==Composition (2007\u20132012)==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"180\"|'''Ward'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Councillors'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"5\"|\n|-\n|Dyce/Bucksburn/Danestone\n|Ron Clark\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Barney Crockett\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|[[Mark McDonald (politician)|Mark McDonald]]\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|George Penny\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Bridge of Don\n|Muriel Jaffrey\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gordon Leslie\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|John Reynolds\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Willie Young\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Kingswells/Sheddocksley\n|Len Ironside\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Peter Stephen\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Wendy Stuart\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Northfield\n|Jackie Dunbar\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gordon Graham\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|[[Kevin Stewart (Scottish politician)|Kevin Stewart]]\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Hilton/Stockethill\n|George Adam\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Neil Fletcher\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Kirsty West\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Tillydrone/Seaton/Old Aberdeen\n|Norman Collie\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jim Noble\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Richard Robertson\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Midstocket/Rosemount\n|Bill Cormie\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jenny Laing\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|John Corral\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|George Street/Harbour\n|Andrew May\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jim Hunter\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|John Stewart\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Lower Deeside\n|Mary Boulton\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|Aileen Malone\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Alan Milne\n|Conservative\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Hazlehead/Ashley/Queens Cross\n|Jim Farquharson\n|Conservative\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Martin Greig\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jennifer Stewart\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|[[John West (Scottish politician)|John West]] \n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Airyhall/Broomhill/Garthdee\n|Scott Cassie\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jill Wisely\n|Conservative\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Ian Yuill\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Torry/Ferryhill\n|Yvonne Allan\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Irene Cormack\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Alan Donnelly\n|Conservative\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jim Kiddle\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Kincorth/Loirston\n|Neil Cooney\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Kate Dean\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|[[Callum McCaig]]\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|''Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927031823/http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/ACCI/nmsruntime/saveasdialog.asp?lID=9433&sID=4858]''\n|}\n\n==Changes since 2007 Election==\n*A by-election was held in the Midstocket/Rosemount Ward following the death of the Conservatives' John Porter on 23 May 2007. The by-election, on 16 August 2007, was won by the SNP's John Corall.\n*In January 2011, Tillydrone/Seaton/Old Aberdeen Cllr Norman Collie resigned from the Labour Party and sat as an Independent.\n*A by-election was held in the Dyce/Bucksburn/Danestone Ward following the death of the Liberal Democrat's Ron Clark on 21 February 2011. The by-election, on 19 May 2011, was won by the SNP's Neil MacGregor.\n*In June 2011, Hazlehead/Ashley/Queens Cross Cllr Jim Farquaharson was expelled from the Conservative Party and sat as an Independent.\n*In June 2011, Lower Deeside Cllr Alan Milne was expelled from the Conservative Party and sat as an Independent.\n*A by-election was held in the Airyhall/Broomhill/Garthdee Ward following the resignation of the Liberal Democrat's Scott Cassie on 27 April 2011 after he was jailed for embezzlement. The by-election, on 23 June 2011, was won by the SNP's Gordon Scott Townson.\n*In September 2011, Bridge of Don Cllr Gordon Leslie was suspended from the Liberal Democrats. He subsequently resigned from the party and sat as an Independent.\n*In February 2012, George Street/Harbour Cllr Jim Hunter was suspended from the Labour Party. He subsequently resigned from the party and sat as an Independent.\n*In March 2012, Bridge of Don Cllr John Reynolds resigned from the Liberal Democrats and sat as an Independent.\n\n==Composition (2003\u20132007)==\nThe previous composition of 43 wards while using the standard [[first-past-the-post]] voting system. Their representative councillors and political parties were:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Ward'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Councillor'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(34) Ashley\n|Martin Greig\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(9) Auchmill\n|[[Kevin Stewart (Scottish politician)|Kevin Stewart]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n| Labour\n|(2) Bankhead/Stoneywood\n|Brian Rattary\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(21) [[Berryden]]\n|John Stewart\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(6) [[Bridge of Don]]\n|Millie McLeod\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(35) [[Broomhill, Aberdeen|Broomhill]]\n|Ian Yuill\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(28) Castlehill\n|Jim Hunter\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(32) [[Cults, Aberdeen|Cults]]\n|Aileen Malone\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(10) Cummings Park\n|Gordon Graham\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(3) [[Danestone]]\n|Raymond Hutcheon\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(7) Donmouth\n|Muriel Jaffrey\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(38) Duthie\n|Irene Cormack\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(1) Dyce\n|Ron Clark\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(36) [[Garthdee]]\n|Scott Cassie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(26) Gilcomston\n|Alison Smith\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(29) [[Hazlehead, Aberdeen|Hazlehead]]\n|Karen Freel\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(15) [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]\n|George Adam\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(37) Holburn\n|David Falconer\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(4) Jesmond\n|Gordon Leslie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(42) [[Kincorth]] East\n|George Urquhart\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"white\"|\n|Independent\n|(41) Kincorth West\n|David Clyne\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(19) [[Kittybrewster]]\n|Neil Fletcher\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(27) Langstane\n|Steve Delaney\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(43) Loirston\n|Katherine Dean\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(33) [[Mannofield]]\n|Jill Wisely\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(12) [[Mastrick]]\n|Ramsey Milne\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(24) [[Midstocket]]\n|John Porter\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(31) Murtle\n|Matthew Duncan\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(8) Newhills\n|Peter Stephen\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(5) Oldmachar\n|John Reynolds\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(30) [[Peterculter]]\n|Pamela MacDonald\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(23) Pittodrie\n|Ronald Webster\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(25) [[Queen's Cross|Queens Cross]]\n|Brenda Craig\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(18) Seaton\n|Norman Collie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(13) Sheddocksley\n|James Lamond\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(11) Springhill\n|Karen Shirron\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(17) St. Machar\n|Sandra Macdonald\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(20) Stockethill\n|June Lamond\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(14) [[Summerhill, Aberdeen|Summerhill]]\n|Len Ironside\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(22) Sunnybank\n|Andrew May\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(39) [[Torry]]\n|Yvonne Allan\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(40) Tullos\n|Jim Kiddie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(16) [[Woodside, Aberdeen|Woodside]]/[[Tillydrone]]\n|Alan Gowers\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|''Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210230442/http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/acci/web/site/xac_Councillor.asp?s=2 Aberdeen City Council]''\n|}\n\n==UK Parliament==\nIn the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom Parliament]], the city is divided between three [[constituencies]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Constituency'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Member'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]]\n|[[Kirsty Blackman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n|[[Stephen Flynn (Scottish politician)|Stephen Flynn]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Gordon (UK Parliament constituency)|Gordon]]\n|[[Richard Thomson (politician)|Richard Thomson]]\n|}\n\n==Scottish Parliament==\nThere are three [[Scottish Parliament]] constituencies that overlap the Aberdeen City Council area in the [[North East Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|North East Scotland]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|electoral region]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Constituency'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Member'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen Central (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen Central]]\n|[[Kevin Stewart (Scottish politician)|Kevin Stewart]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Independent/meta/color}}\"|\n|Independent\n|[[Aberdeen Donside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen Donside]]\n|[[Mark McDonald (politician)|Mark McDonald]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen South and North Kincardine (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South and North Kincardine]]\n|[[Maureen Watt]]\n|}\n\nOther [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSPs]] in the [[North East Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|North East Scotland]] electoral region (but selected by the [[Mixed member proportional representation|Additional Member]] proportional representation system, and not in constituencies overlapping Aberdeen City or the Aberdeen City Council area) are:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Members'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|[[Lewis MacDonald]]\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|[[Jenny Marra]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Peter Chapman (politician)|Peter Chapman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Bill Bowman (Scottish politician)|Bill Bowman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Liam Kerr]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Tom Mason (Scottish politician)|Tom Mason]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|[[Mike Rumbles]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Scottish independence referendum==\n{{main|Scottish independence referendum, 2014}}\nIn 2014 a referendum was held asking voters in [[Scotland]] the question: \"Should Scotland be an independent country?\" The referendum was held by the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] administration after their victory in the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election]] to determine whether Scotland should become an [[Sovereign state|independent nation]] or remain a [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved part]] of the [[United Kingdom]]. Of the 3,623,344 votes cast (on a turnout of 84.6%) 2,001,926 were in favour of a \"No\" vote (55.3%) while 1,617,989 were \"Yes\" (44.7%): leading to Scotland remaining part of the United Kingdom.\n\nThe Aberdeen City local authority area had a higher than average No vote. 84,094 voters in the area voted against independence (58.6%) while 59,390 voted in favour of independence (41.4%). The Aberdeen City council area had the third lowest turnout in Scotland with 143,484 valid ballot papers on a turnout of 81.7%, ahead of [[Dundee]] and [[Glasgow]].\n\n==Twinned cities==\nAberdeen is [[Town twinning|twinned]] with several cities across Europe and throughout the rest of the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/ACCI/web/site/Tourism/SL/tur_TownTwinning.asp|title=Twinning|publisher=Aberdeen City Council|accessdate=2007-02-08}}</ref> These include:\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} - [[Bulawayo]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} - [[Clermont-Ferrand]], [[France]]\n* {{flagicon|Belarus}} - [[Gomel]], [[Belarus]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{flagicon|United States}} - [[Houston]], [[United States]] (as part of [[Grampian]])\n* {{flagicon|Germany}} - [[Regensburg]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|Norway}} - [[Stavanger]], [[Norway]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Aberdeen City Youth Council]]\n*[[Politics of Dundee]]\n*[[Politics of Edinburgh]]\n*[[Politics of Glasgow]]\n*[[Politics of Scotland]]\n*[[Politics of the Highland council area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070307172247/http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/ACCI/web/site/home/home.asp Council website]\n\n{{Aberdeen}}\n{{Former local government regions of Scotland}} \n\n[[Category:Politics of Aberdeen| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2017}}\nThe '''Politics of [[Aberdeen]]''', [[Scotland]] have changed significantly in recent years. In 1996, under the [[Local Government etc. (Scotland) Act 1994]], [[Grampian|Grampian Regional Council]] and Aberdeen District Council were dissolved, creating the new unitary [[Aberdeen City Council]] to represent the city's [[Council areas of Scotland|council area]].\n\n==Aberdeen City Council==\n[[Aberdeen City Council]] represents the Aberdeen City [[Council areas of Scotland|council area]] of [[Scotland]].\n\nThe council area was created in 1996, under the [[Local Government etc. (Scotland) Act 1994]]. However, a sense of Aberdeen as a [[City status in the United Kingdom|city]], with its own city council, can be traced back to 1900, when the [[Counties of Scotland|city of county]] of Aberdeen was created.\n \nIn 1975, under the [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973]], the county of city was combined with [[Bucksburn]], [[Dyce]], Newhills, Old Machar, [[Peterculter]] and the Stoneywood areas of the [[county of Aberdeen]] and, the [[Nigg, Aberdeen|Nigg]] area of the [[county of Kincardine]], (including [[Cove Bay]]) to form the Aberdeen district of the [[Grampian]] [[Regions and districts of Scotland|region]]. This district became the now existing [[unitary council area]] in 1996.\n\nOn 9 May 1995, by resolution under section 23 of the [[Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973]], The City of Aberdeen Council changed the name of the local government area of \"City of Aberdeen\" to \"Aberdeen City\".\n\n==Composition==\nBetween 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat]] and [[Scottish Conservative and Unionist Party|Conservative]] coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council. Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a [[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]] stronghold.<ref>{{cite news|first=Scott|last=David|url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1443312002|title=Labour is set to lose council strongholds in elections|work=The Scotsman|date=2002-12-30|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060109233442/http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1443312002|archivedate=9 January 2006|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Following the [[2007 Aberdeen City Council election|May 2007 election]], contested for the first time using a system of [[proportional representation]], the [[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]] and the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) formed a coalition to run the council, holding 27 of the 43 seats (following an SNP by-election gain from the Conservatives on 16 August 2007, the Liberal Democrat/SNP coalition held 28 of the 43 seats). At the [[2012 Aberdeen City Council election|May 2012 election]], Labour entered into a coalition with the Conservatives and the [[Independent (politics)|independents]] to run the council, with 23 out of the 43 seats.\n\nAberdeen City Council comprises forty-three councillors, who represent the city's thirteen [[ward (politics)|wards]], and is chaired by the [[List of Provosts and Lord Provosts of Aberdeen|Lord Provost]].\n\n==New wards from May 2007==\nBefore May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards, but since then, all seats were contested by the [[first-past-the-post]] electoral system. On 5 May 2007, it was the first [[2007 Aberdeen City Council election|election]] to use the [[single transferable vote]] system of election and multi-member [[ward (politics)|ward]]s, each ward electing three or four councillors. The [[Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland]] completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the [[council areas of Scotland]] and for [[Aberdeen]] it was concluded that there would be 13 multi-member wards with a total of 43 councillors. This system was introduced as a result of the [[Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004]], and was designed to produce a form of [[proportional representation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electoralcommission.gov.uk/your-area/scotelections2007.cfm|title=Scottish elections 2007|publisher=The Electoral Commission|accessdate=2007-02-08 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070127122545/http://www.electoralcommission.gov.uk/your-area/scotelections2007.cfm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-01-27}}</ref>\n\nThe composition of wards changed to:\n\n'''3 councillors:'''\n*(11) Airyhall/[[Broomhill, Aberdeen|Broomhill]]/[[Garthdee]]\n*(8) George Street/Harbour\n*(5) [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]/Stockethill\n*(13) [[Kincorth]]/Loirston\n*(3) [[Kingswells]]/Sheddocksley\n*(9) Lower Deeside\n*(7) [[Midstocket]]/[[Rosemount, Aberdeen|Rosemount]]\n*(4) Northfield\n*(6) [[Tillydrone]]/Seaton/[[Old Aberdeen]]\n\n'''4 councillors:'''\n*(2) [[Bridge of Don]]\n*(1) [[Dyce]]/[[Bucksburn]]/[[Danestone]]\n*(10) [[Hazlehead, Aberdeen|Hazlehead]]/Ashley/[[Queen's Cross|Queens Cross]]\n*(12) [[Torry]]/[[Ferryhill, Aberdeen|Ferryhill]]\n\n'''Name changes'''\n*(3) Kingswells/Sheddocksley to [[Kingswells]]/Sheddocksley/[[Summerhill, Aberdeen|Summerhill]]\n*(4) Northfield to Northfield/[[Mastrick]] North\n*(5) Hilton/Stockethill to [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]/[[Woodside, Aberdeen|Woodside]]/Stockethill\n*(13) Kincorth/Loirston to [[Kincorth]]/[[Nigg, Aberdeen|Nigg]]/[[Cove Bay|Cove]]\n\n==Composition (2012\u20132017)==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"180\"|'''Ward'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Councillors'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"5\"|\n|-\n|Dyce/Bucksburn/Danestone\n|Barney Crockett\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Graeme Lawrence\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Neil MacGregor\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gill Samarai\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Bridge of Don\n|Muriel Jaffrey\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|John Reynolds\n|Independent\n|\n|-\n|\n|Sandy Stuart\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Willie Young\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Kingswells/Sheddocksley/Summerhill\n|David Cameron\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Steve Delaney\n|Liberal Democrat\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Len Ironside\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Northfield/Mastrick North\n|Scott Carle\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Jackie Dunbar\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Gordon Graham\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Hilton/Woodside/Stockethill\n|George Adam\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Kirsty Blackmann (\"n\u00e9e\" West)\n|Scottish National Party\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|\n|Lesley Dunbar\n|Labour\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|-\n|Tillydrone/Seaton/Old Aberdeen\n|Ross Grant\n|Labou