 the Conservative Party and sat as an Independent.\n*In June 2011, Lower Deeside Cllr Alan Milne was expelled from the Conservative Party and sat as an Independent.\n*A by-election was held in the Airyhall/Broomhill/Garthdee Ward following the resignation of the Liberal Democrat's Scott Cassie on 27 April 2011 after he was jailed for embezzlement. The by-election, on 23 June 2011, was won by the SNP's Gordon Scott Townson.\n*In September 2011, Bridge of Don Cllr Gordon Leslie was suspended from the Liberal Democrats. He subsequently resigned from the party and sat as an Independent.\n*In February 2012, George Street/Harbour Cllr Jim Hunter was suspended from the Labour Party. He subsequently resigned from the party and sat as an Independent.\n*In March 2012, Bridge of Don Cllr John Reynolds resigned from the Liberal Democrats and sat as an Independent.\n\n==Composition (2003\u20132007)==\nThe previous composition of 43 wards while using the standard [[first-past-the-post]] voting system. Their representative councillors and political parties were:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Ward'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Councillor'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(34) Ashley\n|Martin Greig\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(9) Auchmill\n|[[Kevin Stewart (Scottish politician)|Kevin Stewart]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n| Labour\n|(2) Bankhead/Stoneywood\n|Brian Rattary\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(21) [[Berryden]]\n|John Stewart\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(6) [[Bridge of Don]]\n|Millie McLeod\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(35) [[Broomhill, Aberdeen|Broomhill]]\n|Ian Yuill\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(28) Castlehill\n|Jim Hunter\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(32) [[Cults, Aberdeen|Cults]]\n|Aileen Malone\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(10) Cummings Park\n|Gordon Graham\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(3) [[Danestone]]\n|Raymond Hutcheon\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(7) Donmouth\n|Muriel Jaffrey\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(38) Duthie\n|Irene Cormack\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(1) Dyce\n|Ron Clark\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(36) [[Garthdee]]\n|Scott Cassie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(26) Gilcomston\n|Alison Smith\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(29) [[Hazlehead, Aberdeen|Hazlehead]]\n|Karen Freel\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(15) [[Hilton, Aberdeen|Hilton]]\n|George Adam\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(37) Holburn\n|David Falconer\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(4) Jesmond\n|Gordon Leslie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(42) [[Kincorth]] East\n|George Urquhart\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"white\"|\n|Independent\n|(41) Kincorth West\n|David Clyne\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(19) [[Kittybrewster]]\n|Neil Fletcher\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(27) Langstane\n|Steve Delaney\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(43) Loirston\n|Katherine Dean\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(33) [[Mannofield]]\n|Jill Wisely\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(12) [[Mastrick]]\n|Ramsey Milne\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(24) [[Midstocket]]\n|John Porter\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(31) Murtle\n|Matthew Duncan\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(8) Newhills\n|Peter Stephen\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(5) Oldmachar\n|John Reynolds\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|(30) [[Peterculter]]\n|Pamela MacDonald\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(23) Pittodrie\n|Ronald Webster\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|(25) [[Queen's Cross|Queens Cross]]\n|Brenda Craig\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(18) Seaton\n|Norman Collie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(13) Sheddocksley\n|James Lamond\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(11) Springhill\n|Karen Shirron\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(17) St. Machar\n|Sandra Macdonald\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(20) Stockethill\n|June Lamond\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(14) [[Summerhill, Aberdeen|Summerhill]]\n|Len Ironside\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(22) Sunnybank\n|Andrew May\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|(39) [[Torry]]\n|Yvonne Allan\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(40) Tullos\n|Jim Kiddie\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|(16) [[Woodside, Aberdeen|Woodside]]/[[Tillydrone]]\n|Alan Gowers\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|''Source: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070210230442/http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/acci/web/site/xac_Councillor.asp?s=2 Aberdeen City Council]''\n|}\n\n==UK Parliament==\nIn the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom Parliament]], the city is divided between three [[constituencies]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Constituency'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Member'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen North (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen North]]\n|[[Kirsty Blackman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen South (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South]]\n|[[Stephen Flynn (Scottish politician)|Stephen Flynn]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Gordon (UK Parliament constituency)|Gordon]]\n|[[Richard Thomson (politician)|Richard Thomson]]\n|}\n\n==Scottish Parliament==\nThere are three [[Scottish Parliament]] constituencies that overlap the Aberdeen City Council area in the [[North East Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|North East Scotland]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|electoral region]]:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Constituency'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Member'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen Central (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen Central]]\n|[[Kevin Stewart (Scottish politician)|Kevin Stewart]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Independent/meta/color}}\"|\n|Independent\n|[[Aberdeen Donside (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen Donside]]\n|[[Mark McDonald (politician)|Mark McDonald]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}\"|\n|Scottish National Party\n|[[Aberdeen South and North Kincardine (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Aberdeen South and North Kincardine]]\n|[[Maureen Watt]]\n|}\n\nOther [[Member of the Scottish Parliament|MSPs]] in the [[North East Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|North East Scotland]] electoral region (but selected by the [[Mixed member proportional representation|Additional Member]] proportional representation system, and not in constituencies overlapping Aberdeen City or the Aberdeen City Council area) are:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|width=\"5\"|\n|width=\"140\"|'''Party'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Members'''\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|[[Lewis MacDonald]]\n|-\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Labour\n|[[Jenny Marra]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Peter Chapman (politician)|Peter Chapman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Bill Bowman (Scottish politician)|Bill Bowman]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Liam Kerr]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Conservative\n|[[Ross Thomson]]\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\"|\n|Liberal Democrat\n|[[Mike Rumbles]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Scottish independence referendum==\n{{main|Scottish independence referendum, 2014}}\nIn 2014 a referendum was held asking voters in [[Scotland]] the question: \"Should Scotland be an independent country?\" The referendum was held by the [[Scottish National Party|SNP]] administration after their victory in the [[2011 Scottish Parliament election]] to determine whether Scotland should become an [[Sovereign state|independent nation]] or remain a [[Devolution in the United Kingdom|devolved part]] of the [[United Kingdom]]. Of the 3,623,344 votes cast (on a turnout of 84.6%) 2,001,926 were in favour of a \"No\" vote (55.3%) while 1,617,989 were \"Yes\" (44.7%): leading to Scotland remaining part of the United Kingdom.\n\nThe Aberdeen City local authority area had a higher than average No vote. 84,094 voters in the area voted against independence (58.6%) while 59,390 voted in favour of independence (41.4%). The Aberdeen City council area had the third lowest turnout in Scotland with 143,484 valid ballot papers on a turnout of 81.7%, ahead of [[Dundee]] and [[Glasgow]].\n\n==Twinned cities==\nAberdeen is [[Town twinning|twinned]] with several cities across Europe and throughout the rest of the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/ACCI/web/site/Tourism/SL/tur_TownTwinning.asp|title=Twinning|publisher=Aberdeen City Council|accessdate=2007-02-08}}</ref> These include:\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{flagicon|Zimbabwe}} - [[Bulawayo]], [[Zimbabwe]]\n* {{flagicon|France}} - [[Clermont-Ferrand]], [[France]]\n* {{flagicon|Belarus}} - [[Gomel]], [[Belarus]]\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{flagicon|United States}} - [[Houston]], [[United States]] (as part of [[Grampian]])\n* {{flagicon|Germany}} - [[Regensburg]], [[Germany]]\n* {{flagicon|Norway}} - [[Stavanger]], [[Norway]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Aberdeen City Youth Council]]\n*[[Politics of Dundee]]\n*[[Politics of Edinburgh]]\n*[[Politics of Glasgow]]\n*[[Politics of Scotland]]\n*[[Politics of the Highland council area]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070307172247/http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/ACCI/web/site/home/home.asp Council website]\n\n{{Aberdeen}}\n{{Former local government regions of Scotland}} \n\n[[Category:Politics of Aberdeen| ]]\n", "name_user": "EditsBoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eScottish Parliament", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Politics_of_Aberdeen"}
{"title_page": "Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:5th_Marquess_of_Dufferin_&_Ava.jpg|thumb|Dufferin in 1975]]\n'''Sheridan Frederick Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava''' (9 July 1938 \u2013 29 May 1988),<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink= Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1196 |pages= |ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref> was a British patron of the arts. Less formally he was usually called '''Sheridan Dufferin'''.\n\n==Childhood and inheritance==\n\nBorn into an [[Anglo-Irish]] [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] family from [[Ulster]], he was the youngest child and only son of [[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|The 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] and his wife, [[Maureen Constance Guinness|Maureen Guinness]] (daughter of [[The Honourable]] Arthur Ernest Guinness, second son of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh|the 1st Earl of Iveagh]]). One of his sisters was the novelist [[Lady Caroline Blackwood]].\n\nNamed after his playwright ancestor [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]], Lord Dufferin was known by his father's courtesy title '''Earl of Ava''' until he succeeded his father in the [[marquessate]] in 1945, when he was only six years old. When he was aged 12, trustees acting in his name sold [[Clandeboye Estate|Clandeboye]], his [[ancestral seat]], to his estates company for \u00a3120,000 in order \"to maintain his station in life\", as the trustees allegedly said at the time.\n\nAfter attending the day school Garth House in [[Bangor, County Down]], he went to [[Eton College]]. After Eton he attended [[Christ Church, Oxford]]. A keen shot and sportsman, he played championship tennis at the [[Queen's Club]], but it was at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] that he developed a passion for the arts.\n\n==Patron of the arts==\n\nAfter Oxford he met and went into partnership with [[John Kasmin]], and opened the Kasmin Gallery on [[New Bond Street]], London in 1963. The Kasmin was a radical gallery for the time and showed British and American [[Abstract art|abstract]] and [[pop art]]. The gallery was described as \"a beautiful space in New Bond Street designed for them by [[Ahrends, Burton and Koralek]], with a curiously shaped white ceiling, white walls and a green-khaki rubberised floor. It was a space described by Kasmin as 'a machine for looking at pictures in'; those pictures, moreover, were prototypes of the new art. They looked as if they had been painted to be seen in museums: the space was designed for canvasses six feet square and upwards that would readily carry across a large room. The gallery thereby affirmed that painting had changed fundamentally: it was no longer being made to fit into drawing-rooms.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/v22/n07/david-sylvester/someone-you-had-to-be-a-bit-careful-with|title=\u2018Someone you had to be a bit careful with\u2019|first=David|last=Sylvester|date=30 March 2000|pages=18\u201320|via=London Review of Books}}</ref> Among the artists the gallery showed were [[Frank Stella]], [[Kenneth Noland]], [[Jules Olitski]], [[Anthony Caro]] and most famously of all [[David Hockney]]. The Kasmin Gallery closed in 1972, with Kasmin going on to work in partnership with other London dealers up to the 1990s.\n\nLord Dufferin was appointed a trustee of the [[Wallace Collection]] in 1973, and was also a trustee of the [[National Gallery, London]] and continued to support up-and-coming contemporary British artists. He also helped in the making of films about the pianist [[Liberace]] and the ''[[Playboy]]'' entrepreneur [[Hugh Hefner]], as well as backing the controversial 1976 film ''[[Sebastiane]]'', directed by the British filmmaker [[Derek Jarman]]. He was also a sometime director of the [[Guinness]] company, being a great-grandson of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]].\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAlthough he was [[homosexual]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: Maureen, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-maureen-marchioness-of-dufferin-and-ava-1158254.html|work=The Independent|date=23 May 1998|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> in 1964 Lord Dufferin married his fourth cousin [[Lindy, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava|Lindy Guinness]].  Their wedding was at [[Westminster Abbey]] where 1,800 guests attended, including [[Princess Margaret]] and the [[Anthony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]]. Lady Dufferin was also passionate about art and together they were at centre of the trendy art scene in late 1960s London. Parties at their house in Holland Park \"were legendary in the late 1960s. You would find yourself talking to Princess Margaret or [[Duncan Grant]] and [[Angelica Garnett]], or [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]] or [[Stephen Spender]] or the [[Queen Mother]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MARK LANCASTER INTERVIEW |author=Gary Comens |year=2004 |url=http://www.warholstars.org/andywarhol/interview/mark/lancaster.html |publisher=Warholstars.org}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nLord Dufferin died on 29 May 1988 from an AIDS-related illness, aged 49.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Reginato|first1=James|title=The Marchioness|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/culture/art-and-design/2009/02/lady_dufferin|accessdate=17 August 2017|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=February 2009}}</ref> As there were no other living descendants in the direct male line from the 1st Marquess, the [[marquessate]] and the other peerages created for the 1st Marquess in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]] became extinct. The [[Baron Dufferin and Claneboye|Barony of Dufferin and Clandeboye]], the family's older title in the [[Peerage of Ireland]], passed to a distant kinsman.<ref name=\"burke\"/>\n\nHis sister married [[Robert Lowell]] in 1972, and they named their son Sheridan after his uncle.\n\nIn the years immediately before, and especially after, her husband's death, Lady Dufferin developed new initiatives at [[Clandeboye Estate|Clandeboye]], and today the estate has associations with a number of environmental organisations and projects, being a home for Conservation Volunteers Northern Ireland's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tcv.org.uk/northernireland|title=TCV in Northern Ireland|first=The Conservation|last=Volunteers|website=TCV}}</ref> biodiversity projects, training centre and tree nursery (in the old walled garden). The Northern Ireland branch of the [[Woodland Trust]] was established in 1998 in partnership with the Dufferin Foundation, and [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] have developed a blossoming relationship with Clandeboye since 2003. Lady Dufferin also returned to the art world, and has exhibited in galleries in London and New York under the name Lindy Guinness. She was also the inspiration behind the opening of the Ava Gallery at Clandeboye in 2004, which exhibits works by leading contemporary Northern Irish artists and an annual exhibition of museum-standard work by a major artist or group of artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clandeboye \u2013 The Irish mansion filled with a diplomats memorabilia |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/luxuryhomes/8862775/Clandeboye-The-Irish-mansion-filled-with-a-diplomats-memorabilia.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Titles and styles==\n*9 July 1938 \u2013 25 March 1945: Earl of Ava\n*25 March 1945 \u2013 29 May 1988: ''The Most Honourable'' the Marquess of Dufferin and Ava\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image =Arms of marquess of dufferin and ava small 2.png\n| crest = 1st:  On a Cap of Maintenance Gules turned up Ermine a Crescent Argent (Blackwood);  2nd, On a Ducal Coronet Or a Martlet Gold (Temple);  3rd, a Demi-Antelope affront\u00e9e Ermine attired and unguled Or holding between his hoofs a Heart Gules (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of an Marquess]]\n| escutcheon = ''Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Azure a Fess Or in chief a Crescent Argent between two Mullets of the second and in base a Mascle of the third'' (Blackwood);  ''2nd, quarterly, 1st and 4th, Or an Eagle displayed Sable, 2nd and 3rd, Argent two Bars Sable each charged with three Martlets Or'' (Temple);  3rd, ''Gules three Cinquefoils pierced Ermine on a Chief Or a Lion passant of the field'' (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| supporters = Dexter:  a Lion Gules armed and langued Azure gorged with a Tressure flory-counterflory Or;  Sinister:  an Heraldic Tiger Ermine gorged with a like Tressure Gules;  each supporter supporting a Flag Staff proper therefrom flowing a Banner Or charged with a Peacock in his Pride also proper\n| motto = ''Per vias rectas'' (By straight ways)\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060618104904/http://www.avagalleryclandeboye.co.uk/ Ava Gallery website]\n*[http://www.clandeboye.co.uk Clandeboye Estate website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Dufferin and Clandeboye]] | before=[[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] | after=[[Francis Blackwood, 10th Baron Dufferin and Claneboye|Francis George Blackwood]] | years=1945\u20131988}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n | years = 1945\u20131988\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dufferin and Ava, Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of}}\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:British people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of English descent]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Blackwood family|Sheridan]]\n[[Category:British art dealers]]\n[[Category:People associated with the National Gallery, London]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Wallace Collection]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Dufferin and Ava]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n[[File:5th_Marquess_of_Dufferin_&_Ava.jpg|thumb|Dufferin in 1975]]\n'''Sheridan Frederick Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava''' (9 July 1938 \u2013 29 May 1988),<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink= Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1196 |pages= |ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref> was a British patron of the arts. Less formally he was usually called '''Sheridan Dufferin'''.\n\n==Childhood and inheritance==\n\nBorn into an [[Anglo-Irish]] [[aristocracy (class)|aristocratic]] family from [[Ulster]], he was the youngest child and only son of [[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|The 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] and his wife, Maureen Guinness (daughter of [[The Honourable]] Arthur Ernest Guinness, second son of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh|the 1st Earl of Iveagh]]). One of his sisters was the novelist [[Lady Caroline Blackwood]].\n\nNamed after his playwright ancestor [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]], Lord Dufferin was known by his father's courtesy title '''Earl of Ava''' until he succeeded his father in the [[marquessate]] in 1945, when he was only six years old. When he was aged 12, trustees acting in his name sold [[Clandeboye Estate|Clandeboye]], his [[ancestral seat]], to his estates company for \u00a3120,000 in order \"to maintain his station in life\", as the trustees allegedly said at the time.\n\nAfter attending the day school Garth House in [[Bangor, County Down]], he went to [[Eton College]]. After Eton he attended [[Christ Church, Oxford]]. A keen shot and sportsman, he played championship tennis at the [[Queen's Club]], but it was at [[Oxford University|Oxford]] that he developed a passion for the arts.\n\n==Patron of the arts==\n\nAfter Oxford he met and went into partnership with [[John Kasmin]], and opened the Kasmin Gallery on [[New Bond Street]], London in 1963. The Kasmin was a radical gallery for the time and showed British and American [[Abstract art|abstract]] and [[pop art]]. The gallery was described as \"a beautiful space in New Bond Street designed for them by [[Ahrends, Burton and Koralek]], with a curiously shaped white ceiling, white walls and a green-khaki rubberised floor. It was a space described by Kasmin as 'a machine for looking at pictures in'; those pictures, moreover, were prototypes of the new art. They looked as if they had been painted to be seen in museums: the space was designed for canvasses six feet square and upwards that would readily carry across a large room. The gallery thereby affirmed that painting had changed fundamentally: it was no longer being made to fit into drawing-rooms.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/v22/n07/david-sylvester/someone-you-had-to-be-a-bit-careful-with|title=\u2018Someone you had to be a bit careful with\u2019|first=David|last=Sylvester|date=30 March 2000|pages=18\u201320|via=London Review of Books}}</ref> Among the artists the gallery showed were [[Frank Stella]], [[Kenneth Noland]], [[Jules Olitski]], [[Anthony Caro]] and most famously of all [[David Hockney]]. The Kasmin Gallery closed in 1972, with Kasmin going on to work in partnership with other London dealers up to the 1990s.\n\nLord Dufferin was appointed a trustee of the [[Wallace Collection]] in 1973, and was also a trustee of the [[National Gallery, London]] and continued to support up-and-coming contemporary British artists. He also helped in the making of films about the pianist [[Liberace]] and the ''[[Playboy]]'' entrepreneur [[Hugh Hefner]], as well as backing the controversial 1976 film ''[[Sebastiane]]'', directed by the British filmmaker [[Derek Jarman]]. He was also a sometime director of the [[Guinness]] company, being a great-grandson of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]].\n\n==Personal life==\n\nAlthough he was [[homosexual]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: Maureen, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-maureen-marchioness-of-dufferin-and-ava-1158254.html|work=The Independent|date=23 May 1998|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> in 1964 Lord Dufferin married his fourth cousin [[Lindy, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava|Lindy Guinness]].  Their wedding was at [[Westminster Abbey]] where 1,800 guests attended, including [[Princess Margaret]] and the [[Anthony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]]. Lady Dufferin was also passionate about art and together they were at centre of the trendy art scene in late 1960s London. Parties at their house in Holland Park \"were legendary in the late 1960s. You would find yourself talking to Princess Margaret or [[Duncan Grant]] and [[Angelica Garnett]], or [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]] or [[Stephen Spender]] or the [[Queen Mother]].\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MARK LANCASTER INTERVIEW |author=Gary Comens |year=2004 |url=http://www.warholstars.org/andywarhol/interview/mark/lancaster.html |publisher=Warholstars.org}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nLord Dufferin died on 29 May 1988 from an AIDS-related illness, aged 49.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Reginato|first1=James|title=The Marchioness|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/culture/art-and-design/2009/02/lady_dufferin|accessdate=17 August 2017|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=February 2009}}</ref> As there were no other living descendants in the direct male line from the 1st Marquess, the [[marquessate]] and the other peerages created for the 1st Marquess in the [[Peerage of the United Kingdom]] became extinct. The [[Baron Dufferin and Claneboye|Barony of Dufferin and Clandeboye]], the family's older title in the [[Peerage of Ireland]], passed to a distant kinsman.<ref name=\"burke\"/>\n\nHis sister married [[Robert Lowell]] in 1972, and they named their son Sheridan after his uncle.\n\nIn the years immediately before, and especially after, her husband's death, Lady Dufferin developed new initiatives at [[Clandeboye Estate|Clandeboye]], and today the estate has associations with a number of environmental organisations and projects, being a home for Conservation Volunteers Northern Ireland's<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tcv.org.uk/northernireland|title=TCV in Northern Ireland|first=The Conservation|last=Volunteers|website=TCV}}</ref> biodiversity projects, training centre and tree nursery (in the old walled garden). The Northern Ireland branch of the [[Woodland Trust]] was established in 1998 in partnership with the Dufferin Foundation, and [[Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew]] have developed a blossoming relationship with Clandeboye since 2003. Lady Dufferin also returned to the art world, and has exhibited in galleries in London and New York under the name Lindy Guinness. She was also the inspiration behind the opening of the Ava Gallery at Clandeboye in 2004, which exhibits works by leading contemporary Northern Irish artists and an annual exhibition of museum-standard work by a major artist or group of artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Clandeboye \u2013 The Irish mansion filled with a diplomats memorabilia |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/property/luxuryhomes/8862775/Clandeboye-The-Irish-mansion-filled-with-a-diplomats-memorabilia.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n==Titles and styles==\n*9 July 1938 \u2013 25 March 1945: Earl of Ava\n*25 March 1945 \u2013 29 May 1988: ''The Most Honourable'' the Marquess of Dufferin and Ava\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image =Arms of marquess of dufferin and ava small 2.png\n| crest = 1st:  On a Cap of Maintenance Gules turned up Ermine a Crescent Argent (Blackwood);  2nd, On a Ducal Coronet Or a Martlet Gold (Temple);  3rd, a Demi-Antelope affront\u00e9e Ermine attired and unguled Or holding between his hoofs a Heart Gules (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of an Marquess]]\n| escutcheon = ''Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Azure a Fess Or in chief a Crescent Argent between two Mullets of the second and in base a Mascle of the third'' (Blackwood);  ''2nd, quarterly, 1st and 4th, Or an Eagle displayed Sable, 2nd and 3rd, Argent two Bars Sable each charged with three Martlets Or'' (Temple);  3rd, ''Gules three Cinquefoils pierced Ermine on a Chief Or a Lion passant of the field'' (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| supporters = Dexter:  a Lion Gules armed and langued Azure gorged with a Tressure flory-counterflory Or;  Sinister:  an Heraldic Tiger Ermine gorged with a like Tressure Gules;  each supporter supporting a Flag Staff proper therefrom flowing a Banner Or charged with a Peacock in his Pride also proper\n| motto = ''Per vias rectas'' (By straight ways)\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060618104904/http://www.avagalleryclandeboye.co.uk/ Ava Gallery website]\n*[http://www.clandeboye.co.uk Clandeboye Estate website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Dufferin and Clandeboye]] | before=[[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] | after=[[Francis Blackwood, 10th Baron Dufferin and Claneboye|Francis George Blackwood]] | years=1945\u20131988}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{s-bef| before=[[Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = [[Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n | years = 1945\u20131988\n}}\n{{s-non | reason = Extinct }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dufferin and Ava, Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of}}\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:British people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:British people of English descent]]\n[[Category:AIDS-related deaths in England]]\n[[Category:Blackwood family|Sheridan]]\n[[Category:British art dealers]]\n[[Category:People associated with the National Gallery, London]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Wallace Collection]]\n[[Category:Gay peers]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Dufferin and Ava]]\n", "name_user": "Smirkybec", "label": "safe", "comment": "adding link for Maureen Constance Guinness", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheridan_Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood,_5th_Marquess_of_Dufferin_and_Ava"}
{"title_page": "Alachua County Library District", "text_new": "[[File:Alachua County Library District Headquarters (NW corner).JPG|thumb|Alachua County Library District Headquarters Branch, 401 East University Avenue, Gainesville, Fl.]]\n'''The Alachua County Library District''' is an [[Special-purpose district|independent special taxing district]] and the sole provider of [[public library]] service to approximately 250,000 citizens of [[Alachua County, Florida]]. This includes all of the incorporated municipalities in the county. It maintains a Headquarters Library and four other branches in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]]. There are branch locations in seven of the eight other incorporated municipalities in the county. ACLD also operates a branch at the county jail, and two [[bookmobile]]s.\n\n==Locations==\nThe Alachua County Library District has twelve locations. Five locations in Gainesville include the Headquarters Branch in downtown Gainesville, Millhopper Branch in northwest Gainesville, Tower Road Branch in unincorporated Alachua county southwest of Gainesville, Library Partnership Branch in northeast Gainesville, and Cone Park Branch in east Gainesville. The district also operates branches in the Alachua County municipalities of [[Alachua, Florida|Alachua]], [[Archer, Florida|Archer]], [[Hawthorne, Florida|Hawthorne]], [[High Springs, Florida|High Springs]], [[Micanopy, Florida|Micanopy]], [[Newberry, Florida|Newberry]], and [[Waldo, Florida|Waldo]], and at the Alachua County Jail. The district operates two bookmobiles which visit more than 25 locations in the county from two to five times a month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locations|url=http://www.aclib.us/locations|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate= 31 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate Programs|url=http://www.alachuasheriff.org/jail/inmate_programs.html|publisher=Alachua County Sheriff's Office|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bookmobile Stops|url=http://www.aclib.us/bookmobile-stops|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n[[ Image:Alachua County Library - Millhopper (4487749479).jpg | thumb|Millhopper Branch Library]]\n\n==History==\nThe Alachua County Library District traces its origins to 1903. A women's group in Gainesville organized a literary society called the Twentieth Century Club. The club issued a call for donated material and money to help initiate the town's first library. By 1905, Gainesville two subscription libraries, for which a small fee was required. In January 1905, Nora Norton established the Gainesville Circulating Library, held in the Gainesville Sewing Machine company, which required a five dollar a year fee. The Twentieth Century Club  opened a library in the Miller Law Exchange with assistance of 200 donated books and a yearly fee of two dollars.\n\nIn January 1906, the Gainesville Public Library on West Liberty (now University Avenue) opened with a collection of 800 books, combining books from the Twentieth Century Club, the library of the [[East Florida Seminary]] (recently absorbed into the University of Florida), and the Gainesville Circulating Library. However, a small fee was still required.\n\nBy 1914 the library moved to several locations, finally ending up at a small building owned by attorney B.A. Thrasher. The Library Association requested assistance from the City Council to make the Gainesville Library a free public library (fees were still 2 dollars a year). To be eligible for Carnegie funds to build a library, the city was required to pay 1000 dollars a year to acquire the deed to 419 East University Avenue. On October 13th 1915, the Gainesville Public Library was established at that location, with the first Library Board including:\u00a0 Dr. A.A. Murphree, Captain C.R. Layton, Hon. W.M. Pepper, Hon. George P. Morris, and Dr. H.W. Cox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ask.aclib.us/faq/190238|title=What is the history of the library? - Alachua Ask Us!|website=ask.aclib.us|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The Gainesville Public Library became a free library in 1918, supported by funds from city taxes, and in a building constructed with the aid of a [[Carnegie library|Carnegie grant]]. The library became a department of the City of Gainesville in 1949. A branch of the Gainesville Public Library, the Carver Branch Library, was opened in 1953 to provide library services to the [[African-American]] population of Gainesville. The Carver Branch closed in 1969, after the main library had been [[Desegregation|desegregated]]. In 1958, the City of Gainesville and Alachua County agreed to jointly operate the library for the whole county.\n\nBranch libraries were opened in High Springs, Hawthorne and Micanopy the next year, and a bookmobile was put into service. Alachua County joined with [[Bradford County, Florida|Bradford County]] to operate the Santa Fe Regional Library. After Bradford County withdrew from the Regional Library, the Alachua County Library District was formally established in 1986. In 1987 funds were approved by vote for a new main library. After being postponed due to asbestos, construction of the new 78,000 sq. ft. library headquarters was underway. In 1991 the new Alachua County Library District headquarters building was opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ask.aclib.us/faq/190238|title=What is the history of the library? - Alachua Ask Us!|website=ask.aclib.us|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Millhopper and Tower Road branches opened in 1992, and the branches in Alachua, Archer, Newberry and Waldo were all opened by 1997. In 2008, the Alachua branch underwent a $1.5 million renovation and expansion project that saw the library's size double to 10,000 square feet and included the addition of a drive-up window and specialized areas for both young children and teenagers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gainesville.com/news/20080814/a-new-look-for-alachua-libraries |title=A New Look for Alachua Libraries |publisher=The Gainesville Sun |date=15 August 2008 |website=Gainesville.com |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> The Library Partnership Branch opened in 2009 and the Cone Park Branch in 2011. A new, permanent location for the Cone Park Branch Library was opened near the Eastside Community Center in Gainesville on December 14, 2013.<ref name=\"carrico\">{{cite web|last=Carrico|first=Steve|title=A Summarized Timeline of the History of Libraries in Alachua County|url=http://guides.uflib.ufl.edu/content.php?pid=9442&sid=64388|publisher=University of Florida Libraries|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gainesville Public Library|url=http://heritage.acld.lib.fl.us/1051-1100/1100.html|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cone Park Library Hosting Grand Opening|url=http://www.gainesville.com/article/20131211/GUARDIAN/131219916|publisher=The Gainesville Sun|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Headquarters branch celebrated 25 years - with an estimated 3.8 million items checked out that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wuft.org/news/2016/02/02/gainesvilles-downtown-library-celebrates-25-years/|title=Alachua County\u2019s Headquarters Library Celebrates 25 Years|last=Smith|first=Melissa|date=2016-02-02|website=WUFT|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> In 2016, High Springs branch added 3,000 square feet to their original building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alligator.org/news/local/article_88221d0c-6f2a-11e6-8a01-5fdd6cbbe6ad.html|title=High Springs library celebrates new expansion|last=Guzman|first=Amy|date=2016-08-31|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> In January 2017, the Tower Road Branch library began undergoing renovations to add 8,500 square feet of space, which would include additions of a quiet reading room, three study rooms, new restrooms and an expanded children's area, among other features.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclib.us/tower-road-branch-expansion-and-renovation-starts-january |title=Tower Road Branch Expansion and Renovation Starts in January |last=Kortus |first=Nickie|publisher=Alachua County Library District |date=19 December 2016 |website=aclib.us |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Library cards==\nLibrary cards are free to any resident of the State of Florida and to non-residents who own property in Florida. Out of state residents may get a card by paying a fee. A potential user must register in person with proper identification and proof of residency or of ownership of property in the state. The registration of a minor requires the parent or legal guardian to have their own ID plus an acceptable form of ID for the child. Acceptable forms of identification for a minor include:   \n* Health insurance card\n* School report card\n* School immunization record\n* Social Security card\n* Birth certificate\n* Passport \nLibrary card renewal is required every two years and must be done in person with a photo ID and proof of mailing address. A patron must have a $0 account balance in order to renew a card.<ref>{{cite web|title=Get a Library Card|url=http://www.aclib.us/my-account/get-a-library-card|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlachua County residents are eligible for free library cards from 12 counties: [[Baker]], [[Bradford]], [[Clay]], [[Columbia County, Florida|Columbia]], [[Dixie]], [[Gilchrist County, Florida|Gilchrist]], [[Lafayette County, Florida|Lafayette]], [[Levy County, Florida|Levy]], [[Marion County, Florida|Marion]], [[Putnam County, Florida|Putnam]], [[St. Johns County, Florida|St. Johns]], and [[Union County, Florida|Union]] counties.<ref>https://www.aclib.us/cards</ref>\n\n==Student Library cards==\n\nIn 2018 The Alachua County Library District and [https://www.sbac.edu Alachua County Public Schools] partnered in a new initiative aimed at expanding access by providing students in public schools with their own library card for free. More than 27,000 cards were distributed the first year of the program.<ref>https://www.aclib.us/studentcards</ref> The program was then continued into the 2019-2020 school year and expanded to include students at P.K. Yonge Developmental Research School. Student cards allow for:\n\n* Check out of 3 Print or Audiobooks\n* Borrowing eBooks, downloadable music and digital magazine\n* Use of eSources, including tutoring help and research resources.\n* Ability to log on to computers at any of the Library District\u2019s 12 branches.\n\nStudents new to the program receive a welcome letter along with the card at the school and then are able to use the library card to access services online as well as in the branches.  Although the Alachua County Library District charges no late fees, students are still expected to return materials and parents may receive a quarterly statement from the library for anything not returned.\n\n==Checkouts and returns==\nLibrary card holders can checkout and return items at any branch located in Alachua County, including the two bookmobiles. Total checkout is limited to 100 items with a max of 8 DVDs per account. Books and audiobooks check out for 4 weeks, music CDs check out for 2 weeks, and DVDs check out for 1 week. Items may be renewed twice, as long as they are not on hold for another patron. Audiobooks, eBooks, music, TV shows and movies are available to library card holders as downloadable digital media from the ACLD website.\n\nIf a library card holder wishes to checkout an item that is not currently available, they may place a hold request on that item through the online catalog. By entering their library card number, a patron can then choose the branch they wish to have the item delivered to once it becomes available.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q. How do I reserve, or place a \"hold,\" on library materials? |url=http://ask.aclib.us/faq/67625 |publisher=Alachua County Library District |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Library District does not have late fees. However, five or more overdue items or $50.00 worth of overdue materials will block borrowing privileges until the items are returned or paid for.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fines|url=http://www.aclib.us/fines|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lost Materials|url=http://www.aclib.us/lost-materials|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> Additionally, any items returned by patrons with damaged or missing parts will result in a standard replacement charge for that individual.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclib.us/patronaccounts |title=Patron Accounts |publisher=Alachua County Library District |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nApart from library card privileges, the Alachua County Library District branches offer other services including meeting rooms, events for all ages, ebooks, audiobooks, computer access, free mp3 downloads, downloadable magazines, Wi-Fi, printing, interlibrary loans, proctoring, and literacy tutoring for adults and ESOL learners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclib.us/services|title=Services {{!}} Alachua County Library District|website=www.aclib.us|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> Working with the University of Florida's Center for Autism and Related Disabilities, the Library District offers sensory storytime, a special storytime open to all children but designed to serve children with sensory integration challenges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclib.us/high-springs/blog/sensory-storytime|title=Sensory Storytime {{!}} Alachua County Library District|website=www.aclib.us|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref> The library district also offers mailing services of print material to the homebound of Alachua County. Additionally, multiple branch locations have served as polling locations during Alachua County elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcjb.com/local-news/2012/10/early-voting-alachua-county |title=Early Voting for Alachua County |publisher=Diversified Broadcasting Inc. |date=27 October 2012 |website=WCJB TV-20 |access-date=9 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317031438/http://wcjb.com/local-news/2012/10/early-voting-alachua-county |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Library support==\n[[File:ACLD book sale Gainesville.jpg|thumb|352x352px|The Friends of the Library fall book sale, October 25, 2016.]]\nThe Library District is supported by the '''[http://folacld.org/ Friends of the Library]''' (established in 1954) with a bi-annual book sale, usually in October and April.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bookstore|url=http://folacld.org/|publisher=Friends of the Library|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> The Friends of the Library book sale is the largest of its kind in the state of Florida, with 500,000 books, magazines, videos, puzzles, games, and more available for sale. The book sale also has a Collector's Corner, which specializes in rare books, including first editions, signed copies, and Florida-related materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://folacld.org/n_sale_colcor.html|title=FOL Sale Collector's Corner Page|website=folacld.org|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gainesville.com/lifestyle/20150417/friends-of-the-library-spring-book-sale-is-next-weekend|title=Friends of the Library Spring Book Sale is next weekend|last=Valencic|first=Brittany|date=2015-04-17|work=|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|access-date=2016-10-25|via=}}</ref> The sale offers more than 64 categories of books, including general fiction, classics, cookbooks, children's and young adult fiction, and comic books. Proceeds from the sale fund different programs benefiting the Alachua County Library District. In 2015-2016, the book sale proceeds funded $150,000 in direct support to the library district for adult and children's programming, for purchasing library materials, and for other needs. The library also raised scholarship funds for library personnel to complete their [[Master of Library and Information Science]] degrees. The Friends of the Library also helped fund a variety of literacy projects, including the Family Literacy Festival, distribution of books for Head Start programs, and mini-grants for local literacy organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://folacld.org/n_projcts.html|title=FOL Projects Page|website=folacld.org|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\nThe library district is also supported by the '''[http://acldfound.org/ ACLD Foundation]''', which raises money through the sale of name plaques and author galas.<ref name=\"carrico\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=ACLD Foundation|url=http://www.acldfound.org/|publisher=Alachua County Library District Foundation, Inc.|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n*The Alachua County Library District was co-recipient of the [[Florida Library Association]] 2010 Library of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Library Awards Recipients 2010|url=http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/Awards%20Recipients_2010.pdf|publisher=Florida Library Association|accessdate=16 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415013644/http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/Awards%20Recipients_2010.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The Library Partnership branch was selected for the [[Ash Center for Democratic Governance and Innovation]] Bright Ideas program in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Bright Ideas Recognizes Innovative Government|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/news-events/news/press-releases/ash-bright-ideas|publisher=Harvard University John F. Kennedy School of Government|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n*Sol Hirsch, Director of the district (2004-2011), received the 2011 Peggy Sullivan Award for Public Library Administrators Supporting Services to Children from the American Library Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sol M. Hirsch receives 2011 Sullivan Award |url=http://americanlibrariesmagazine.org/news/ala/sol-m-hirsch-receives-2011-sullivan-award |publisher=American Library Association |accessdate=16 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421011557/http://americanlibrariesmagazine.org/news/ala/sol-m-hirsch-receives-2011-sullivan-award |archivedate=21 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Curry|first=Christopher|title=Library director Sol Hirsch to retire|url=http://www.gainesville.com/article/20110301/ARTICLES/110309963|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|date=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n*The district was one of five libraries and five museums to receive the 2011 [[National Medal for Museum and Library Service]] awarded by the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]].<ref>{{cite web|title=IMLS Announces the 2011 National Medal for Museum and Library Service Recipients|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/imls-announces-the-2011-national-medal-for-museum-and-library-service-recipients-132527718.html|publisher=PRNewswire|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n*The Alachua County Library District received the Betty Davis Miller Youth Services - Children award at the [[Florida Library Association]] annual conference in 2016 for their Sensory Storytime program for children on the autism spectrum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/2016/2016%20Award%20Winners.pdf|title=2016 Award Winners|website=Florida Library Association|access-date=2016-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913085253/http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/2016/2016%20Award%20Winners.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181109233735/https://www.aclib.us/ Official Alachua County Library District Website]\n* [http://catalog.aclib.us/ Official catalog] and [http://catalog.aclib.us/Children/ Children's catalog]\n* [https://catalog.aclib.us/mobile/ Official Mobile Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Florida|Alachua]]\n[[Category:Education in Alachua County, Florida|Library]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Florida]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Alachua County Library District Headquarters (NW corner).JPG|thumb|Alachua County Library District Headquarters Branch, 401 East University Avenue, Gainesville, Fl.]]\n'''The Alachua County Library District''' is an [[Special-purpose district|independent special taxing district]] and the sole provider of [[public library]] service to approximately 250,000 citizens of [[Alachua County, Florida]]. This includes all of the incorporated municipalities in the county. It maintains a Headquarters Library and four other branches in [[Gainesville, Florida|Gainesville]]. There are branch locations in seven of the eight other incorporated municipalities in the county. ACLD also operates a branch at the county jail, and two [[bookmobile]]s.\n\n==Locations==\nThe Alachua County Library District has twelve locations. Five locations in Gainesville include the Headquarters Branch in downtown Gainesville, Millhopper Branch in northwest Gainesville, Tower Road Branch in unincorporated Alachua county southwest of Gainesville, Library Partnership Branch in northeast Gainesville, and Cone Park Branch in east Gainesville. The district also operates branches in the Alachua County municipalities of [[Alachua, Florida|Alachua]], [[Archer, Florida|Archer]], [[Hawthorne, Florida|Hawthorne]], [[High Springs, Florida|High Springs]], [[Micanopy, Florida|Micanopy]], [[Newberry, Florida|Newberry]], and [[Waldo, Florida|Waldo]], and at the Alachua County Jail. The district operates two bookmobiles which visit more than 25 locations in the county from two to five times a month.<ref>{{cite web|title=Locations|url=http://www.aclib.us/locations|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate= 31 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Inmate Programs|url=http://www.alachuasheriff.org/jail/inmate_programs.html|publisher=Alachua County Sheriff's Office|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bookmobile Stops|url=http://www.aclib.us/bookmobile-stops|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n[[ Image:Alachua County Library - Millhopper (4487749479).jpg | thumb|Millhopper Branch Library]]\n\n==History==\nThe Alachua County Library District traces its origins to 1905. A women's group in Gainesville organized a literary society called the Twentieth Century Club. The club issued a call for donated material and money to help initiate the town's first library. By 1905, Gainesville two subscription libraries, for which a small fee was required. In January 1905, Nora Norton established the Gainesville Circulating Library, held in the Gainesville Sewing Machine company, which required a five dollar a year fee. The Twentieth Century Club  opened a library in the Miller Law Exchange with assistance of 200 donated books and a yearly fee of two dollars.\n\nIn January 1906, the Gainesville Public Library on West Liberty (now University Avenue) opened with a collection of 800 books, combining books from the Twentieth Century Club, the library of the [[East Florida Seminary]] (recently absorbed into the University of Florida), and the Gainesville Circulating Library. However, a small fee was still required.\n\nBy 1914 the library moved to several locations, finally ending up at a small building owned by attorney B.A. Thrasher. The Library Association requested assistance from the City Council to make the Gainesville Library a free public library (fees were still 2 dollars a year). To be eligible for Carnegie funds to build a library, the city was required to pay 1000 dollars a year to acquire the deed to 419 East University Avenue. On October 13th 1915, the Gainesville Public Library was established at that location, with the first Library Board including:\u00a0 Dr. A.A. Murphree, Captain C.R. Layton, Hon. W.M. Pepper, Hon. George P. Morris, and Dr. H.W. Cox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ask.aclib.us/faq/190238|title=What is the history of the library? - Alachua Ask Us!|website=ask.aclib.us|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> The Gainesville Public Library became a free library in 1918, supported by funds from city taxes, and in a building constructed with the aid of a [[Carnegie library|Carnegie grant]]. The library became a department of the City of Gainesville in 1949. A branch of the Gainesville Public Library, the Carver Branch Library, was opened in 1953 to provide library services to the [[African-American]] population of Gainesville. The Carver Branch closed in 1969, after the main library had been [[Desegregation|desegregated]]. In 1958, the City of Gainesville and Alachua County agreed to jointly operate the library for the whole county.\n\nBranch libraries were opened in High Springs, Hawthorne and Micanopy the next year, and a bookmobile was put into service. Alachua County joined with [[Bradford County, Florida|Bradford County]] to operate the Santa Fe Regional Library. After Bradford County withdrew from the Regional Library, the Alachua County Library District was formally established in 1986. In 1987 funds were approved by vote for a new main library. After being postponed due to asbestos, construction of the new 78,000 sq. ft. library headquarters was underway. In 1991 the new Alachua County Library District headquarters building was opened.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ask.aclib.us/faq/190238|title=What is the history of the library? - Alachua Ask Us!|website=ask.aclib.us|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nThe Millhopper and Tower Road branches opened in 1992, and the branches in Alachua, Archer, Newberry and Waldo were all opened by 1997. In 2008, the Alachua branch underwent a $1.5 million renovation and expansion project that saw the library's size double to 10,000 square feet and included the addition of a drive-up window and specialized areas for both young children and teenagers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gainesville.com/news/20080814/a-new-look-for-alachua-libraries |title=A New Look for Alachua Libraries |publisher=The Gainesville Sun |date=15 August 2008 |website=Gainesville.com |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref> The Library Partnership Branch opened in 2009 and the Cone Park Branch in 2011. A new, permanent location for the Cone Park Branch Library was opened near the Eastside Community Center in Gainesville on December 14, 2013.<ref name=\"carrico\">{{cite web|last=Carrico|first=Steve|title=A Summarized Timeline of the History of Libraries in Alachua County|url=http://guides.uflib.ufl.edu/content.php?pid=9442&sid=64388|publisher=University of Florida Libraries|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gainesville Public Library|url=http://heritage.acld.lib.fl.us/1051-1100/1100.html|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Cone Park Library Hosting Grand Opening|url=http://www.gainesville.com/article/20131211/GUARDIAN/131219916|publisher=The Gainesville Sun|accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Headquarters branch celebrated 25 years - with an estimated 3.8 million items checked out that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wuft.org/news/2016/02/02/gainesvilles-downtown-library-celebrates-25-years/|title=Alachua County\u2019s Headquarters Library Celebrates 25 Years|last=Smith|first=Melissa|date=2016-02-02|website=WUFT|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> In 2016, High Springs branch added 3,000 square feet to their original building.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alligator.org/news/local/article_88221d0c-6f2a-11e6-8a01-5fdd6cbbe6ad.html|title=High Springs library celebrates new expansion|last=Guzman|first=Amy|date=2016-08-31|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> In January 2017, the Tower Road Branch library began undergoing renovations to add 8,500 square feet of space, which would include additions of a quiet reading room, three study rooms, new restrooms and an expanded children's area, among other features.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclib.us/tower-road-branch-expansion-and-renovation-starts-january |title=Tower Road Branch Expansion and Renovation Starts in January |last=Kortus |first=Nickie|publisher=Alachua County Library District |date=19 December 2016 |website=aclib.us |access-date=13 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Library cards==\nLibrary cards are free to any resident of the State of Florida and to non-residents who own property in Florida. Out of state residents may get a card by paying a fee. A potential user must register in person with proper identification and proof of residency or of ownership of property in the state. The registration of a minor requires the parent or legal guardian to have their own ID plus an acceptable form of ID for the child. Acceptable forms of identification for a minor include:   \n* Health insurance card\n* School report card\n* School immunization record\n* Social Security card\n* Birth certificate\n* Passport \nLibrary card renewal is required every two years and must be done in person with a photo ID and proof of mailing address. A patron must have a $0 account balance in order to renew a card.<ref>{{cite web|title=Get a Library Card|url=http://www.aclib.us/my-account/get-a-library-card|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAlachua County residents are eligible for free library cards from 12 counties: [[Baker]], [[Bradford]], [[Clay]], [[Columbia County, Florida|Columbia]], [[Dixie]], [[Gilchrist County, Florida|Gilchrist]], [[Lafayette County, Florida|Lafayette]], [[Levy County, Florida|Levy]], [[Marion County, Florida|Marion]], [[Putnam County, Florida|Putnam]], [[St. Johns County, Florida|St. Johns]], and [[Union County, Florida|Union]] counties.<ref>https://www.aclib.us/cards</ref>\n\n==Student Library cards==\n\nIn 2018 The Alachua County Library District and [https://www.sbac.edu Alachua County Public Schools] partnered in a new initiative aimed at expanding access by providing students in public schools with their own library card for free. More than 27,000 cards were distributed the first year of the program.<ref>https://www.aclib.us/studentcards</ref> The program was then continued into the 2019-2020 school year and expanded to include students at P.K. Yonge Developmental Research School. Student cards allow for:\n\n* Check out of 3 Print or Audiobooks\n* Borrowing eBooks, downloadable music and digital magazine\n* Use of eSources, including tutoring help and research resources.\n* Ability to log on to computers at any of the Library District\u2019s 12 branches.\n\nStudents new to the program receive a welcome letter along with the card at the school and then are able to use the library card to access services online as well as in the branches.  Although the Alachua County Library District charges no late fees, students are still expected to return materials and parents may receive a quarterly statement from the library for anything not returned.\n\n==Checkouts and returns==\nLibrary card holders can checkout and return items at any branch located in Alachua County, including the two bookmobiles. Total checkout is limited to 100 items with a max of 8 DVDs per account. Books and audiobooks check out for 4 weeks, music CDs check out for 2 weeks, and DVDs check out for 1 week. Items may be renewed twice, as long as they are not on hold for another patron. Audiobooks, eBooks, music, TV shows and movies are available to library card holders as downloadable digital media from the ACLD website.\n\nIf a library card holder wishes to checkout an item that is not currently available, they may place a hold request on that item through the online catalog. By entering their library card number, a patron can then choose the branch they wish to have the item delivered to once it becomes available.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q. How do I reserve, or place a \"hold,\" on library materials? |url=http://ask.aclib.us/faq/67625 |publisher=Alachua County Library District |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe Library District does not have late fees. However, five or more overdue items or $50.00 worth of overdue materials will block borrowing privileges until the items are returned or paid for.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fines|url=http://www.aclib.us/fines|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lost Materials|url=http://www.aclib.us/lost-materials|publisher=Alachua County Library District|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> Additionally, any items returned by patrons with damaged or missing parts will result in a standard replacement charge for that individual.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.aclib.us/patronaccounts |title=Patron Accounts |publisher=Alachua County Library District |access-date=9 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Services ==\nApart from library card privileges, the Alachua County Library District branches offer other services including meeting rooms, events for all ages, ebooks, audiobooks, computer access, free mp3 downloads, downloadable magazines, Wi-Fi, printing, interlibrary loans, proctoring, and literacy tutoring for adults and ESOL learners.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclib.us/services|title=Services {{!}} Alachua County Library District|website=www.aclib.us|access-date=2016-09-06}}</ref> Working with the University of Florida's Center for Autism and Related Disabilities, the Library District offers sensory storytime, a special storytime open to all children but designed to serve children with sensory integration challenges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclib.us/high-springs/blog/sensory-storytime|title=Sensory Storytime {{!}} Alachua County Library District|website=www.aclib.us|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref> The library district also offers mailing services of print material to the homebound of Alachua County. Additionally, multiple branch locations have served as polling locations during Alachua County elections.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wcjb.com/local-news/2012/10/early-voting-alachua-county |title=Early Voting for Alachua County |publisher=Diversified Broadcasting Inc. |date=27 October 2012 |website=WCJB TV-20 |access-date=9 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317031438/http://wcjb.com/local-news/2012/10/early-voting-alachua-county |archive-date=17 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Library support==\n[[File:ACLD book sale Gainesville.jpg|thumb|352x352px|The Friends of the Library fall book sale, October 25, 2016.]]\nThe Library District is supported by the '''[http://folacld.org/ Friends of the Library]''' (established in 1954) with a bi-annual book sale, usually in October and April.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Bookstore|url=http://folacld.org/|publisher=Friends of the Library|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> The Friends of the Library book sale is the largest of its kind in the state of Florida, with 500,000 books, magazines, videos, puzzles, games, and more available for sale. The book sale also has a Collector's Corner, which specializes in rare books, including first editions, signed copies, and Florida-related materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://folacld.org/n_sale_colcor.html|title=FOL Sale Collector's Corner Page|website=folacld.org|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gainesville.com/lifestyle/20150417/friends-of-the-library-spring-book-sale-is-next-weekend|title=Friends of the Library Spring Book Sale is next weekend|last=Valencic|first=Brittany|date=2015-04-17|work=|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|access-date=2016-10-25|via=}}</ref> The sale offers more than 64 categories of books, including general fiction, classics, cookbooks, children's and young adult fiction, and comic books. Proceeds from the sale fund different programs benefiting the Alachua County Library District. In 2015-2016, the book sale proceeds funded $150,000 in direct support to the library district for adult and children's programming, for purchasing library materials, and for other needs. The library also raised scholarship funds for library personnel to complete their [[Master of Library and Information Science]] degrees. The Friends of the Library also helped fund a variety of literacy projects, including the Family Literacy Festival, distribution of books for Head Start programs, and mini-grants for local literacy organizations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://folacld.org/n_projcts.html|title=FOL Projects Page|website=folacld.org|access-date=2016-10-25}}</ref>\n\nThe library district is also supported by the '''[http://acldfound.org/ ACLD Foundation]''', which raises money through the sale of name plaques and author galas.<ref name=\"carrico\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=ACLD Foundation|url=http://www.acldfound.org/|publisher=Alachua County Library District Foundation, Inc.|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n*The Alachua County Library District was co-recipient of the [[Florida Library Association]] 2010 Library of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite web|title=Florida Library Awards Recipients 2010|url=http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/Awards%20Recipients_2010.pdf|publisher=Florida Library Association|accessdate=16 December 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415013644/http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/Awards%20Recipients_2010.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The Library Partnership branch was selected for the [[Ash Center for Democratic Governance and Innovation]] Bright Ideas program in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=New Bright Ideas Recognizes Innovative Government|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/news-events/news/press-releases/ash-bright-ideas|publisher=Harvard University John F. Kennedy School of Government|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n*Sol Hirsch, Director of the district (2004-2011), received the 2011 Peggy Sullivan Award for Public Library Administrators Supporting Services to Children from the American Library Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sol M. Hirsch receives 2011 Sullivan Award |url=http://americanlibrariesmagazine.org/news/ala/sol-m-hirsch-receives-2011-sullivan-award |publisher=American Library Association |accessdate=16 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421011557/http://americanlibrariesmagazine.org/news/ala/sol-m-hirsch-receives-2011-sullivan-award |archivedate=21 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Curry|first=Christopher|title=Library director Sol Hirsch to retire|url=http://www.gainesville.com/article/20110301/ARTICLES/110309963|accessdate=21 December 2011|newspaper=Gainesville Sun|date=March 1, 2011}}</ref>\n*The district was one of five libraries and five museums to receive the 2011 [[National Medal for Museum and Library Service]] awarded by the [[Institute of Museum and Library Services]].<ref>{{cite web|title=IMLS Announces the 2011 National Medal for Museum and Library Service Recipients|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/imls-announces-the-2011-national-medal-for-museum-and-library-service-recipients-132527718.html|publisher=PRNewswire|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n*The Alachua County Library District received the Betty Davis Miller Youth Services - Children award at the [[Florida Library Association]] annual conference in 2016 for their Sensory Storytime program for children on the autism spectrum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/2016/2016%20Award%20Winners.pdf|title=2016 Award Winners|website=Florida Library Association|access-date=2016-09-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913085253/http://www.flalib.org/awards_documents/2016/2016%20Award%20Winners.pdf|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181109233735/https://www.aclib.us/ Official Alachua County Library District Website]\n* [http://catalog.aclib.us/ Official catalog] and [http://catalog.aclib.us/Children/ Children's catalog]\n* [https://catalog.aclib.us/mobile/ Official Mobile Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:County library systems in Florida|Alachua]]\n[[Category:Education in Alachua County, Florida|Library]]\n[[Category:Public libraries in Florida]]\n", "name_user": "Cocogruver", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alachua_County_Library_District"}
{"title_page": "Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name             = The Marquess of Dufferin and Ava\n| honorific-suffix = [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| office           = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]]\n| term_start       = 1937\n| term_end         = 1940\n| predecessor      = [[Herbrand Sackville, 9th Earl De La Warr|The Earl De La Warr]]\n| successor        = [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]]\n| office1          = [[Lord-in-waiting]] to [[King George VI]]\n| term_start1      = 1936\n| term_end1        = 1937\n| predecessor1     = [[Charles Duncombe, 3rd Earl of Feversham|The Earl of Feversham]]\n| successor1       = [[Hugh Fortescue, 5th Earl Fortescue|The Earl Fortescue]]\n| birth_name       = Basil Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood\n| birth_date       = {{birth-date|6 April 1909|}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|1945|03|25|1909|04|06}}\n| death_place      = [[Burma]]\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education        = [[Lockers Park School]]<br>[[Eton College]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]\n| parents          = [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Maureen Constance Guinness<br>|3 July 1930|25 March 1945|reason=his death}}\n| children         = [[Caroline Blackwood|Lady Caroline Blackwood]]<br>Lady Perdita Blackwood<br>[[Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Sheridan Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n| signature        = \n| relations        = [[Basil Temple Blackwood]] (uncle)<br>[[Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 2nd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] (uncle)\n}}\n'''Basil Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (6 April 1909 \u2013 25 March 1945), styled '''Earl of Ava''' from 1918 until 1930, was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and soldier.\n\n==Early life ==\nDufferin was the eldest child, and only son, of the [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] and the former Brenda Woodhouse. Following his father's succession to the [[Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|marquessate]] in 1918, he was known as the Earl of Ava.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>  His grandfather, a descendant of the 18th-century playwright [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]], \"was the cultured and worldly [[1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\", who served as the [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy and Governor-General of India]].<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\nHe was educated at [[Lockers Park School]]<ref>Michael Bloch, ''James Lees-Milne: The Life'' (2009), p. 17</ref> and [[Eton College]], and then at [[Balliol College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>  At Eton, when aged sixteen, he won the coveted Rosebery Prize, the highest possible distinction for a history pupil.  At [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], he was friends with among others [[Frank Pakenham, 7th Earl of Longford]]. He was also a contemporary and close friend of the poet [[John Betjeman]]. Betjeman wrote of his friend as \"the dark, heavy-lidded companion\" in his poem ''Brackenbury Scholar of Balliol''.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter university Lord Dufferin pursued a career in politics. He made his maiden speech in the [[House of Lords]] in December 1931, aged just 22, during a debate on [[India]]. Only a few days later he was appointed to the Indian Franchise Committee which was to tour the country during its researches.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\">{{cite news |last1=Meyers |first1=Jeffrey |title=The Tragic Destiny of Basil Blackwood |url=https://standpointmag.co.uk/issues/april-2014/features-april-14-tragic-death-basil-blackwood-jeffrey-meyers-burma/ |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]] |date=24 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter his return from India he was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Philip Kerr, 11th Marquess of Lothian|11th Marquess of Lothian]], who was [[Under-Secretary of State for India]], and then to the 3rd Viscount Halifax (later [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|1st Earl of Halifax]]) who was successively [[President of the Board of Education]] from 1932 to 1935, [[Secretary of State for War]] in 1935, and [[Lord Privy Seal]] from 1935 to 1937.  Lord Dufferin was chairman of the [[Primrose League]] from 1932 to 1934, a [[Lord-in-waiting]] to [[King George VI]] from 1936 to 1937 and was himself appointed [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]] in 1937, serving until his resignation in 1940.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/> \n\n===War service===\nIn 1940, he resigned from the government to join the [[British Army]], refusing a post in the [[World War II]] coalition government of [[Winston Churchill]].  He received a commission as a captain in the [[Royal Horse Guards]] in July 1940 but was released from the Army in 1941 to become Director of the Empire Division of the [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Information]]. The following year he undertook a special mission abroad for the ministry, and rejoined the Army in 1944.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\">{{cite web|title=Dufferin and Ava, Marquess of (UK, 1888 - 1988)|url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/dufferin1888.htm|website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk|publisher=Heraldic Media Limited|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nLord Dufferin was serving with the Indian Field Broadcasting Unit on 25 March 1945 when he was filmed demanding the surrender of Japanese troops who were sheltered in a tunnel; the film then captured Lord Dufferin's death when a Japanese mortar shell landed on the unit, just a few weeks short of his 36th birthday.<ref>Rankin, Nicholas. ''Telegram from Guernica: The Extraordinary Life of George Steer, War Correspondent''. Faber & Faber, 2003.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Maureen Constance Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (n\u00e9e Guinness), Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava.jpg|thumb|Maureen Constance Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (n\u00e9e Guinness), Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava, by Bassano Ltd, 1933]]\n\nOn 3 July 1930, Lord Dufferin and Ava was married to brewery heiress [[Maureen Constance Guinness]], the second daughter of Hon. Arthur Ernest Guinness, himself the second son of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]] at [[St. Margaret's, Westminster]].<ref name=\"TCJ2018\">{{cite news |title=The Dufferin and Ava Shamrock Tiara |url=http://www.thecourtjeweller.com/2018/03/the-dufferin-and-ava-shamrock-tiara.html |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=The Court Jeweller |date=17 March 2018}}</ref> They had three children:<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink= Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1196 |pages= |ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref>\n\n* [[Caroline Blackwood|Lady Caroline Maureen Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] (1931\u20131996), who married three times; first to [[Lucian Freud]] (son of architect [[Ernst L. Freud]] and grandson of [[Sigmund Freud]]), secondly to Israel Citkowitz, and lastly to American poet [[Robert Lowell]].<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>\n* Lady Perdita Maureen Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (b. 1934)<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>\n* [[Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Sheridan Frederick Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th and last Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] (1938\u20131988), who married his fourth cousin [[Lindy, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava|Serena Belinda \"Lindy\" Rosemary Guinness]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Reginato|first1=James|title=The Marchioness|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/culture/art-and-design/2009/02/lady_dufferin|accessdate=17 August 2017|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=February 2009}}</ref>\n\nBecause he has no known grave in Burma, Lord Dufferin is commemorated by the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]], his name listed on Face 1 of the Rangoon Memorial in [[Taukkyan War Cemetery]].<ref name=cwgc>[http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/1291914/HAMILTON-TEMPLE-BLACKWOOD,%20BASIL%20SHERIDAN] CWGC Casualty Record.</ref>  In the family burial ground of Campo Santo at [[Clandeboye]], [[County Down]] a Celtic cross stands to mark his loss and the earlier losses of the Dufferin family to war. His friend [[John Betjeman]] wrote the poem ''In Memory of Basil, Marquess of Dufferin and Ava'' in his memory.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\nHis widow married twice after his death, first to Major Harry Alexander Desmond ('Kelpie') Buchanan [[Military Cross|MC]] in 1948 (divorced 1954) and second in 1955 to judge [[John Maude]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (1901-1986), but against precedent always used the title she acquired from her first marriage. Maureen, Lady Dufferin died on 3 May 1998 and is buried at Clandeboye.<ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: Maureen, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-maureen-marchioness-of-dufferin-and-ava-1158254.html|work=The Independent|date=23 May 1998|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image =\n| crest = 1st:  On a Cap of Maintenance Gules turned up Ermine a Crescent Argent (Blackwood);  2nd, On a Ducal Coronet Or a Martlet Gold (Temple);  3rd, a Demi-Antelope affront\u00e9e Ermine attired and unguled Or holding between his hoofs a Heart Gules (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of an Marquess]]\n| escutcheon = Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Azure a Fess Or in chief a Crescent Argent between two Mullets of the second and in base a Mascle of the third (Blackwood);  2nd, quarterly, 1st and 4th, Or an Eagle displayed Sable, 2nd and 3rd, Argent two Bars Sable each charged with three Martlets Or (Temple);  3rd, Gules three Cinquefoils pierced Ermine on a Chief Or a Lion passant of the field (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| supporters = Dexter:  a Lion Gules armed and langued Azure gorged with a Tressure flory-counterflory Or;  Sinister:  an Heraldic Tiger Ermine gorged with a like Tressure Gules;  each supporter supporting a Flag Staff proper therefrom flowing a Banner Or charged with a Peacock in his Pride also proper\n| motto = Per Vias Rectas (By straight ways)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|83115338}}\n* [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F62950 Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, Basil Sheridan (1909-1945) 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava, colonial administrator] at [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Charles Duncombe, 3rd Earl of Feversham|The Earl of Feversham]] | after=[[Hugh Fortescue, 5th Earl Fortescue|The Earl Fortescue]] | years=1936&ndash;1937}}\n{{succession box  | title  = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]]  | years  = 1937&ndash;1940  | before = [[Herbrand Sackville, 9th Earl De La Warr|The Earl De La Warr]]  | after  = [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] | before=[[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] | after=[[Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] | years=1930\u20131945}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dufferin and Ava, Basil Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1945 deaths]]\n[[Category:British military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:British Army personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Horse Guards officers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Lockers Park School]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) Baronesses- and Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Blackwood family|Basil]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants]]\n[[Category:Foreign Office personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Dufferin and Ava]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Most Honourable]]\n| name             = The Marquess of Dufferin and Ava\n| honorific-suffix = [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| office           = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]]\n| term_start       = 1937\n| term_end         = 1940\n| predecessor      = [[Herbrand Sackville, 9th Earl De La Warr|The Earl De La Warr]]\n| successor        = [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]]\n| office1          = [[Lord-in-waiting]] to [[King George VI]]\n| term_start1      = 1936\n| term_end1        = 1937\n| predecessor1     = [[Charles Duncombe, 3rd Earl of Feversham|The Earl of Feversham]]\n| successor1       = [[Hugh Fortescue, 5th Earl Fortescue|The Earl Fortescue]]\n| birth_name       = Basil Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood\n| birth_date       = {{birth-date|6 April 1909|}}\n| birth_place      =\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|df=yes|1945|03|25|1909|04|06}}\n| death_place      = [[Burma]]\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = \n| party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education        = [[Lockers Park School]]<br>[[Eton College]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Balliol College, Oxford]]\n| parents          = [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Maureen Constance Guinness<br>|3 July 1930|25 March 1945|reason=his death}}\n| children         = [[Caroline Blackwood|Lady Caroline Blackwood]]<br>Lady Perdita Blackwood<br>[[Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Sheridan Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\n| signature        = \n| relations        = [[Basil Temple Blackwood]] (uncle)<br>[[Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 2nd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] (uncle)\n}}\n'''Basil Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava''' [[Deputy Lieutenant|DL]] (6 April 1909 \u2013 25 March 1945), styled '''Earl of Ava''' from 1918 until 1930, was a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] politician and soldier.\n\n==Early life ==\nDufferin was the eldest child, and only son, of the [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|3rd Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] and the former Brenda Woodhouse. Following his father's succession to the [[Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|marquessate]] in 1918, he was known as the Earl of Ava.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>  His grandfather, a descendant of the 18th-century playwright [[Richard Brinsley Sheridan]], \"was the cultured and worldly [[1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]]\", who served as the [[Governor-General of India|Viceroy and Governor-General of India]].<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\nHe was educated at [[Lockers Park School]]<ref>Michael Bloch, ''James Lees-Milne: The Life'' (2009), p. 17</ref> and [[Eton College]], and then at [[Balliol College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>  At Eton, when aged sixteen, he won the coveted Rosebery Prize, the highest possible distinction for a history pupil.  At [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], he was friends with among others [[Frank Pakenham, 7th Earl of Longford]]. He was also a contemporary and close friend of the poet [[John Betjeman]]. Betjeman wrote of his friend as \"the dark, heavy-lidded companion\" in his poem ''Brackenbury Scholar of Balliol''.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter university Lord Dufferin pursued a career in politics. He made his maiden speech in the [[House of Lords]] in December 1931, aged just 22, during a debate on [[India]]. Only a few days later he was appointed to the Indian Franchise Committee which was to tour the country during its researches.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\">{{cite news |last1=Meyers |first1=Jeffrey |title=The Tragic Destiny of Basil Blackwood |url=https://standpointmag.co.uk/issues/april-2014/features-april-14-tragic-death-basil-blackwood-jeffrey-meyers-burma/ |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=[[Standpoint (magazine)|Standpoint]] |date=24 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nAfter his return from India he was appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to the [[Philip Kerr, 11th Marquess of Lothian|11th Marquess of Lothian]], who was [[Under-Secretary of State for India]], and then to the 3rd Viscount Halifax (later [[E. F. L. Wood, 1st Earl of Halifax|1st Earl of Halifax]]) who was successively [[President of the Board of Education]] from 1932 to 1935, [[Secretary of State for War]] in 1935, and [[Lord Privy Seal]] from 1935 to 1937.  Lord Dufferin was chairman of the [[Primrose League]] from 1932 to 1934, a [[Lord-in-waiting]] to [[King George VI]] from 1936 to 1937 and was himself appointed [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]] in 1937, serving until his resignation in 1940.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/> \n\n===War service===\nIn 1940, he resigned from the government to join the [[British Army]], refusing a post in the [[World War II]] coalition government of [[Winston Churchill]].  He received a commission as a captain in the [[Royal Horse Guards]] in July 1940 but was released from the Army in 1941 to become Director of the Empire Division of the [[Ministry of Information (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Information]]. The following year he undertook a special mission abroad for the ministry, and rejoined the Army in 1944.<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\">{{cite web|title=Dufferin and Ava, Marquess of (UK, 1888 - 1988)|url=http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/dufferin1888.htm|website=www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk|publisher=Heraldic Media Limited|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nLord Dufferin was serving with the Indian Field Broadcasting Unit on 25 March 1945 when he was filmed demanding the surrender of Japanese troops who were sheltered in a tunnel; the film then captured Lord Dufferin's death when a Japanese mortar shell landed on the unit, just a few weeks short of his 36th birthday.<ref>Rankin, Nicholas. ''Telegram from Guernica: The Extraordinary Life of George Steer, War Correspondent''. Faber & Faber, 2003.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Maureen Constance Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (n\u00e9e Guinness), Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava.jpg|thumb|Maureen Constance Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (n\u00e9e Guinness), Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava, by Bassano Ltd, 1933]]\n\nOn 3 July 1930, Lord Dufferin and Ava was married to brewery heiress Maureen Constance Guinness, the second daughter of Hon. Arthur Ernest Guinness, himself the second son of [[Edward Guinness, 1st Earl of Iveagh]] at [[St. Margaret's, Westminster]].<ref name=\"TCJ2018\">{{cite news |title=The Dufferin and Ava Shamrock Tiara |url=http://www.thecourtjeweller.com/2018/03/the-dufferin-and-ava-shamrock-tiara.html |accessdate=6 January 2020 |work=The Court Jeweller |date=17 March 2018}}</ref> They had three children:<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite book |title= Burke's Peerage, Baronetage & Knighthood|publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry |editor= Mosley, Charles |editorlink= Charles Mosley (genealogist) |edition=107 |year= 2003 |page=1196 |pages= |ref=Burke |isbn=0-9711966-2-1}}</ref>\n\n* [[Caroline Blackwood|Lady Caroline Maureen Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood]] (1931\u20131996), who married three times; first to [[Lucian Freud]] (son of architect [[Ernst L. Freud]] and grandson of [[Sigmund Freud]]), secondly to Israel Citkowitz, and lastly to American poet [[Robert Lowell]].<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>\n* Lady Perdita Maureen Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood (b. 1934)<ref name=\"cracroftspeerage\"/>\n* [[Sheridan Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava|Sheridan Frederick Terence Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 5th and last Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]] (1938\u20131988), who married his fourth cousin [[Lindy, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava|Serena Belinda \"Lindy\" Rosemary Guinness]] in 1964.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Reginato|first1=James|title=The Marchioness|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/culture/art-and-design/2009/02/lady_dufferin|accessdate=17 August 2017|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=February 2009}}</ref>\n\nBecause he has no known grave in Burma, Lord Dufferin is commemorated by the [[Commonwealth War Graves Commission]], his name listed on Face 1 of the Rangoon Memorial in [[Taukkyan War Cemetery]].<ref name=cwgc>[http://www.cwgc.org/find-war-dead/casualty/1291914/HAMILTON-TEMPLE-BLACKWOOD,%20BASIL%20SHERIDAN] CWGC Casualty Record.</ref>  In the family burial ground of Campo Santo at [[Clandeboye]], [[County Down]] a Celtic cross stands to mark his loss and the earlier losses of the Dufferin family to war. His friend [[John Betjeman]] wrote the poem ''In Memory of Basil, Marquess of Dufferin and Ava'' in his memory.<ref name=\"Meyers2014\"/>\n\nHis widow married twice after his death, first to Major Harry Alexander Desmond ('Kelpie') Buchanan [[Military Cross|MC]] in 1948 (divorced 1954) and second in 1955 to judge [[John Maude]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]] (1901-1986), but against precedent always used the title she acquired from her first marriage. Maureen, Lady Dufferin died on 3 May 1998 and is buried at Clandeboye.<ref>{{cite web |title=Obituary: Maureen, Marchioness of Dufferin and Ava |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-maureen-marchioness-of-dufferin-and-ava-1158254.html|work=The Independent|date=23 May 1998|accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Arms==\n\n{{Infobox COA wide\n| image =\n| crest = 1st:  On a Cap of Maintenance Gules turned up Ermine a Crescent Argent (Blackwood);  2nd, On a Ducal Coronet Or a Martlet Gold (Temple);  3rd, a Demi-Antelope affront\u00e9e Ermine attired and unguled Or holding between his hoofs a Heart Gules (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| coronet = A [[Coronet|Coronet of an Marquess]]\n| escutcheon = Quarterly, 1st and 4th, Azure a Fess Or in chief a Crescent Argent between two Mullets of the second and in base a Mascle of the third (Blackwood);  2nd, quarterly, 1st and 4th, Or an Eagle displayed Sable, 2nd and 3rd, Argent two Bars Sable each charged with three Martlets Or (Temple);  3rd, Gules three Cinquefoils pierced Ermine on a Chief Or a Lion passant of the field (Hamilton, Earl of Clanbrassill)\n| supporters = Dexter:  a Lion Gules armed and langued Azure gorged with a Tressure flory-counterflory Or;  Sinister:  an Heraldic Tiger Ermine gorged with a like Tressure Gules;  each supporter supporting a Flag Staff proper therefrom flowing a Banner Or charged with a Peacock in his Pride also proper\n| motto = Per Vias Rectas (By straight ways)\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|83115338}}\n* [https://discovery.nationalarchives.gov.uk/details/c/F62950 Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, Basil Sheridan (1909-1945) 4th Marquess of Dufferin and Ava, colonial administrator] at [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Charles Duncombe, 3rd Earl of Feversham|The Earl of Feversham]] | after=[[Hugh Fortescue, 5th Earl Fortescue|The Earl Fortescue]] | years=1936&ndash;1937}}\n{{succession box  | title  = [[Under-Secretary of State for the Colonies]]  | years  = 1937&ndash;1940  | before = [[Herbrand Sackville, 9th Earl De La Warr|The Earl De La Warr]]  | after  = [[George Henry Hall, 1st Viscount Hall|George Hall]]}}\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=