{"title_page": "Hern\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez Matte", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Hern\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez Matte''' (Santiago, Chile, May 16th, 1972) Chilean author, director and screenwriter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0735341/|title=Hernan Rodriguez Matte|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> is principally known for his literary work<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hernan-Rodriguez-Matte/e/B0076CGPDQ/|title=Books on Amazon|last=Rodriguez Matte|first=Hernan|date=|website=www.amazon.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> and his extensive work as a screenwriter. He is the author of the novel Barrio Alto<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez M., Hern\u00e1n, 1972-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/63241745|title=Barrio alto|date=2004|publisher=Alfaguara|isbn=956-239-318-6|edition=1. ed|location=Providencia, Santiago de Chile|oclc=63241745}}</ref> and the creator of the successful television series \u2018La Colonia\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=La colonia (serie de televisi\u00f3n)|date=2019-10-23|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=La_colonia_(serie_de_televisi%C3%B3n)&oldid=120697680|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> and \u2018Pap\u00e1 Mono\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=Pap\u00e1 mono|date=2019-09-10|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pap%C3%A1_mono&oldid=119171461|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> among others. \n\n== Biography ==\n\nIn the 90s, he achieved great notoriety for his column \"La Vida Seg\u00fan Benito<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez M., Hern\u00e1n, 1972-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/48246660|title=La vida seg\u00fan Benito|date=1998|publisher=Editorial Los Andes|isbn=956-7014-07-8|edition=1. ed|location=Santiago de Chile|oclc=48246660}}</ref>\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.cl/books/about/La_vida_seg%C3%BAn_Benito.html?id=SXUsAQAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=La vida seg\u00fan Benito|last=M|first=Hern\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez|date=1998|publisher=Editorial Los Andes|language=es}}</ref> in the missing youth publication Zona de Contacto<ref>{{Citation|title=Zona de Contacto|date=2019-06-16|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Zona_de_Contacto&oldid=116738300|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>, of [[El Mercurio]]. In 2000, he completed his MFA (Master in Screenwriting) at the prestigious [[American Film Institute]] in Los Angeles, California; and worked on translating and adapting formats on [[Sony Pictures Television]] for the Hispanic market. One of the most successful formats was the creation and development of \u2018Bienvenida Realidad\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/tv/news/chile-station-sets-ctit-co-production-1117800515/|title=Chile station sets CTIT co-production|last=Staff|first=Variety|last2=Staff|first2=Variety|date=2001-06-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>; a television series commissioned by Sony Pictures Television and aired by [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|Chilean National Television]] in 2004 and later acquired by [[Se\u00f1al Colombia|Cadena 3]], [[RCN Televisi\u00f3n|RCN]], Sony Spin United States, Rede CNT Brasil and [[Teleamazonas]] Ecuador.\n\nIn the year of 2005 while based in Chile, he published his first novel titled Barrio Alto<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez M., Hern\u00e1n, 1972-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/63241745|title=Barrio alto|date=2004|publisher=Alfaguara|isbn=956-239-318-6|edition=1. ed|location=Providencia, Santiago de Chile|oclc=63241745}}</ref> under [[Alfaguara|Editorial Alfaguara]]. The book achieved significant sales successes, but hard literary criticism.\n\nHern\u00e1n then began a prolific career as a television screenwriter, writing for hit series such as \u2018[[Casado con hijos (Chilean TV series)|Casado con Hijos]]\u2019, \u2018Tiempo Final\u2019, \u2018La Nany\u2019, \u2018Tres son Multitud\u2019, \u2018Cartas de Mujer\u2019, \u2018El diario secreto de una profesional\u2019, \u2018La Colonia\u2019, \u2018[[El Reemplazante|El reemplazante]]\u2019, etc. He later worked as a director on the series \u2018Una pareja Dispareja\u2019 with actors [[Luciano Cruz-Coke|Luciano Cruz Coke]], Felipe Braun and [[Delfina Guzm\u00e1n]] among others. He is the creator of the successful series \u2018La Colonia\u2019, a comedy broadcast by [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]] that produced more than 200 episodes and quickly became the only Chilean sitcom sold abroad. In 2011 he was named director of scripts on [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|TVN]], where he wrote and was head of the scriptwriter team for \u2018[[El Reemplazante]]\u2019, which was then awarded the best series of the year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24horas.cl/tendencias/espectaculosycultura/el-reemplazante-arraso-en-los-premios-altazor-638787|title=\"El Reemplazante\" arras\u00f3 en los Altazor|date=2013-05-09|website=24Horas.cl|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>. He soon returned to the screen on [[Canal 13 (Chilean TV channel)|Channel 13]], where he was the creator and executive producer of the successful series \u2018[[:es:Pap\u00e1_mono|Pap\u00e1 Mono]]\u2019 that won 32 share points. He has been repeatedly nominated for the [[Altazor Award]] as best fiction writer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodr\u00edguez Matte, Hernan}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chilean writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chilean writers]]\n[[Category:Chilean television directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Primary sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{Unreliable sources|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n'''Hern\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez Matte''' (Santiago, Chile, May 16th, 1972) Chilean author, director and screenwriter<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0735341/|title=Hernan Rodriguez Matte|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> is principally known for his literary work<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hernan-Rodriguez-Matte/e/B0076CGPDQ/|title=Books on Amazon|last=Rodriguez Matte|first=Hernan|date=|website=www.amazon.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> and his extensive work as a screenwriter. He is the author of the novel Barrio Alto<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez M., Hern\u00e1n, 1972-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/63241745|title=Barrio alto|date=2004|publisher=Alfaguara|isbn=956-239-318-6|edition=1. ed|location=Providencia, Santiago de Chile|oclc=63241745}}</ref> and the creator of the successful television series \u2018La Colonia\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=La colonia (serie de televisi\u00f3n)|date=2019-10-23|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=La_colonia_(serie_de_televisi%C3%B3n)&oldid=120697680|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> and \u2018Pap\u00e1 Mono\u2019<ref>{{Citation|title=Pap\u00e1 mono|date=2019-09-10|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pap%C3%A1_mono&oldid=119171461|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> among others. \n\n== Biography ==\n\nIn the 90s, he achieved great notoriety for his column \"La Vida Seg\u00fan Benito\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.cl/books/about/La_vida_seg%C3%BAn_Benito.html?id=SXUsAQAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=La vida seg\u00fan Benito|last=M|first=Hern\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez|date=1998|publisher=Editorial Los Andes|language=es}}</ref> in the missing youth publication Zona de Contacto<ref>{{Citation|title=Zona de Contacto|date=2019-06-16|url=https://es.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Zona_de_Contacto&oldid=116738300|work=Wikipedia, la enciclopedia libre|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>, of [[El Mercurio]]. In 2000, he completed his MFA (Master in Screenwriting) at the prestigious [[American Film Institute]] in Los Angeles, California; and worked on translating and adapting formats on [[Sony Pictures Television]] for the Hispanic market. One of the most successful formats was the creation and development of \u2018Bienvenida Realidad\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/tv/news/chile-station-sets-ctit-co-production-1117800515/|title=Chile station sets CTIT co-production|last=Staff|first=Variety|last2=Staff|first2=Variety|date=2001-06-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>; a television series commissioned by Sony Pictures Television and aired by [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|Chilean National Television]] in 2004 and later acquired by [[Se\u00f1al Colombia|Cadena 3]], [[RCN Televisi\u00f3n|RCN]], Sony Spin United States, Rede CNT Brasil and [[Teleamazonas]] Ecuador.\n\nIn the year of 2005 while based in Chile, he published his first novel titled Barrio Alto<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rodr\u00edguez M., Hern\u00e1n, 1972-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/63241745|title=Barrio alto|date=2004|publisher=Alfaguara|isbn=956-239-318-6|edition=1. ed|location=Providencia, Santiago de Chile|oclc=63241745}}</ref> under [[Alfaguara|Editorial Alfaguara]]. The book achieved significant sales successes, but hard literary criticism.\n\nHern\u00e1n then began a prolific career as a television screenwriter, writing for hit series such as \u2018[[Casado con hijos (Chilean TV series)|Casado con Hijos]]\u2019, \u2018Tiempo Final\u2019, \u2018La Nany\u2019, \u2018Tres son Multitud\u2019, \u2018Cartas de Mujer\u2019, \u2018El diario secreto de una profesional\u2019, \u2018La Colonia\u2019, \u2018[[El Reemplazante|El reemplazante]]\u2019, etc. He later worked as a director on the series \u2018Una pareja Dispareja\u2019 with actors [[Luciano Cruz-Coke|Luciano Cruz Coke]], Felipe Braun and [[Delfina Guzm\u00e1n]] among others. He is the creator of the successful series \u2018La Colonia\u2019, a comedy broadcast by [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]] that produced more than 200 episodes and quickly became the only Chilean sitcom sold abroad. In 2011 he was named director of scripts on [[Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile|TVN]], where he wrote and was head of the scriptwriter team for \u2018[[El Reemplazante]]\u2019, which was then awarded the best series of the year<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.24horas.cl/tendencias/espectaculosycultura/el-reemplazante-arraso-en-los-premios-altazor-638787|title=\"El Reemplazante\" arras\u00f3 en los Altazor|date=2013-05-09|website=24Horas.cl|language=es|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref>. He soon returned to the screen on [[Canal 13 (Chilean TV channel)|Channel 13]], where he was the creator and executive producer of the successful series \u2018[[:es:Pap\u00e1_mono|Pap\u00e1 Mono]]\u2019 that won 32 share points. He has been repeatedly nominated for the [[Altazor Award]] as best fiction writer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodr\u00edguez Matte, Hernan}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chilean writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chilean writers]]\n[[Category:Chilean television directors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Chilean novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Hernyboy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hern%C3%A1n_Rodr%C3%ADguez_Matte"}
{"title_page": "Wolves and moose on Isle Royale", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n[[File:Wolves of Isle Royale (1966) Wolves vs Moose.png|thumb|A pack of wolves hunting a moose on Isle Royale, 1966]]\n\nThe single [[predator]]-single [[prey]] relationship between '''[[gray wolf|wolves]] and [[western moose|moose]] on [[Isle Royale]]''' in [[Lake Superior]] is unique, and has been the subject of detailed study for over 50 years. Isle Royale, the principal island of [[Isle Royale National Park]] in [[Michigan]] in the [[United States]], is an isolated island with little [[wikt:migration|migration]] of animals into and out of the island, and as a [[national park]], human interaction and impact on the two species is also limited. Both the wolves and the moose first became established populations on Isle Royale in the 1900s. Over the fifty years of the study, the populations of both moose and wolves have shown repeated spikes and declines and have not settled to a balanced relationship. The moose populations have ranged from 500 to 2500 while the number of wolves has ranged from almost 50<ref name=IRWO>{{cite web|url=http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview/overview/at_a_glance.html|title=About The Project: Overview|work=The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> to down to two.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nps.gov/isro/learn/nature/wolves.htm | title=Wolves - Isle Royale National Park (U.S. National Park Service)}}</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\">Just 2 wolves left on Isle Royale, Detroit News, Retrieved April 18, 2016: http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2016/04/11/isle-royale-wolves-two/82893406/</ref>. As of 2018, wolves are being released at Isle Royale in hopes of bringing back the wolf population.\n\nThe relationship between wolves and moose on Isle Royale has been the subject of the longest predator-prey research study, begun in 1958.<ref name=\"overview\">\"Overview of the Ecology and Research of Wolves and Moose on Isle Royale.\" The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale. April 16, 2006 [http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview_of_research.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208141144/http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview_of_research.htm |date=December 8, 2006 }}</ref> The wolves have been subject to inbreeding and carry a spinal deformity.<ref name =\"Myers\">''Isle Royale pack down to 2 female wolves'' by John Myers  March 30, 2011  ''Duluth News Tribune'' newspaper </ref> As of the 2014 count, there were only 9 wolves on the island,<ref name=\"MR\">{{cite news|url=http://michiganradio.org/post/isle-royale-researchers-take-air-birds-eye-view-wolves-and-moose|title=Isle Royale researchers take to the air for bird's eye view of wolves and moose |last=Rebecca Williams|date=Jan 6, 2015|publisher=Michigan Radio|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> with the 2015\u20132017 counts showing only 2.<ref>Two wolves survive in world's longest running predator-prey study, Science, Retrieved September 7, 2017: http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/04/two-wolves-survive-world-s-longest-running-predator-prey-study</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web | access-date=April 18, 2015 | first1=John | last1=Flesher | url=https://www.usnews.com/news/science/news/articles/2015/04/17/scientists-3-wolves-remain-at-isle-royale-national-park | title=Scientists say Isle Royale National Park gray wolf population down to 2 and may soon die out | date=April 17, 2015 | website=usnews.com/}}</ref> A review completed in 2014 determined that new wolves would not be introduced into the park to attempt a genetic rescue,<ref name=\"DP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedickinsonpress.com/sports/outdoors/3697616-pair-wolves-cross-lake-superior-island-no-success-breeding|title=Pair of wolves cross to Lake Superior island, but no success in breeding |last=Lisa Kaczke|date=Mar 11, 2015|work=The Dickinson Press|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/> but as of December 2016, the National Park Service had instead decided to introduce 20 to 30 wolves to the island.  In 2018, three females and one male wolf from Minnesota were transferred to the island system.<ref name=\"2018Relocation\">{{cite web |title=Isle Royale wolf relocation |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/10/13/isle-royale-wolf-relocation-project/1634106002/ |publisher=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIsle Royale National Park is made up of about 400 islands, and is in the northwest portion of [[Lake Superior]]. It is about {{convert|50|mi|km}} from Michigan's shore, and {{convert|12|mi|km}} from the Canadian shore. The main island is about {{convert|45|mi|km}} long, and {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} wide at the widest point, with an area of {{convert|205|mi2|km2}}. There are no roads, and no motorized vehicles are allowed on the island.<ref name=\"NPS-stats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nature.nps.gov/stats/viewReport.cfm|title=Ranking Report for Recreation Visits in 2008|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=August 20, 2009}}</ref> The park is closed from September to May during which the wolf-moose study personnel are the only humans resident on the island.\n\n==Wolf-moose dynamics interactions==\n[[File:Moose superior.jpg|thumb|left|Moose health and population on Isle Royale have a great effect on other animal and plant life.]]\nAs an isolated island, Isle Royale initially had neither wolves nor moose. The moose are believed to have either swum across [[Lake Superior]] from [[Minnesota]] in the early 1900s or were stocked on the island by man for the purpose of recreational hunting.<ref name=\"flesher\">Flesher, John. \"Biologist Never Tires of Watching Wolves, Moose on Isle Royale.\" [http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2006/03/24/biologist_never_tires_of_watching_wolves/?page=full The Boston Globe] March 24, 2006. April 9, 2006</ref>  In 1949 a pair of wolves crossed an ice bridge from [[Ontario]] to the island during a harsh winter.<ref name=\"line\">Line, Les. \"In Long-Running Wolf-Moose Drama, Wolves Recover From Disaster.\" The New York Times March 19, 1996. April 3, 2006 [http://www.admin.mtu.edu/urel/PressReleases/feature/wolves/wolf.html]</ref> But because only one pair of wolves migrated to the island, they have suffered from severe [[inbreeding]]. According to Rolf Peterson, a professor at [[Michigan Technological University]] and the lead wolf-moose researcher, \"Moose were isolated here 100 years ago. Most of the [[gene]]s are still here, but they have enough population (to compensate). There are so few wolves that they have lost genetic variability. The scientific dogma suggests that they are not going to make it.\"<ref name=\"weier\">Weier, Anita. \"Isle is Perfect Laboratory for Moose and Wolves \u2013 Their Interactions Studied Since 1958. (Saturday Extra)\" The Capital Times (Madison, WI) (May 31, 2003): 1B.</ref>  In fact, all of the wolves' [[DNA]] on Isle Royale can be traced back to one ancestor.<ref name=\"line\" />  Inbreeding leads to inbreeding depression and fitness problems, often accompanied by violent social rejection by other wolves.<ref name=\"weier\" />\n\nWhen the study began in 1958, many researchers believed the two species would eventually reach a population equilibrium of about 25 wolves and 1,500 moose; but there has been no sign of this, with populations fluctuating unpredictably.<ref name=\"myers\">Myers, John. \"Isle Royale's Moose Numbers Continue Crash.\" [http://www.duluthsuperior.com/mld/duluthsuperior/14064838.html Duluth News Tribune] March 10, 2006. April 2, 2006</ref>  The highest number of moose observed since the arrival of wolves was 2,450 in 1995. The highest number of wolves observed was 50 in 1980 followed by a population crash to 14 by 1982.<ref name=\"line\" />  As of 2005, there were 540 moose, the lowest recorded, and a relatively high population of 30 wolves. In 2008, there were 700 moose and 23 wolves.\n\nThe density of the two species depends strongly on the density of [[forage]]. Moose prefer [[birch]] and [[aspen]] trees, which used to grow plentifully on the island, but over a century of moose browsing have been largely replaced by the less nutritious [[balsam fir]], which now makes up 59% of a moose's diet.<ref name=\"mclaren\">McLaren, B.E., and R.O. Peterson. \"Wolves, moose, and tree rings on Isle Royale. (Isle Royale National Park, Michigan).\" Science 266.n5190 (Dec 2, 1994): 1555(4).</ref> Even this has declined dramatically: as of 2002, [[understory]] growth of balsam fir was at 5%, down 40% from 19th century observations.<ref name=\"weier\" />  The plant is more plentiful on the east side of the island, which draws a higher concentration of moose.<ref name=\"wilmers\">{{cite journal | last1 = Wilmers | first1 = CC | last2 = Post | first2 = ES | last3 = Peterson | first3 = RO | last4 = Vucetich | first4 = JA | year = 2006 | title = Disease mediated switch from top-down to bottom-up control exacerbates climatic effects on moose population dynamics | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/11a4a1bbf5499ad475eb83d22d0374bbcd68ca49| journal = Ecology Letters | volume = 9 | issue = 4| pages = 383\u2013389 | doi=10.1111/j.1461-0248.2006.00890.x| pmid = 16623723 }}</ref>  Because balsam fir does not give sufficient moisture, moose have recently been spotted eating snow, a very rare occurrence.<ref name=\"myers\" />  They have also been sighted eating [[lichen]], which researcher Rolf Peterson has compared to eating dust.<ref name=\"myers\" />  When the moose population grows too high, the balsam fir population crashes, leading to a crash in the moose population, in a continuing population \"see-saw\". Moose mostly die from the consequences of [[malnutrition]]: they become emaciated and slowed down by [[arthritis]], until they are easy prey for a [[pack (canine)|wolf pack]]. Also, calves suffer from malnutrition when they are born during a winter with snow too deep for easy foraging.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />\n\nMoose make up nine-tenths of an Isle Royale wolf's diet (the remainder being [[snowshoe hare]] and [[North American beaver|beaver]]).<ref name=\"overview\" /> Moose in their prime years commonly outrun wolves in a hunt, especially on soft snow: moose can cross snow two feet deep at {{convert|20|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"flesher\" />  Even if wolves can catch up to a moose, they cannot always bring it down; researchers often find wolves with hunting bruises and scars.<ref name=\"weier\" />  To improve their chances, wolves pick out moose which are calves, old, diseased, or injured. The typical moose killed is about 12 years old and suffers from arthritis, osteoporosis, and/or periodontitis.<ref name=\"isleroyalestudy\">\"Isle Royale is a study in moose and wolves.\" Akron Beacon Journal (Akron, OH) (Dec 29, 2005): NA.</ref>  Eighty to ninety percent of moose are brought down by wolves rather than directly by disease,<ref name=\"peterson\">Peterson, R.O., R.E. Page, and K.M. Dodge. \"Wolves, moose, and the allometry of population cycles.\" Science 224 (June 22, 1984): 1350(3)</ref> and each wolf kills an average of between 0.44 and 1.69 moose per month.<ref name=\"vucetich\">Vucetich, JA & RO Peterson. 2004. Long-term population and predation dynamics of wolves on Isle Royale. Pages 281\u2013292 in Biology and Conservation of Wild Canids, edited by D. Macdonald & C. Sillero-Zubiri, Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\n==Wolf population dynamics==\n[[File:Canis lupus laying.jpg|thumb|right|The wolf is the prominent predator on Isle Royale.]]\nWolves on the island have, historically, been separated into three or four packs, with each pack usually having between three and eight members, including two or three [[Names given to animals young|pup]]s. The number of wolves in a pack depends mainly on the amount of snow that fell in the previous winter. In winters with light snow, pups tend to leave the pack to find mates, so packs run at four or five members; in heavily snowy winters, the pups stay with the pack, which can reach ten to twelve members. If many members of a pack die, the pack dissolves and a new one forms within a year. One pack will dissolve about once every thirty years.<ref name=\"vucetich\" />\n\nIn 2006, the wolf population, with the exception of 10 loners and separate pairs, formed three [[pack (canine)|pack]]s; the ''east pack'', the ''middle pack'', and the ''Chippewa Harbor pack''.<ref name=\"moosedecline\">\"Moose population decline leaves Isle Royale wolves scrapping for food.\" The America's Intelligence Wire (March 11, 2006): NA.</ref> Wolf packs on the island have been known to fight to try to extend their [[territoriality|territory]] and, thus, supply of moose. In 2006, the east pack killed Chippewa Harbor pack's alpha male, as witnessed by John Vucetich, a professor at [[Michigan Technological University]] and one of the lead researchers on the island, who believed that the Chippewa Harbor pack may die off without their leader.<ref name=\"moosedecline\"/>\n\n===Old Gray Guy===\n\nDuring the winter of 1997 a particularly virile wolf (later named \"Old Gray Guy\" and wolf No. 93) crossed the 15 miles of ice to Isle Royale. Old Gray Guy was larger and more territorial than the other Isle Royale wolves.   His own pack grew to an unusually large 10 wolves, and displaced and drove to extinction one of the other 4 packs.<ref name =OldGray/>   He was so-named because as he aged his fur became very pale, an unusual phenomenon. It was determined that by 2009, 56% of the wolves on Isle Royale had descended from Old Gray Guy.<ref name =OldGray/>\n\n\"We don't know of any other instance \u2014 except when they first came \u2014 of wolves crossing the ice,\" said John A. Vucetich, the lead author of a study of the wolves published online in The Proceedings of the Royal Society B in 2011. \"The entire population is descended from a single female.\" <ref name =OldGray/>\n\nThe wolf population on Isle Royale is small, averaging only about 23 wolves. By the end of his eight years of breeding, he produced 34 pups, those had produced an additional 45 pups.<ref name =OldGray/>\n\nSuch a genetic impact is evidence for substantially greater fitness of Old Gray compared to the other inbred wolves on the island. Scientists expected that such an introduction would create a \"genetic rescue\" population boom, but it did not happen. \"A co-author of the study, Rolf O. Peterson, a research professor at Michigan Technological University, said that the population of Isle Royale hangs on by a thread, as it has for decades. The average reproduction after the Old Gray Guy arrived was no different from before. Yet this does not mean that he had no effect.\"<ref name =OldGray/>\n\n\"The simple interpretation is that genetic rescue doesn't work,\" said Dr. Vucetich, an assistant professor of wildlife ecology at Michigan Technological University. \"But what happened here is that when the immigrant came in 1997, in the decade that followed, the moose population declined radically. It's plausible that we didn't see an effect because the wolves were suffering from some other trouble that disguised the benefit. What if wolf No. 93 had never arrived? Dr. Vucetich said that it is impossible to know for sure, but the Isle Royale wolves might have disappeared completely. It may be that the Old Gray Guy arrived just in time.\"<ref name =\"OldGray\">Nicholas Bakalar, New York Times April 4, 2011 https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/science/05wolf.html?_r=1 Wolf Crosses the Lake Superior Ice to Become Leader of the Pack\"</ref>\n\n==Other species==\n[[File:Snowshoe hare.jpg|thumb|A snowshoe hare, one of the other species impacting the wolf and moose on Isle Royale.]]\nOnce a moose is brought down and killed, wolves have to compete with [[scavenger|scavenging]] [[raven]]s. Ravens are tenacious scavengers that can easily dodge the strike of a wolf and are unbothered by them. Ravens can eat and store up to {{convert|2|lb|kg|spell=in}} in a few days, which is minuscule compared to the storage capacity of wolves, which is up to {{convert|18|lb|kg|spell=in}} in just a few hours.<ref name=\"vucetich\"/>\n\nOther anti-social species have an effect, though rather small, on the relationship between wolves and moose on Isle Royale. Before wolves hunted them to [[extinction]], [[coyote]]s used to inhabit the island. Beavers and snowshoe hares also have an effect on both populations, because beavers and snowshoe hares are the only two animals that wolves prey on excluding moose, constituting a tenth of an Isle Royale wolf's diet.<ref name=\"overview\"/> The beaver population has sharply declined since the arrival of wolves, but they still are present, and though they are not a prime food source for typical wolves, they are the second to moose as the most consumed animal by the wolves on the island.<ref name=\"species\">\"Species of Lesser Significance.\" [http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/fauna7/fauna5l.htm ParkNet]. July 4, 2002. National Park Service. May 18, 2006</ref>  Beavers benefit both species. They are as easy prey for wolves and they create aquatic [[macrophyte]]s, very nutritional plants for moose, although the macrophytes are also consumed by the beavers.<ref name=\"mclaren\" /> Though wolves are thought to contribute to the decline in beaver, researchers believe that the decline of aspen, the primary food source of beavers, which used to be plentiful, could have led to their decrease. Beavers have been exposed to predation by having to travel long distances to find only parts of the island where aspen remains.\n\nSnowshoe hares, the third most consumed animal by wolves on Isle Royale constitute a very small portion of the wolves' diet, because snowshoe hares are so difficult to catch. Researchers have found that wolves do not show much interest in preying on hares, and only feed on them incidentally.<ref name=\"species\" />  Snowshoe hares have a negative effect on moose as they eat some of the same vegetation that moose eat, which only contributes to the decline in appropriate forage for moose.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />  The red fox is yet another animal that inhabits Isle Royale; red foxes mainly feed on snowshoe hares and occasionally scavenge on moose, or any other meat a wolf leaves behind. Wolves do not commonly hunt foxes, though wolves have been observed killing foxes when they attempt to feed on an animal carcass.<ref name=\"species\" />\n\n==Studies==\n\nIn 1958, as a graduate student at Purdue University, [[L. David Mech]] began studying the wolves of Isle Royale.<ref name =TheFarReach>''The Far Reach: The lifework of a Minnesota biologist circles the world'' by Greg Breining  Pages 32-41 Minnesota Department of Resources Conservation Volunteer Magazine. January\u2013February 2004</ref>  One of the first publications on the subject of the Wolves on the Island of Isle Royale  was the book \"The Wolves of Isle Royale\" by Mech which led to the prominence of both the author and the topic.  The book was published in 1966 by the Department of the Interior, having evolved from his doctoral thesis.  Mech's project  would become the world's longest-running predator-prey study.<ref name = \"Mihell\">''A Reasonable Illusion'' by Conor Mihell ''Sierra'' magazine November/December 2019 issue Pages 30-35 </ref>\n\n==Climate effects==\n[[Climate]] plays a major role in the moose-wolf relationship as well. Since [[El Ni\u00f1o]] hit in 1998, the climate has warmed up, which has significantly affected the moose population across North America.<ref name=\"predatorsandprey\">\"Predators and prey affected by warming. (Ecology)(decline in numbers of North American moose, increase in number of wolves)(Brief Article).\" USA Today (Magazine) 133.2711 (August 2004): 7(1).</ref>  The warmer climate in recent years has produced more [[Moose winter tick]]s, which consume the blood of animals, making them more susceptible to [[anemia]], and induce the moose to scratch off their hair, exposing them to [[hypothermia]] in cold weather.<ref name=\"predatorsandprey\" />  A moose can have tens of thousands of ticks feeding on its blood at one time, each sucking up to one milliliter of blood. The biting ticks cause a lot of discomfort for the moose, so they try to get the ticks off their bodies by biting off their hair, and rubbing up against trees. This preoccupies moose, and keeps them from browsing for food, which can lead to malnutrition. Compounded with blood loss, moose weakened by ticks are easier for wolves to kill.<ref name=\"goodrich\">Goodrich, Marcia. \"Isle Royale Wolf-Moose Study Report.\" [http://www.admin.mtu.edu/urel/news/media_relations/211/ Michigan Tech News/Media]. March 4, 2004. Michigan Technological University. April 3, 2006</ref>  Ticks are more prominent in years where spring arrives earlier than usual, because when they fall on ground not covered in snow, then they can reproduce. Otherwise, they die out.<ref name=\"roach\">Roach, John. \"Wolves, Ticks, Send Michigan Moose Numbers Plummeting.\" [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2005/06/0606_050606_wolves.html National Geographic] June 6, 2005. April 5, 2006</ref>  Then, if the summer is hot, ticks are able to reproduce at a higher rate. Hot summers also lead to moose resting in the shade, or in the water to keep cool, making them easier prey for wolves. Also, hot summers lead to tougher foraging for moose which makes them less prepared and more vulnerable to the winter. Not only has the recent warming of Isle Royale hurt the moose, but completely opposite problems harm them also. Harsh winters pose significant problems to moose, because moose have problems finding food when there is too much snow on the ground.<ref name=\"isleroyalestudy\" />  The less snow there is, the more freely moose can move around the island. When there is a significant amount of snow, moose stay in [[conifer]] [[swamp]]s, making them easier prey for wolves, because they are more confined, and immobilized due to the snow.<ref name=\"moosedecline\" />    Deep or heavy snow decreases the speed and agility of moose that is necessary to evade wolf attacks, and calves born during a winter with particularly deep snow are more vulnerable to being weaker prey for wolves later on in their lives because of foraging problems that occur when the snow is deep.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />\nThe keen survival instincts of moose have been clearly evident from the studying of their actions on Isle Royale. Female moose (called \"cows\") have been spotted on nearby smaller islands, around the main island of Isle Royale, because they swim across to give birth. This allows for them to give birth and raise their young without the threat of wolves preying on their young when they are vulnerable. This also causes trouble for moose that are born in the winter, because they can no longer swim across the water to another island, and must raise the new calf in the snow. Once the calves are physically mature, they are able to swim back, and are then able to better protect themselves from wolves, as they are then in their prime years.<ref name=\"weier\" />\n\n==Trends==\nInitially, it was thought that the wolf and moose populations would reach a stable balance,<ref name=IRWO/>. However, during the nearly sixty years of the study, the populations of both species have fluctuated up and down with the number of moose ranging from a high of nearly 2500 down to 500 and the number of wolves ranging from a high of 50<ref name=IRWO/> down to one in 2017/18.\n\nDuring 2016, the wolf population was nearly extirpated with only two severely inbred wolves present.<ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bhanoo|first1=Sindya|title=Only Three Wolves Left on an Island Full of Prey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/28/science/only-three-wolves-left-on-an-island-full-of-prey.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=New York Times|date=27 April 2015}}</ref> The moose population was about 2/3rd of its historical maximum with ample forage and growing rapidly. Absent a new infusion of migrant wolves, or human intervention, the original situation of a high moose population limited only by starvation is the prospect.<ref name=Annual14-15>{{cite web|author1=John A. Vucetich and Rolf O. Peterson|title=Ecological Studies of Wolves on Isle Royale Annual Report 2014\u201315|url=http://isleroyalewolf.org/sites/default/files/annual-report-pdf/Annual%20Report%2019%20April%202015.pdf|website=isleroyalewolf.org|publisher=School of Forest Resources and Environmental Science, Michigan Technological University|accessdate=April 20, 2015|date=31 March 2015|quote=These changes are part of a longer trend. Since 2009 the wolf population has dropped by nearly 90%. As a result of very low wolf abundance, each of the past four years has seen unprecedented low rates of predation. In response, the moose population has been growing at a mean rate of 22% per year for each of the past four years. If that growth rate persists, the moose population will double in size over the next three years.}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHowever, in December 2016, the [[National Park Service]] (NPS) put forward a plan in which they would add 20 to 30 [[Northwestern wolf|wolves]] to the island in order to prevent the pack from disappearing completely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle Royale may add 20\u201330 wolves to keep pack from disappearing|url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2016/12/16/isle-royale-wolves-michigan/95486866/|publisher=Freep|date=December 16, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Sarah Hoy et al. of Michigan Technological University published results of a 40-year study showing a decrease in the size and lifespans of moose. Analysis of moose skulls documents a 16% shrinkage likely consistent with warming winters which are correlated with smaller brain size in one-year-old moose. The moose population has tripled in the past decade, reaching about 1,600 in the 2017 survey, but as wolf die off approaches, competition for food due to overpopulation will become a further stress on moose.<ref>{{cite report |title=The shrinking moose of Isle Royale |publisher=Michigan Technological University |date=December 18, 2017 |url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2017-12/mtu-tsm121817.php |access-date=December 24, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Climate warming is associated with smaller body size and shorter lifespans in moose near their southern range limit |authors=Sarah R. Hoy, Rolf O. Peterson, John A. Vucetich |journal=Global Change Biology |volume=24 |issue=6 |pages=2488\u20132497 |date=December 10, 2017 |doi=10.1111/gcb.14015|pmid=29226555 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, with the release of the final Environmental Impact Statement, the NPS formally proposed to relocate 20 to 30 wolves to the island over a three-year time period, starting immediately. An official Record of Decision was released on 7 June 2018 selecting this preferred alternative over several others including taking no action, introducing wolves over a longer 20-year period, and delaying immediate action but allowing for the possibility of future action after the continued monitoring of moose population metrics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parkplanning.nps.gov/projectHome.cfm?projectId=59316|title=National Park Service - PEPC - Environmental Impact Statement to Address the Presence of Wolves at Isle Royale National Park|website=parkplanning.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref> As of June 2018, the NPS is actively developing specific implementation strategies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/isro/learn/news/press-release-national-park-service-releases-record-of-decision-to-introduce-wolves-at-isle-royale-national-park.htm|title=Press Release National Park Service Releases Record of Decision to Introduce Wolves at Isle Royale National Park - Isle Royale National Park (U.S. National Park Service)|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-06-09}}</ref> By the end of 2018, three females and a male were trapped in Minnesota and relocated to the park, with more to come.<ref name=\"2018Relocation\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.isleroyalewolf.org The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/isro/ Isle Royale National Park Web site]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*\"Food Fight: Wolves Pack Up to Out-Eat Ravens.\" Ascribe Higher Education News Service (August 19, 2004): NA.\n*[http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/56270 ''The Moose of Isle Royale,''] (1934). [[Adolph Murie]]. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan, Museum of Zoology, Misc. Publication No. 25. Study of the moose population before the wolves arrived.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolves And Moose On Isle Royale}}\n[[Category:Isle Royale]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Great Lakes region (North America)]]\n[[Category:Ecological experiments]]\n[[Category:Wolves in the United States]]\n[[Category:Moose]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2012}}\n[[File:Wolves of Isle Royale (1966) Wolves vs Moose.png|thumb|A pack of wolves hunting a moose on Isle Royale, 1966]]\n\nThe single [[predator]]-single [[prey]] relationship between '''[[gray wolf|wolves]] and [[western moose|moose]] on [[Isle Royale]]''' in [[Lake Superior]] is unique, and has been the subject of detailed study for over 50 years. Isle Royale, the principal island of [[Isle Royale National Park]] in [[Michigan]] in the [[United States]], is an isolated island with little [[wikt:migration|migration]] of animals into and out of the island, and as a [[national park]], human interaction and impact on the two species is also limited. Both the wolves and the moose first became established populations on Isle Royale in the 1900s. Over the fifty years of the study, the populations of both moose and wolves have shown repeated spikes and declines and have not settled to a balanced relationship. The moose populations have ranged from 500 to 2500 while the number of wolves has ranged from almost 50<ref name=IRWO>{{cite web|url=http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview/overview/at_a_glance.html|title=About The Project: Overview|work=The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref> to down to two.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nps.gov/isro/learn/nature/wolves.htm | title=Wolves - Isle Royale National Park (U.S. National Park Service)}}</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\">Just 2 wolves left on Isle Royale, Detroit News, Retrieved April 18, 2016: http://www.detroitnews.com/story/news/local/michigan/2016/04/11/isle-royale-wolves-two/82893406/</ref>. As of 2018, wolves are being released at Isle Royale in hopes of bringing back the wolf population.\n\nThe relationship between wolves and moose on Isle Royale has been the subject of the longest predator-prey research study, begun in 1958.<ref name=\"overview\">\"Overview of the Ecology and Research of Wolves and Moose on Isle Royale.\" The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale. April 16, 2006 [http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview_of_research.htm] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208141144/http://www.isleroyalewolf.org/overview_of_research.htm |date=December 8, 2006 }}</ref> The wolves have been subject to inbreeding and carry a spinal deformity.<ref name =\"Myers\">''Isle Royale pack down to 2 female wolves'' by John Myers  March 30, 2011  ''Duluth News Tribune'' newspaper </ref> As of the 2014 count, there were only 9 wolves on the island,<ref name=\"MR\">{{cite news|url=http://michiganradio.org/post/isle-royale-researchers-take-air-birds-eye-view-wolves-and-moose|title=Isle Royale researchers take to the air for bird's eye view of wolves and moose |last=Rebecca Williams|date=Jan 6, 2015|publisher=Michigan Radio|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref> with the 2015\u20132017 counts showing only 2.<ref>Two wolves survive in world's longest running predator-prey study, Science, Retrieved September 7, 2017: http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/04/two-wolves-survive-world-s-longest-running-predator-prey-study</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web | access-date=April 18, 2015 | first1=John | last1=Flesher | url=https://www.usnews.com/news/science/news/articles/2015/04/17/scientists-3-wolves-remain-at-isle-royale-national-park | title=Scientists say Isle Royale National Park gray wolf population down to 2 and may soon die out | date=April 17, 2015 | website=usnews.com/}}</ref> A review completed in 2014 determined that new wolves would not be introduced into the park to attempt a genetic rescue,<ref name=\"DP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedickinsonpress.com/sports/outdoors/3697616-pair-wolves-cross-lake-superior-island-no-success-breeding|title=Pair of wolves cross to Lake Superior island, but no success in breeding |last=Lisa Kaczke|date=Mar 11, 2015|work=The Dickinson Press|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/> but as of December 2016, the National Park Service had instead decided to introduce 20 to 30 wolves to the island.  In 2018, three females and one male wolf from Minnesota were transferred to the island system.<ref name=\"2018Relocation\">{{cite web |title=Isle Royale wolf relocation |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2018/10/13/isle-royale-wolf-relocation-project/1634106002/ |publisher=Detroit Free Press |accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIsle Royale National Park is made up of about 400 islands, and is in the northwest portion of [[Lake Superior]]. It is about {{convert|50|mi|km}} from Michigan's shore, and {{convert|12|mi|km}} from the Canadian shore. The main island is about {{convert|45|mi|km}} long, and {{convert|9|mi|km|spell=in}} wide at the widest point, with an area of {{convert|205|mi2|km2}}. There are no roads, and no motorized vehicles are allowed on the island.<ref name=\"NPS-stats\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nature.nps.gov/stats/viewReport.cfm|title=Ranking Report for Recreation Visits in 2008|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=August 20, 2009}}</ref> The park is closed from September to May during which the wolf-moose study personnel are the only humans resident on the island.\n\n==Wolf-moose dynamics interactions==\n[[File:Moose superior.jpg|thumb|left|Moose health and population on Isle Royale have a great effect on other animal and plant life.]]\nAs an isolated island, Isle Royale initially had neither wolves nor moose. The moose are believed to have either swum across [[Lake Superior]] from [[Minnesota]] in the early 1900s or were stocked on the island by man for the purpose of recreational hunting.<ref name=\"flesher\">Flesher, John. \"Biologist Never Tires of Watching Wolves, Moose on Isle Royale.\" [http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2006/03/24/biologist_never_tires_of_watching_wolves/?page=full The Boston Globe] March 24, 2006. April 9, 2006</ref>  In 1949 a pair of wolves crossed an ice bridge from [[Ontario]] to the island during a harsh winter.<ref name=\"line\">Line, Les. \"In Long-Running Wolf-Moose Drama, Wolves Recover From Disaster.\" The New York Times March 19, 1996. April 3, 2006 [http://www.admin.mtu.edu/urel/PressReleases/feature/wolves/wolf.html]</ref> But because only one pair of wolves migrated to the island, they have suffered from severe [[inbreeding]]. According to Rolf Peterson, a professor at [[Michigan Technological University]] and the lead wolf-moose researcher, \"Moose were isolated here 100 years ago. Most of the [[gene]]s are still here, but they have enough population (to compensate). There are so few wolves that they have lost genetic variability. The scientific dogma suggests that they are not going to make it.\"<ref name=\"weier\">Weier, Anita. \"Isle is Perfect Laboratory for Moose and Wolves \u2013 Their Interactions Studied Since 1958. (Saturday Extra)\" The Capital Times (Madison, WI) (May 31, 2003): 1B.</ref>  In fact, all of the wolves' [[DNA]] on Isle Royale can be traced back to one ancestor.<ref name=\"line\" />  Inbreeding leads to inbreeding depression and fitness problems, often accompanied by violent social rejection by other wolves.<ref name=\"weier\" />\n\nWhen the study began in 1958, many researchers believed the two species would eventually reach a population equilibrium of about 25 wolves and 1,500 moose; but there has been no sign of this, with populations fluctuating unpredictably.<ref name=\"myers\">Myers, John. \"Isle Royale's Moose Numbers Continue Crash.\" [http://www.duluthsuperior.com/mld/duluthsuperior/14064838.html Duluth News Tribune] March 10, 2006. April 2, 2006</ref>  The highest number of moose observed since the arrival of wolves was 2,450 in 1995. The highest number of wolves observed was 50 in 1980 followed by a population crash to 14 by 1982.<ref name=\"line\" />  As of 2005, there were 540 moose, the lowest recorded, and a relatively high population of 30 wolves. In 2008, there were 700 moose and 23 wolves.\n\nThe density of the two species depends strongly on the density of [[forage]]. Moose prefer [[birch]] and [[aspen]] trees, which used to grow plentifully on the island, but over a century of moose browsing have been largely replaced by the less nutritious [[balsam fir]], which now makes up 59% of a moose's diet.<ref name=\"mclaren\">McLaren, B.E., and R.O. Peterson. \"Wolves, moose, and tree rings on Isle Royale. (Isle Royale National Park, Michigan).\" Science 266.n5190 (Dec 2, 1994): 1555(4).</ref> Even this has declined dramatically: as of 2002, [[understory]] growth of balsam fir was at 5%, down 40% from 19th century observations.<ref name=\"weier\" />  The plant is more plentiful on the east side of the island, which draws a higher concentration of moose.<ref name=\"wilmers\">{{cite journal | last1 = Wilmers | first1 = CC | last2 = Post | first2 = ES | last3 = Peterson | first3 = RO | last4 = Vucetich | first4 = JA | year = 2006 | title = Disease mediated switch from top-down to bottom-up control exacerbates climatic effects on moose population dynamics | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/11a4a1bbf5499ad475eb83d22d0374bbcd68ca49| journal = Ecology Letters | volume = 9 | issue = 4| pages = 383\u2013389 | doi=10.1111/j.1461-0248.2006.00890.x| pmid = 16623723 }}</ref>  Because balsam fir does not give sufficient moisture, moose have recently been spotted eating snow, a very rare occurrence.<ref name=\"myers\" />  They have also been sighted eating [[lichen]], which researcher Rolf Peterson has compared to eating dust.<ref name=\"myers\" />  When the moose population grows too high, the balsam fir population crashes, leading to a crash in the moose population, in a continuing population \"see-saw\". Moose mostly die from the consequences of [[malnutrition]]: they become emaciated and slowed down by [[arthritis]], until they are easy prey for a [[pack (canine)|wolf pack]]. Also, calves suffer from malnutrition when they are born during a winter with snow too deep for easy foraging.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />\n\nMoose make up nine-tenths of an Isle Royale wolf's diet (the remainder being [[snowshoe hare]] and [[North American beaver|beaver]]).<ref name=\"overview\" /> Moose in their prime years commonly outrun wolves in a hunt, especially on soft snow: moose can cross snow two feet deep at {{convert|20|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"flesher\" />  Even if wolves can catch up to a moose, they cannot always bring it down; researchers often find wolves with hunting bruises and scars.<ref name=\"weier\" />  To improve their chances, wolves pick out moose which are calves, old, diseased, or injured. The typical moose killed is about 12 years old and suffers from arthritis, osteoporosis, and/or periodontitis.<ref name=\"isleroyalestudy\">\"Isle Royale is a study in moose and wolves.\" Akron Beacon Journal (Akron, OH) (Dec 29, 2005): NA.</ref>  Eighty to ninety percent of moose are brought down by wolves rather than directly by disease,<ref name=\"peterson\">Peterson, R.O., R.E. Page, and K.M. Dodge. \"Wolves, moose, and the allometry of population cycles.\" Science 224 (June 22, 1984): 1350(3)</ref> and each wolf kills an average of between 0.44 and 1.69 moose per month.<ref name=\"vucetich\">Vucetich, JA & RO Peterson. 2004. Long-term population and predation dynamics of wolves on Isle Royale. Pages 281\u2013292 in Biology and Conservation of Wild Canids, edited by D. Macdonald & C. Sillero-Zubiri, Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\n==Wolf population dynamics==\n[[File:Canis lupus laying.jpg|thumb|right|The wolf is the prominent predator on Isle Royale.]]\nWolves on the island have, historically, been separated into three or four packs, with each pack usually having between three and eight members, including two or three [[Names given to animals young|pup]]s. The number of wolves in a pack depends mainly on the amount of snow that fell in the previous winter. In winters with light snow, pups tend to leave the pack to find mates, so packs run at four or five members; in heavily snowy winters, the pups stay with the pack, which can reach ten to twelve members. If many members of a pack die, the pack dissolves and a new one forms within a year. One pack will dissolve about once every thirty years.<ref name=\"vucetich\" />\n\nIn 2006, the wolf population, with the exception of 10 loners and separate pairs, formed three [[pack (canine)|pack]]s; the ''east pack'', the ''middle pack'', and the ''Chippewa Harbor pack''.<ref name=\"moosedecline\">\"Moose population decline leaves Isle Royale wolves scrapping for food.\" The America's Intelligence Wire (March 11, 2006): NA.</ref> Wolf packs on the island have been known to fight to try to extend their [[territoriality|territory]] and, thus, supply of moose. In 2006, the east pack killed Chippewa Harbor pack's alpha male, as witnessed by John Vucetich, a professor at [[Michigan Technological University]] and one of the lead researchers on the island, who believed that the Chippewa Harbor pack may die off without their leader.<ref name=\"moosedecline\"/>\n\n===Old Gray Guy===\n\nDuring the winter of 1997 a particularly virile wolf (later named \"Old Gray Guy\" and wolf No. 93) crossed the 15 miles of ice to Isle Royale. Old Gray Guy was larger and more territorial than the other Isle Royale wolves.   His own pack grew to an unusually large 10 wolves, and displaced and drove to extinction one of the other 4 packs.<ref name =OldGray/>   He was so-named because as he aged his fur became very pale, an unusual phenomenon. It was determined that by 2009, 56% of the wolves on Isle Royale had descended from Old Gray Guy.<ref name =OldGray/>\n\n\"We don't know of any other instance \u2014 except when they first came \u2014 of wolves crossing the ice,\" said John A. Vucetich, the lead author of a study of the wolves published online in The Proceedings of the Royal Society B in 2011. \"The entire population is descended from a single female.\" <ref name =OldGray/>\n\nThe wolf population on Isle Royale is small, averaging only about 23 wolves. By the end of his eight years of breeding, he produced 34 pups, those had produced an additional 45 pups.<ref name =OldGray/>\n\nSuch a genetic impact is evidence for substantially greater fitness of Old Gray compared to the other inbred wolves on the island. Scientists expected that such an introduction would create a \"genetic rescue\" population boom, but it did not happen. \"A co-author of the study, Rolf O. Peterson, a research professor at Michigan Technological University, said that the population of Isle Royale hangs on by a thread, as it has for decades. The average reproduction after the Old Gray Guy arrived was no different from before. Yet this does not mean that he had no effect.\"<ref name =OldGray/>\n\n\"The simple interpretation is that genetic rescue doesn't work,\" said Dr. Vucetich, an assistant professor of wildlife ecology at Michigan Technological University. \"But what happened here is that when the immigrant came in 1997, in the decade that followed, the moose population declined radically. It's plausible that we didn't see an effect because the wolves were suffering from some other trouble that disguised the benefit. What if wolf No. 93 had never arrived? Dr. Vucetich said that it is impossible to know for sure, but the Isle Royale wolves might have disappeared completely. It may be that the Old Gray Guy arrived just in time.\"<ref name =\"OldGray\">Nicholas Bakalar, New York Times April 4, 2011 https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/05/science/05wolf.html?_r=1 Wolf Crosses the Lake Superior Ice to Become Leader of the Pack\"</ref>\n\n==Other species==\n[[File:Snowshoe hare.jpg|thumb|A snowshoe hare, one of the other species impacting the wolf and moose on Isle Royale.]]\nOnce a moose is brought down and killed, wolves have to compete with [[scavenger|scavenging]] [[raven]]s. Ravens are tenacious scavengers that can easily dodge the strike of a wolf and are unbothered by them. Ravens can eat and store up to {{convert|2|lb|kg|spell=in}} in a few days, which is minuscule compared to the storage capacity of wolves, which is up to {{convert|18|lb|kg|spell=in}} in just a few hours.<ref name=\"vucetich\"/>\n\nOther anti-social species have an effect, though rather small, on the relationship between wolves and moose on Isle Royale. Before wolves hunted them to [[extinction]], [[coyote]]s used to inhabit the island. Beavers and snowshoe hares also have an effect on both populations, because beavers and snowshoe hares are the only two animals that wolves prey on excluding moose, constituting a tenth of an Isle Royale wolf's diet.<ref name=\"overview\"/> The beaver population has sharply declined since the arrival of wolves, but they still are present, and though they are not a prime food source for typical wolves, they are the second to moose as the most consumed animal by the wolves on the island.<ref name=\"species\">\"Species of Lesser Significance.\" [http://www.cr.nps.gov/history/online_books/fauna7/fauna5l.htm ParkNet]. July 4, 2002. National Park Service. May 18, 2006</ref>  Beavers benefit both species. They are as easy prey for wolves and they create aquatic [[macrophyte]]s, very nutritional plants for moose, although the macrophytes are also consumed by the beavers.<ref name=\"mclaren\" /> Though wolves are thought to contribute to the decline in beaver, researchers believe that the decline of aspen, the primary food source of beavers, which used to be plentiful, could have led to their decrease. Beavers have been exposed to predation by having to travel long distances to find only parts of the island where aspen remains.\n\nSnowshoe hares, the third most consumed animal by wolves on Isle Royale constitute a very small portion of the wolves' diet, because snowshoe hares are so difficult to catch. Researchers have found that wolves do not show much interest in preying on hares, and only feed on them incidentally.<ref name=\"species\" />  Snowshoe hares have a negative effect on moose as they eat some of the same vegetation that moose eat, which only contributes to the decline in appropriate forage for moose.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />  The red fox is yet another animal that inhabits Isle Royale; red foxes mainly feed on snowshoe hares and occasionally scavenge on moose, or any other meat a wolf leaves behind. Wolves do not commonly hunt foxes, though wolves have been observed killing foxes when they attempt to feed on an animal carcass.<ref name=\"species\" />\n\n==Studies==\n\nIn 1958, as a graduate student at Purdue University, [[L. David Mech]] began studying the wolves of Isle Royale.<ref name =TheFarReach>''The Far Reach: The lifework of a Minnesota biologist circles the world'' by Greg Breining  Pages 32-41 Minnesota Department of Resources Conservation Volunteer Magazine. January\u2013February 2004</ref>  One of the first publications on the subject of the Wolves on the Island of Isle Royale  was the book \"The Wolves of Isle Royale\" by Mech which led to the prominence of both the author and the topic.  The book was published in 1966 by the Department of the Interior, having evolved from his doctoral thesis.  Mech's project  would become the world's longest-running predator-prey study.<ref name = \"Mihell\">''A Reasonable Illusion'' by Conor Mihell ''Sierra'' magazine November/December 2019 issue Pages 30-35 </ref>\n\n==Climate effects==\n[[Climate]] plays a major role in the moose-wolf relationship as well. Since [[El Ni\u00f1o]] hit in 1998, the climate has warmed up, which has significantly affected the moose population across North America.<ref name=\"predatorsandprey\">\"Predators and prey affected by warming. (Ecology)(decline in numbers of North American moose, increase in number of wolves)(Brief Article).\" USA Today (Magazine) 133.2711 (August 2004): 7(1).</ref>  The warmer climate in recent years has produced more [[Moose winter tick]]s, which consume the blood of animals, making them more susceptible to [[anemia]], and induce the moose to scratch off their hair, exposing them to [[hypothermia]] in cold weather.<ref name=\"predatorsandprey\" />  A moose can have tens of thousands of ticks feeding on its blood at one time, each sucking up to one milliliter of blood. The biting ticks cause a lot of discomfort for the moose, so they try to get the ticks off their bodies by biting off their hair, and rubbing up against trees. This preoccupies moose, and keeps them from browsing for food, which can lead to malnutrition. Compounded with blood loss, moose weakened by ticks are easier for wolves to kill.<ref name=\"goodrich\">Goodrich, Marcia. \"Isle Royale Wolf-Moose Study Report.\" [http://www.admin.mtu.edu/urel/news/media_relations/211/ Michigan Tech News/Media]. March 4, 2004. Michigan Technological University. April 3, 2006</ref>  Ticks are more prominent in years where spring arrives earlier than usual, because when they fall on ground not covered in snow, then they can reproduce. Otherwise, they die out.<ref name=\"roach\">Roach, John. \"Wolves, Ticks, Send Michigan Moose Numbers Plummeting.\" [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2005/06/0606_050606_wolves.html National Geographic] June 6, 2005. April 5, 2006</ref>  Then, if the summer is hot, ticks are able to reproduce at a higher rate. Hot summers also lead to moose resting in the shade, or in the water to keep cool, making them easier prey for wolves. Also, hot summers lead to tougher foraging for moose which makes them less prepared and more vulnerable to the winter. Not only has the recent warming of Isle Royale hurt the moose, but completely opposite problems harm them also. Harsh winters pose significant problems to moose, because moose have problems finding food when there is too much snow on the ground.<ref name=\"isleroyalestudy\" />  The less snow there is, the more freely moose can move around the island. When there is a significant amount of snow, moose stay in [[conifer]] [[swamp]]s, making them easier prey for wolves, because they are more confined, and immobilized due to the snow.<ref name=\"moosedecline\" />    Deep or heavy snow decreases the speed and agility of moose that is necessary to evade wolf attacks, and calves born during a winter with particularly deep snow are more vulnerable to being weaker prey for wolves later on in their lives because of foraging problems that occur when the snow is deep.<ref name=\"mclaren\" />\nThe keen survival instincts of moose have been clearly evident from the studying of their actions on Isle Royale. Female moose (called \"cows\") have been spotted on nearby smaller islands, around the main island of Isle Royale, because they swim across to give birth. This allows for them to give birth and raise their young without the threat of wolves preying on their young when they are vulnerable. This also causes trouble for moose that are born in the winter, because they can no longer swim across the water to another island, and must raise the new calf in the snow. Once the calves are physically mature, they are able to swim back, and are then able to better protect themselves from wolves, as they are then in their prime years.<ref name=\"weier\" />\n\n==Trends==\nInitially, it was thought that the wolf and moose populations would reach a stable balance,<ref name=IRWO/>. However, during the nearly sixty years of the study, the populations of both species have fluctuated up and down with the number of moose ranging from a high of nearly 2500 down to 500 and the number of wolves ranging from a high of 50<ref name=IRWO/> down to one in 2017/18.\n\nDuring 2016, the wolf population is now nearly extirpated with only two severely inbred wolves present.<ref name=\"detroitnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bhanoo|first1=Sindya|title=Only Three Wolves Left on an Island Full of Prey|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/28/science/only-three-wolves-left-on-an-island-full-of-prey.html|accessdate=23 November 2015|work=New York Times|date=27 April 2015}}</ref> The moose population was about 2/3rd of its historical maximum with ample forage and growing rapidly. Absent a new infusion of migrant wolves, or human intervention, the original situation of a high moose population limited only by starvation is the prospect.<ref name=Annual14-15>{{cite web|author1=John A. Vucetich and Rolf O. Peterson|title=Ecological Studies of Wolves on Isle Royale Annual Report 2014\u201315|url=http://isleroyalewolf.org/sites/default/files/annual-report-pdf/Annual%20Report%2019%20April%202015.pdf|website=isleroyalewolf.org|publisher=School of Forest Resources and Environmental Science, Michigan Technological University|accessdate=April 20, 2015|date=31 March 2015|quote=These changes are part of a longer trend. Since 2009 the wolf population has dropped by nearly 90%. As a result of very low wolf abundance, each of the past four years has seen unprecedented low rates of predation. In response, the moose population has been growing at a mean rate of 22% per year for each of the past four years. If that growth rate persists, the moose population will double in size over the next three years.}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHowever, in December 2016, the [[National Park Service]] (NPS) put forward a plan in which they would add 20 to 30 [[Northwestern wolf|wolves]] to the island in order to prevent the pack from disappearing completely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Isle Royale may add 20\u201330 wolves to keep pack from disappearing|url=http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2016/12/16/isle-royale-wolves-michigan/95486866/|publisher=Freep|date=December 16, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Sarah Hoy et al. of Michigan Technological University published results of a 40-year study showing a decrease in the size and lifespans of moose. Analysis of moose skulls documents a 16% shrinkage likely consistent with warming winters which are correlated with smaller brain size in one-year-old moose. The moose population has tripled in the past decade, reaching about 1,600 in the 2017 survey, but as wolf die off approaches, competition for food due to overpopulation will become a further stress on moose.<ref>{{cite report |title=The shrinking moose of Isle Royale |publisher=Michigan Technological University |date=December 18, 2017 |url=https://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2017-12/mtu-tsm121817.php |access-date=December 24, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Climate warming is associated with smaller body size and shorter lifespans in moose near their southern range limit |authors=Sarah R. Hoy, Rolf O. Peterson, John A. Vucetich |journal=Global Change Biology |volume=24 |issue=6 |pages=2488\u20132497 |date=December 10, 2017 |doi=10.1111/gcb.14015|pmid=29226555 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, with the release of the final Environmental Impact Statement, the NPS formally proposed to relocate 20 to 30 wolves to the island over a three-year time period, starting immediately. An official Record of Decision was released on 7 June 2018 selecting this preferred alternative over several others including taking no action, introducing wolves over a longer 20-year period, and delaying immediate action but allowing for the possibility of future action after the continued monitoring of moose population metrics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://parkplanning.nps.gov/projectHome.cfm?projectId=59316|title=National Park Service - PEPC - Environmental Impact Statement to Address the Presence of Wolves at Isle Royale National Park|website=parkplanning.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-16}}</ref> As of June 2018, the NPS is actively developing specific implementation strategies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/isro/learn/news/press-release-national-park-service-releases-record-of-decision-to-introduce-wolves-at-isle-royale-national-park.htm|title=Press Release National Park Service Releases Record of Decision to Introduce Wolves at Isle Royale National Park - Isle Royale National Park (U.S. National Park Service)|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-06-09}}</ref> By the end of 2018, three females and a male were trapped in Minnesota and relocated to the park, with more to come.<ref name=\"2018Relocation\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.isleroyalewolf.org The Wolves and Moose of Isle Royale]\n* [http://www.nps.gov/isro/ Isle Royale National Park Web site]\n\n==Bibliography==\n*\"Food Fight: Wolves Pack Up to Out-Eat Ravens.\" Ascribe Higher Education News Service (August 19, 2004): NA.\n*[http://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/handle/2027.42/56270 ''The Moose of Isle Royale,''] (1934). [[Adolph Murie]]. Ann Arbor: University of Michigan, Museum of Zoology, Misc. Publication No. 25. Study of the moose population before the wolves arrived.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolves And Moose On Isle Royale}}\n[[Category:Isle Royale]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Great Lakes region (North America)]]\n[[Category:Ecological experiments]]\n[[Category:Wolves in the United States]]\n[[Category:Moose]]\n", "name_user": "QuarticReeds", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrends:changed a sentence to the past tense", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolves_and_moose_on_Isle_Royale"}
{"title_page": "Sandy Hook, Connecticut", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Sandy Hook, Connecticut\n| settlement_type                 = Village\n| image_skyline                   = PostcardSandyHookPostOfficeAndDam1914.jpg\n| image_size                      = 250px\n| image_caption                   = Sandy Hook post office and dam, from a postcard sent in 1914\n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| coordinates                     = \n| coordinates_footnotes           = \n| subdivision_type                = [[Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[U.S. state]]\n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Connecticut}}\n| subdivision_type2               = [[County (United States)|County]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Metropolitan area\n| subdivision_name3               = [[Greater Danbury|Danbury]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Administrative divisions of Connecticut#Town|Town]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Newtown, Connecticut|Newtown]]\n| established_title               = \n| established_date                = 1711\n| founder                         = \n| seat_type                       = \n| seat                            = \n| unit_pref                       = US\n| population_density_sq_mi        = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_note                 = \n| timezone                        = [[North American Eastern Standard Time|EST]]\n| utc_offset                      = &minus;5\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = &minus;4\n| postal_code_type                = ZIP code\n| postal_code                     = 06482\n| area_code                       = [[Area codes 203 and 475|203/475]]\n| iso_code                        = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Sandy Hook''' is a village in the town of [[Newtown, Connecticut]].  Sandy Hook was founded in 1711.\n\nIt borders the [[Botsford, Connecticut|Botsford]] section of town, Newtown borough, and also the towns of [[Monroe, Connecticut|Monroe]], [[Southbury, Connecticut|Southbury]], and [[Oxford, Connecticut|Oxford]] along the [[Housatonic River]]. The village of Sandy Hook includes the communities of Berkshire, Riverside, Walnut Tree Hill, and Zoar. It also extends, for a short distance, into the Town of Monroe along Old Zoar Road and Bagburn Hill/Jordan Hill Road.\n\n==History==\nSeveral proprietors with land in the same area relocated together to reduce isolation. Within a year of the settlement of Newtown, some of its proprietors began moving away from the central village to some of their larger parcels. Colonists found that the [[Pootatuck River]] at Sandy Hook allowed for the setting up of saw and grist mills. Therefore Sandy Hook was one of the first of the outlying areas settled. The neighborhood did not grow dramatically until the mid-19th century when industrialization was well-established.<ref>Cruson, Daniel, [http://www.newtownhistory.org/the-settlement.html \"A Brief History of Newtown\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128000853/http://www.newtownhistory.org/the-settlement.html |date=2013-01-28 }}, Web page at Newtown Historical Society Web site, accessed December 14, 2012.</ref>\n\n===2012 school shooting===\n{{main article|Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting}}\n<!-- \nNOTE: This section is a short summary of the event. The expanded details should be put in the main article at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n-->\n{{As of|2012|12|alt=On December 14, 2012}}, Adam Lanza shot and killed his mother at home, then went to [[Sandy Hook Elementary School]]<ref name=\"ID\">{{cite news|author=Miguel Llanos|title=Authorities ID gunman who killed 27 in elementary school massacre|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/12/14/15911025-authorities-id-gunman-who-killed-27-in-elementary-school-massacre?lite|newspaper=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=December 14, 2012|date=December 14, 2012}}</ref> where he killed 26 people before taking his own life. It was the {{As of|2012|12|alt=second-deadliest}} mass shooting in U.S. history at the time, after the 2007 [[Virginia Tech shooting]]s.<ref name=\"BBC News school shooting\">{{cite news|title=28 dead in school shooting|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-20730717||publisher=BBC News|accessdate=December 14, 2012|date=December 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christoffersen |first=John |url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONNECTICUT_SCHOOL_SHOOTING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2012-12-14-13-27-48 |title=Official: 27 dead in Conn. school shooting |work=ap.org |accessdate=January 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121217025156/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONNECTICUT_SCHOOL_SHOOTING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2012-12-14-13-27-48 |archivedate=December 17, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2718-201_162-1950/cbs-news-live-video/ |work=CBS News |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214184526/http://www.cbsnews.com/2718-201_162-1950/cbs-news-live-video/ |archive-date=2012-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<!-- \nNOTE: This section is a short summary of the event. The expanded details should be put in the main article at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n-->\n\n[[Image:SandyHook.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sandy Hook in 2007]]\n\n===Landmarks===\n \t\n* [[Nathan B. Lattin Farm]] \u2013 22 Walker Hill Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n \n* [[New York Belting and Packing Co.]] \u2013 45\u201371 and 79\u201389 Glen Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n\n* [[Sanford-Curtis-Thurber House]] \u2013 71 Riverside Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Luther Meade Blackman]], Major during the [[American Civil War]], accused of forging the [[Bat Creek inscription]], born in Sandy Hook, Newtown, in Fairfield County, Connecticut.\n*[https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgamedesigner/23572/james-brunot James Brunot], promoter of the game [[Scrabble]], resident of Newtown, Connecticut in the 1940s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/1953/05/30/only-the-beginning|title=Only the Beginning|last=Mangold|first=William|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n* [[Suzanne Collins]], American television writer and author of ''[[The Underland Chronicles]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games trilogy|The Hunger Games]]'' trilogy,<ref name=NBC-Connecticut>{{cite news|last=Gendreau|first=LeAnne|title=Anticipated Film Based on Local Author\u2019s Book|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/the-scene/events/Anticipated-Film-Based-on-Local-Authors-Book-142804085.html|accessdate=December 28, 2012|newspaper=NBC|date=March 15, 2012}}</ref> resident of Sandy Hook.\n* [[William Hamilton Gibson]], 19th-century American illustrator, author, and naturalist,<ref>Adams, John Coleman, 'William Hamilton Gibson,' {{cite web|url=http://digital.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=newe;cc=newe;rgn=full%20text;idno=newe0021-6;didno=newe0021-6;view=image;seq=00651;node=newe0021-6%3A1|title=New England Magazine|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}, Feb. 1897, p. 643</ref> born in Sandy Hook, Connecticut.\n* [[Charles R. Jackson]], writer and novelist, author of ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]'' lived in Sandy Hook in the 1950s.\n* [[Caitlyn Jenner]] (then Bruce),{{efn|Jenner changed name due to [[gender transition]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author = [[Buzz Bissinger]] |title=Introducing Caitlyn Jenner|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/caitlyn-jenner-bruce-cover-annie-leibovitz/|work=Vanity Fair|date=June 1, 2015|accessdate=June 1, 2015}}</ref> }} [[1976 Summer Olympics]] decathlon gold medalist, attended Newtown High School in Newtown, Connecticut.\n* [[Molly Pearson]], 20th-century stage actress, lived in Sandy Hook, Connecticut at the time of her death in 1959.\n* [[Albert Berger Rossdale]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from New York, lived in Sandy Hook, Connecticut in the early 1930s.\n* [[James Thurber]], writer, satirist, cartoonist, author of ''[[The Secret Life of Walter Mitty]],'' lived in Sandy Hook in the 1930s.\n* [[Marcus Tracy]], professional soccer player, grew up in Newtown, and attended Newtown High School.\n* [[Mead Treadwell]], 13th Lieutenant Governor of Alaska and former Chair of the [[U.S. Arctic Research Commission]], grew up in the Sandy Hook section of Newtown, Connecticut.\n* [[Jenna von O\u00ff]], actress and singer, attended Newtown High School.\n* [[Thelma Wood]], American sculptor, lived in Sandy Hook in the 1930s.\n* [[John Angel (sculptor)|John Angel]], internationally known sculptor, lived in Sandy Hook 1940 - 1960.\n*[[Elia Kazan]], stage/motion picture director and author, lived in Sandy Hook in the 1960s-2003\n*[[Grace Moore]], American operatic soprano and actress in musical theater and film in the 1930\u2019s, maintained a home in Connecticut. \n*[[Valent\u00edn Parera|Valentin Panera]], Spanish actor, husband of Grace Moore in the 1930\u2019s, maintained a home in Connecticut.\n*[https://www.encyclopedia.com/arts/educational-magazines/howat-john-k-1937-john-keith-howat John K. \u201cJock\u201d] and Anne Hadley Howat, he was a curator at The Metropolitan Museum of Art, American Paintings and Sculpture and then as Chairman of the American Wing. Donators of 68 acres of land on route 34 (109 Berkshire rd), land that had been in the Hadley and Howat families since 1889. The original home there dates back to 1767.\n*[[Arthur Twining Hadley]], lived in Sandy Hook at 109 Berkshire Rd, became the president of Yale University, in 1899. He married Helen Harrison Morris on June 30, 1891, daughter of [[Luzon B. Morris|Luzon Buritt Morris]], who was to become Governor of Connecticut in 1893.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n\n{{wikivoyage|Brookfield (Connecticut)|Brookfield, Connecticut}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Newtown, Connecticut}}\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n\n{{coord|41|25|12|N|73|16|55|W|type:city_region:US-CT_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Newtown, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Villages in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Villages in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1711 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1711]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name=Sandy Hook, Connecticut\n| settlement_type         = Village\n| image_skyline=PostcardSandyHookPostOfficeAndDam1914.jpg\n| image_size=250px\n| image_caption=Sandy Hook post office and dam, from a postcard sent in 1914\n| image_map               =\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             =\n| coordinates             = \n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[U.S. state]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{flag|Connecticut}}\n| subdivision_type2       = [[County (United States)|County]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield]]\n| subdivision_type3        = Metropolitan area\n| subdivision_name3        = [[Greater Bridgeport|Bridgeport-Stamford]]\n| subdivision_type4       = [[Administrative divisions of Connecticut#Town|Town]]\n| subdivision_name4       = [[Newtown, Connecticut|Newtown]]\n| established_title=\n| established_date= 1711\n| founder=\n| seat_type=\n| seat=\n| unit_pref=US\n| population_density_sq_mi=auto\n| population_demonym=\n| population_note=\n| timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Standard Time|EST]]\n| utc_offset               = &minus;5\n| timezone_DST             = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST           = &minus;4\n| postal_code_type=ZIP code\n| postal_code=06482\n| area_code=[[Area codes 203 and 475|203/475]]\n| iso_code=\n}}\n\n'''Sandy Hook''' is a village in the town of [[Newtown, Connecticut]].  Sandy Hook was founded in 1711.\n\nIt borders the [[Botsford, Connecticut|Botsford]] section of town, Newtown borough, and also the towns of [[Monroe, Connecticut|Monroe]], [[Southbury, Connecticut|Southbury]] and [[Oxford, Connecticut|Oxford]] along the [[Housatonic River]]. The village of Sandy Hook includes the communities of Berkshire, Riverside, Walnut Tree Hill, and Zoar, which also extends for a short distance into the Town of Monroe along Old Zoar Road and Bagburn Hill/Jordan Hill Road.\n\n==History==\nWithin a year of the settlement of Newtown, some of its proprietors began moving away from the central village to some of their larger parcels. Several proprietors with land in the same area relocated to these areas together to reduce isolation. Sandy Hook was one of the first of the outlying areas settled. Colonists found the [[Pootatuck River]] at Sandy Hook allowed for the setting up of saw and grist mills. The neighborhood would not grow dramatically until the industrialization of the mid 19th century.<ref>Cruson, Daniel, [http://www.newtownhistory.org/the-settlement.html \"A Brief History of Newtown\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130128000853/http://www.newtownhistory.org/the-settlement.html |date=2013-01-28 }}, Web page at Newtown Historical Society Web site, accessed December 14, 2012.</ref>\n\n===2012 school shooting===\n{{main article|Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting}}\n<!-- \nNOTE: This section is a short summary of the event. The expanded details should be put in the main article at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n-->\n{{As of|2012|12|alt=On December 14, 2012}}, Adam Lanza shot his mother at home, then killed 26 people besides himself at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School]].<ref name=\"ID\">{{cite news|author=Miguel Llanos|title=Authorities ID gunman who killed 27 in elementary school massacre|url=http://usnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/12/14/15911025-authorities-id-gunman-who-killed-27-in-elementary-school-massacre?lite|newspaper=[[NBC News]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=December 14, 2012|date=December 14, 2012}}</ref>  It was the {{As of|2012|12|alt=second-deadliest}} mass shooting in U.S. history at the time, after the 2007 [[Virginia Tech shooting]]s.<ref name=\"BBC News school shooting\">{{cite news|title=28 dead in school shooting|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-20730717||publisher=BBC News|accessdate=December 14, 2012|date=December 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Christoffersen |first=John |url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONNECTICUT_SCHOOL_SHOOTING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2012-12-14-13-27-48 |title=Official: 27 dead in Conn. school shooting |work=ap.org |accessdate=January 15, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121217025156/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_CONNECTICUT_SCHOOL_SHOOTING?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2012-12-14-13-27-48 |archivedate=December 17, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2718-201_162-1950/cbs-news-live-video/ |work=CBS News |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-12-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121214184526/http://www.cbsnews.com/2718-201_162-1950/cbs-news-live-video/ |archive-date=2012-12-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<!-- \nNOTE: This section is a short summary of the event. The expanded details should be put in the main article at [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n-->\n\n[[Image:SandyHook.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sandy Hook in 2007]]\n\n===Landmarks===\n \t\n* [[Nathan B. Lattin Farm]] \u2013 22 Walker Hill Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n \n* [[New York Belting and Packing Co.]] \u2013 45\u201371 and 79\u201389 Glen Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n\n* [[Sanford-Curtis-Thurber House]] \u2013 71 Riverside Road, [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Luther Meade Blackman]], Major during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], accused of forging the [[Bat Creek inscription]], born in Sandy Hook, Newtown, in Fairfield County, Connecticut.\n* James Brunot, promoter of the game [[Scrabble]], resident of Newtown, Connecticut in the 1940s.{{citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n* [[Suzanne Collins]], American television writer and author of ''[[The Underland Chronicles]]'' and ''[[The Hunger Games trilogy|The Hunger Games]]'' trilogy,<ref name=NBC-Connecticut>{{cite news|last=Gendreau|first=LeAnne|title=Anticipated Film Based on Local Author\u2019s Book|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/the-scene/events/Anticipated-Film-Based-on-Local-Authors-Book-142804085.html|accessdate=December 28, 2012|newspaper=NBC|date=March 15, 2012}}</ref> resident of Sandy Hook.\n* [[William Hamilton Gibson]], 19th-century American illustrator, author, and naturalist,<ref>Adams, John Coleman, 'William Hamilton Gibson,' {{cite web|url=http://digital.library.cornell.edu/cgi/t/text/pageviewer-idx?c=newe;cc=newe;rgn=full%20text;idno=newe0021-6;didno=newe0021-6;view=image;seq=00651;node=newe0021-6%3A1|title=New England Magazine|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}, Feb. 1897, p. 643</ref> born in Sandy Hook, Connecticut.\n* [[Charles R. Jackson]], writer and novelist, author of ''[[The Lost Weekend (novel)|The Lost Weekend]]'' lived in Sandy Hook in the 1950s.\n* [[Caitlyn Jenner]] (then Bruce),{{efn|Jenner changed name due to [[gender transition]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author = [[Buzz Bissinger]] |title=Introducing Caitlyn Jenner|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/06/caitlyn-jenner-bruce-cover-annie-leibovitz/|work=Vanity Fair|date=June 1, 2015|accessdate=June 1, 2015}}</ref> }} [[1976 Summer Olympics]] decathlon gold medalist, attended Newtown High School in Newtown, Connecticut.\n* [[Molly Pearson]], 20th-century stage actress, lived in Sandy Hook, Connecticut at the time of her death in 1959.\n* [[Albert Berger Rossdale]], [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from New York, lived in Sandy Hook, Connecticut in the early 1930s.\n* [[James Thurber]], writer, satirist, cartoonist, author of ''[[The Secret Life of Walter Mitty]]'' lived in Sandy Hook in the 1930s.\n* [[Marcus Tracy]], professional soccer player, grew up in Newtown, and attended Newtown High School.\n* [[Mead Treadwell]], 13th Lieutenant Governor of Alaska and former Chair of the [[U.S. Arctic Research Commission]], grew up in the Sandy Hook section of Newtown, Connecticut.\n* [[Jenna von O\u00ff]], actress and singer, attended Newtown High School.\n* [[Thelma Wood]], American sculptor, lived in Sandy Hook in the 1930s.\n* [[John Angel (sculptor)|John Angel]], internationally known sculptor, lived in Sandy Hook 1940 - 1960.\n* Elia Kazan, stage/motion picture director and author, Sandy Hook in the 1960s-2003\n* Grace Moore, American operatic soprano and actress in musical theater and film in the 1930\u2019s\n* Valentin Panera, Spanish actor, husband of Grace Moore in the 1930\u2019s\n* John K. \u201cJock\u201d and Anne Hadley Howat, he was a curator at The Metropolitan Museum of Art, American Paintings and Sculpture and then as Chairman of the American Wing. Donators of 68 acres of land on route 34 (109 Berkshire rd), land that had been in the Hadley and Howat families since 1889. The original home there dates back to 1767.\n* Arthur Twining Hadley, 109 Berkshire rd, became the president of Yale University, in 1899. He married Helen Harrison Morris on June 30, 1891, daughter of Luzon Buritt Morris, who was to become Governor of Connecticut in 1893.\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Connecticut}}\n\n{{wikivoyage|Brookfield (Connecticut)|Brookfield, Connecticut}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Newtown, Connecticut}}\n{{Fairfield County, Connecticut}}\n{{Connecticut}}\n{{New York metropolitan area}}\n\n{{coord|41|25|12|N|73|16|55|W|type:city_region:US-CT_source:GNIS-enwiki|display=title}}\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Newtown, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Villages in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Villages in Fairfield County, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:1711 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1711]]\n", "name_user": "Rfolk7X", "label": "safe", "comment": "I rephrased some of the content to make it flow better. I included hyperlinks and citations that were missing. I made minor grammatical fixes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandy_Hook,_Connecticut"}
